<HEADLINE>Lara set for his return to action</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667777</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Lara is set to make his return to cricket tomorrow for Trinidad and
Tobago in a Red Stripe Cup trial match.
Theo Cuffy, the Trinidad and Tobago manager, said that Lara, who withdrew from
the West Indies party for the current tour of Australia, has accepted the
captaincy of the team for the Cup competition starting next month.
``Brian is set to play on Friday and we are all looking forward to seeing him
back making runs. It will be great to see him out there,'' said Cuffy.
``He has had his rest and he wants to get back to playing cricket. He is
looking relaxed and at ease. This holiday has done him a world of good.''
He also hinted that the record-breaking batsman would play for the West Indies
in the forthcoming World Cup.
``I am sure he would like to captain Trinidad and Tobago to a Red Stripe
victory, but he will most likely be available for only the first two games, as
the West Indies are due to travel to India for the World Cup.''
The holder of world record scores for Test (375) and first-class cricket (501
not out), withdrew from the West Indies squad for Australia after being fined
10% of his fee for breaches of contract during the tour to England this summer.
It was reported that he was in conflict with other members of the party,
including skipper Richie Richardson, and threatened to quit the tour and even
retire from cricket.
WEST INDIES NEWS
</TEXT>
