<HEADLINE>A hot political year lies ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667778</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN TRUTH, as we hurtle towards the new twelve-month, there are only two
political questions worth the asking. Will Mr John Major avoid being booted out
in 1996? Will Mr Tony Blair avoid being found out?
I have long held to the view, as Ms Ruth Wishart of these pages but not of my
party will give witness M'Lud, that Mr Major will lead the Tories into the next
election. Indeed I offered, on air, to wager with the good lady that this would
be the ultimate turn of events, a bet she, probably wisely, turned down. But
that does not completely answer the first question.
The Grim Reaper might intervene, invite a few Conservative servants to join him
on the first tee of the Heavenly golf course, like tomorrow. Mr Major's
anorexic Commons majority could wither on the vine, an election be forced, a
furniture van called. Yet I still do not think it will end that way.
Those men of natural suspicion, and maybe they have much to be suspicious
about, the Ulster Unionists, are in no great hurry to install the socialists,
or what passes for them nowadays, to rule over our land. Mr Blair's charm is
not sufficient for them - it will never be enough to becalm the great wind of
Paisley.
So the Unionists will threaten, cajole, procrastinate but not, I guess, pull
the plug.
The PM, however, faces the enemy within, and the foe faces several ways at
once. On Europe he is at risk from both the sceptics and the phobes but most of
all from the 50 or so of his MPs who are opting for early retirement. ``You can
take your Whip and stick it where . . .''
Come May, say, and the party is still looking like being relegated from the
Premier League opinion polls, what then? Will the pin-striped suited ones -
they were never grey - come a-calling? It could happen, though it is not my
belief that it will.
Whatever might be said of John Major he can hardly be called a quitter.
Coruscated by critics from right and left, lampooned on television, snobbily
sneered at by magazines who should know better, the PM contrives to survive and
to maintain his good humour. I think he will be on the starting line; but you
can still have the bet, Ruth.
No-one doubts, unless he flings himself under that murderous old bus, that Mr
Blair will lead Labour. The question is - to where? To Government, you foolish
boy. Yes, I know that is the plan, and one would have to say it appears to be
proceeding smoothly, but I sense the big examinations are just around the
corner.
Can we ask about Peter Mandelson, Tony? This good pal of yours, we learn -
lovely to have Labour leak for a change - wrote a 22-page outline for a book
which suggested he believed, post-devolution, that we should shed 15 of our
Scottish MPs at Westminster.
I think he is absolutely right, myself, and so do the Liberal Democrats, but
that is hardly the point. It's not what we are being told by you, is it? It's
not party policy.
Will Peter have to be publicly humiliated, like Clare Short when she said we
might examine whether certain drugs could be de-criminalised? Or is he echoing
his master's voice? What about his notion of abolishing local education
authorities - that will go down a treat with the Labour councillors - or
forming coalitions with the Lib-Dems? This is not some doe-eyed kid from the
back benches, this is your doctor of spin, your guru.
Now we will be told that this was only a rough draft of what Peter intended to
write, that the published book will be different - I'm certain it will - and
that the Tories are troublemaking again. Stand by for a lot more of that. And
maybe even from your own side.
Like Mr John McWilliam, MP for Blaydon. I know him - he used to be the City
Treasurer in Edinburgh - and he is a perfectly moderate bloke. Yet John is
worried, as are a lot of northern English MPs, that their regions might be
disadvantaged if a Scottish Parliament is set up.
He is threatening to table amendments to any devolution Bill if assurances are
not received. Shades of a certain Mr Cunningham (Lab) in days gone by.
You see, Tony, there are still a lot of Scots, and not just Nats, who wonder
about your commitment to the Parliament. They see how you have wriggled on
English regional assemblies, have agreed to make the Welsh Parliament little
more than a hot-air stall, and have run away from the implications of a Tartan
Tax. ``We won't necessarily raise the tax.'' And the band played.
You cannot blame them for wondering what else is being hidden. You will not
stop them asking such questions in the next year.
Paul Johnson is another pal of yours, or so he claims. You know the chap - was
once a red-hot socialist, then worshipped Mrs Thatcher, is now a declared
supporter of you. He says he hopes and believes that you will be our first
Catholic Prime Minister.
That would make not one whit of difference to the manner in which I would judge
Mr Blair. Indeed, if the Prince of Wales wanted to marry someone of the
Catholic faith after his divorce, I should fight for his right to do so.
But I can just hear the spin doctors going into over-rev. ``You can't do it,
Tony, even if you wanted to, it would offend too many voters.'' I do not think
we will hear confirmation of any change of church from Mr Blair.
Which, if that is what he would like to do, is rather sad.
We are in for a hot political year, mes amis; you will understand if I take a
little break in King Carlos's land before we gear up for it together.
</TEXT>
