<HEADLINE>Call for inquiry into arms dumping</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667779</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CLYDE town has stepped into the row over dangers posed by munitions dumped in
a trench off the south-west coast.
Dumbarton is to protest to the European Commissioner for the Environment about
the Beaufort's Dyke disposal site in the North Channel.
The council is to demand the introduction of more comprehensive monitoring
programmes in the area by the Ministry of Defence.
Dumbarton district's planning convener, Mr Jack Duffy, said the council wished
to establish the dump's impact on the environment.
``It is of the utmost importance to determine the extent and nature of the
environmental problems and also of the threat posed to the fishing and tourism
industries by such disposal sites,'' Mr Duffy said.
``In the light of the full facts, we must consider any appropriate action.''
The council's action follows a protest by Lancashire County Council about
dangerous phosphorous bombs being washed up on beaches along the coast there.
Mr Gordon Johnson, Lancashire's chief executive, said: ``Of particular concern
to Lancashire County Council is the dumping site of Beaufort's Dyke in the
North Channel and the surrounding area, and exercises such as Operation
Sandcastle, whereby chemical weapons were shipped from locations on the
north-west coast for disposal in deep Atlantic waters.
``The council is also concerned about numerous accounts which cast doubt on
whether some of these operations were carried out in the correct manner, and
whether materials were actually disposed of in the authorised sites.''
Some observers believe the situation only came to light because British Gas
disturbed the munitions while laying a pipeline from Scotland to Ireland.
</TEXT>
