<TEXT>
Beating victim
might be Scot
A MAN found dead in the yard of a public house in Yorkshire is believed to be
from Scotland, murder hunt police said yesterday.
The body was found on Boxing Day at the Sun Inn, Kirkgate, Shipley, with
injuries to the head. Police believe the man was beaten to death. He was in his
60s, 5ft 6in tall, about 10st, and had a bushy beard and ginger hair. He was
drinking in the pub on Christmas Eve.
Murder charges
CINEMA owner Peter Moore, 49, was yesterday remanded in custody charged with
murdering three men by Colwyn Bay magistrates. He is charged with the murders
of Mr Tony Davies, 40, on Pensaern Beach, Abergele on December 18; Mr Keith
Randells, 49, at a building site at Mona, Angelsey, between November 28 and
December 1; and an unidentified man in Denbigh, Clywd, in September.
McCarthy on air
JOURNALIST and former Beirut hostage John McCarthy will present the New Year's
Day edition of Outlook, the World Service magazine programme on BBC radio,
which he used to listened to with fellow captives Brian Keenan and Terry Waite.
Team spirit
LEADING sportsmen and sportswomen are being recruited by the GMB union. So far
Rugby League players have been approached to sign up.
Partick arrest
A MAN of 36 is in police custody after the death of James Brady, 40, in a house
in North Gardner Street, Partick, Glasgow, on Tuesday night. He is expected to
appear at Glasgow Sheriff Court today. Mr Brady was a resident of the Davenport
Nursing Home in Burnbank Terrace, Glasgow.
Housing trap
FREDERICK and Rosemary West's former neighbours on Cromwell Street, Gloucester,
are struggling to sell their houses. One property was recently on sale for half
of its #60,000 market value and still remains unsold, local estate agent Ted
Wynn said yesterday.
Ski death
A MAN collapsed and died on Boxing Day while skiing at the Glenshee Ski Centre.
Mr Ian Cameron, 51, of Midlothian, was believed to have been with his son on
the Sunnyside piste. A post-mortem is being carried out.
Beef slump
MORE than one million British households refused to buy beef for Christmas
because of fears about mad cow disease, market research firm Nielsen revealed
yesterday. There has been a steady decline in beef buying since the beginning
of last month.
Benefits call
YOUNG Scottish Nationalists have raised an 800 signature petition in
Dunbartonshire calling for the restoration of benefits for 16 to 17-year-olds.
Madam chair
THE leader of the new West Dunbartonshire Council, Mary Campbell, has asked for
castors to be put on chairs in the Dumbarton chambers because they are too
cumbersome for members to move.
Man missing
POLICE in Edinburgh are trying to trace 55-year-old John Lindsay who has been
missing since Christmas Eve. Mr Lindsay was last seen at a hostel in the
Grassmarket on Sunday. He is 5ft 1in, of slim build with a sallow complexion
and dark greying hair balding on top.
</TEXT>
