<HEADLINE>McKenna tops the open bill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667781</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SQUASH
SCOTTISH junior champion Lisa McKenna, last year's beaten finalist, is the only
home top seed in the Bank of Scotland Scottish Junior Open championships which
start today in Edinburgh.
With a record entry of almost 200, including players from every continent, the
championships have been split into two venues this year - Heriot-Watt
University and Colinton Castle - and, after a season troubled by injury McKenna
will have to recapture her best form to justify her favourite's billing.
Belgium's Kim Hanns is the No.2 seed. She lost to McKenna in last year's
semi-finals but is currently the top-ranked junior on the European circuit.
``It's been a very frustrating time for me over the last few months,'' said
McKenna, a full-timer who will be 18 on New Year's Day. ``But, hopefully, my
feet, thumb, and finger problems are behind me and this championship will mark
the start of the comeback.''
Sweden's No.1, Johan Jungling, is top seed in the boys' under-19 championship,
with Grant Finlay, the leading South African junior, at No.2.
Scottish junior champion Colin Hamilton cannot get higher than the 5/8 list of
seeds, while Neil Dickson is in the 9/16 group.
In the younger sections, Elgin's Simon Hall and Steven Halliday, from Eyemouth,
are both seeded 5/8 in the under-16 championships, while Bridge of Allan's
Peter Campbell, a shock finalist in this season's British event, and Waverley's
Lizzie Leitch should figure in the later stages of the under-14 age group.
</TEXT>
