<HEADLINE>Butterfly McQueen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667783</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Butterfly McQueen, actress, born January 8, 1911, Tampa, Florida, died December
22, 1995, Augusta, Georgia
THE black Hollywood actress Butterfly McQueen, who has died at the age of 84,
is essentially remembered for just one film performance, her first. She made
her screen debut as Prissy, the stereo-typical Southern slave servant who
tended to Olivia de Havilland in David O Selznick's 1939 epic, Gone With The
Wind.
It was, for its day, a controversial role and one which, in today's politically
correct times, would never be permitted. In racial terms, Prissy was a
caricature - and a comic one at that. Nevertheless, the exquisitely-named
Butterfly played the part with memorable aplomb and absurdity.
Ms McQueen, the last living connection with the multi-Oscar winning Civil War
soap opera, was born in Tampa, Florida, the daughter of a dock worker father
and domestic servant mother. Before becoming an actress, she worked in a
variety of jobs including factory work and a children's nurse.
In the mid-30s she travelled to New York to join Vanezuela Jones's Negro Youth
Project in Harlem where she trained as a dancer. After changing her Christian
name from Thelma to Butterfly, she sought work on stage and screen.
After her success in Gone With The Wind, she had a minor role in George Cukor's
comedy, The Women, the same year and later in Michael Curtiz's 1945 film noir,
Mildred Pierce.
By the late forties, however, she was becoming uncomfortable with playing the
role of black ``handkerchief head'' all the time and, after appearing as
Lillian Gish's servant in Selznick's 1946 Western, Duel in the Sun, she
deserted Hollywood - and the acting profession.
She took many jobs over the years including a sales assistant in the toy
department at Macy's in New York, a taxi-cab dispatcher in the Bronx, and
(ironically) the maid to a white couple in Atlanta. In the 1970s, as the civil
rights movement gained momentum, Ms McQueen concentrated on helping with social
work projects in Harlem and, at the age of 64, she gained a degree from the
City College in New York.
Occasionally, she would return to acting. She received an Emmy Award in 1965
for a role in the television film, The Seven Wishes Of A Rich Kid, and in 1986
she had a small role in the Australian director Peter Weir's film, The Mosquito
Coast.
In 1989, as the movie industry marked the 50th anniversary of Gone With The
Wind, the elderly actress was in tremendous demand worldwide. She made a
memorable appearance during the Edinburgh Film Festival that year and endeared
herself to millions with several appearances on television chat shows.
ALLAN LAING
</TEXT>
