<HEADLINE>Stewart flops again but Gallian holds firm Uphill fight as England rue dropped catches</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667784</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND denied teenager Paul Adams instant success at St George's Park, but
face an uphill battle after losing a lot of ground on day two of the fourth
Test in Port Elizabeth.
First they allowed South Africa to total 428 all out, spilling six catches
along the way. Then opener Alec Stewart fell for only four during the second
over after edging an ambitious back-foot forcing shot against fast bowler Shaun
Pollock.
Stewart has now gone 16 Test innings since his last half-century as an opener
and yesterday's dismissal put new recruit Jason Gallian under real pressure,
which increased once Adams was introduced after only half-an-hour.
The debut-making, 18-year-old wrist spinner had a raucous lbw appeal against
Gallian turned down when his third delivery turned past a forward defensive
stroke.
But England's new No.3 and Lancashire team-mate Mike Atherton kept Adams at
bay, taking 16 runs off his seven overs as the tourists reached 40 for one by
close.
Atherton's team denied Daryll Cullinan (91) and Dave Richardson (84) centuries
yesterday, but, apart from that, there was little cause for satisfaction, with
Mark Ilott's thigh strain, which forced the Essex paceman off the field in
mid-afternoon, adding to a worrying picture.
South Africa's innings finally came to a close 50 minutes into the evening
session, when last-man Adams was run out by Gallian's throw from the deep. The
teenager failed to get off the mark after facing only two deliveries, but,
thanks to his team-mates, the left-armer has plenty of runs to bowl at today.
England did their prospects no good at all by failing to take most of the
chances that came their way.
Dominic Cork prompted thoughts of a successful day for the tourists when he
dismissed former Derbyshire team-mate Cullinan after South Africa had added
only 21 runs to their overnight total of 230 for four.
Called up for the seventh over of the morning, Cork's first ball was short and
wide outside off stump, but Cullinan's attempted cut gave Jack Russell a low
catch in front of first slip.
England's attack showed an alarming lack of accuracy, which allowed Brian
McMillan and Richardson to add 75 runs for the sixth wicket.
All five bowlers - Peter Martin, Ilott, Cork, Richard Illingworth, and Gallian
- tried by Atherton during the morning session failed to apply the basic
principles of line and length. Twenty-seven overs before lunch yielded eleven
4s, as well as the 6 McMillan pulled off an Illingworth full toss.
All-rounder McMillan reached 49 only to miss out on a mini-milestone by
under-edging a cut against spinner Illingworth during the fifth over after
lunch.
At 326 for six, England could still have kept the home total to reasonable
proportions, but then came Richardson's stand of 53 with Shaun Pollock, who
survived difficult chances to Atherton at short mid-wicket and Illingworth off
the left-armer's own bowling, and then was given the benefit of the doubt
following a run-out appeal.
Cork ended Pollock's contribution at 23 by winning an lbw verdict and, after
tea, Richardson's near four-hour innings - containing 11 boundaries - was
brought to a close by Illingworth. A ball pitching outside leg stump turned
quite sharply, brushed bat, glove, and pad, and finally ended in Russell's
gloves as the keeper scampered from behind the stumps.
By then, South Africa were past 400 but more catches were about to go down,
even if they cost very little. Three chances in four balls were dropped, with
Craig Matthews being reprieved by Graham Thorpe at extra cover, before Gallian
and Illingworth let Allan Donald escape - all during an over from Illingworth.
q.DOMINIC Cork has been warned to keep his celebrations on ``an even keel'' by
match referee Clive Lloyd.
The England all-rounder appeared to shout something after dismissing South
African batsman Jonty Rhodes on the opening day and former West Indies captain
Lloyd asked to look at a recording of the incident and decided no official
action was necessary.
``The umpires had no complaint and I'm satisfied nothing was said to the
batsman,'' commented the referee. ``But I've had a friendly word with Cork and
told him of the need to keep his celebrations on an even keel in case something
is misconstrued.''
