<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown predicted yesterday that the Prime
Minister would be forced to go to the polls next year because his beleaguered
Government could not last another 12 months.
``In my bones, I do not think the Government is going to get through the next
year,'' Mr Ashdown said.
Mr Major faces the prospect of a Commons majority of three in the new year
following the death of the South-east Staffordshire MP, Sir David Lightbown,
and potentially disastrous local government elections in May.
He must call a General Election by May 1997, but his overall majority could be
demolished by two further by-election losses, prompting speculation that
Ministers are planning an early election to avoid running the risks of
staggering into the final year as some sort of lame-duck government.
In what may be seen as a high-risk strategy, Mr Ashdown said the Liberal
Democrats would contest the election on a platform which included a clear
commitment to European integration and a single currency.
``I want people out there to know that on this issue the Liberal Democrats can
be relied upon to be a rock in favour of the process of European integration,''
he told ITN.
He said: ``If the Prime Minister leads a divided party, with lack of leadership
and without a capacity to stake out a clear position, I am afraid to say that
the same precisely applies to the Labour Party.''
</TEXT>
