<HEADLINE>Festival's bank  account arrested</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667790</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE bank account of the troubled Burns International Festival company has been
arrested as part of a continuing legal battle with a firm which carried out
work for next year's festival.
Sheriff officers yesterday served an order on the Bank of Scotland in High
Street, Ayr, which effectively freezes #20,000 in the account until a wrangle
over outstanding professional fees is resolved.
A writ for non-payment of professional fees is also being served on the
festival company.
The Greenock-based Affinity Partnership was engaged almost a year ago to seek
sponsorship for the 1996 festival, which is being staged to commemorate the
bicentenary of the death of Robert Burns.
After many months of disagreement between the festival and Affinity over the
work which was being carried out, there was a parting of the ways in August.
Mr George Mills of the Affinity Partnership said: ``We regret that things have
come to this but we have contracts which state that we are due certain
professional fees. Quite frankly we are fed up waiting for the festival, which
seems to be stumbling from crisis to crisis, to pay up.
``We hope that the action we are taking will be brought to a speedy and
satisfactory conclusion by our legal advisers.''
By coincidence the fees which are in dispute relate to early work carried out
on the possibility of a tie-up between the festival and the Bank of Scotland on
a Burns bicentenary Visa card.
A bank spokeswoman said: ``An announcement on the card is likely to be made in
the middle of January. I would stress that negotiations relating to the card
took place between the festival and a company acting on our behalf in Reading.
``At no time were we involved in negotiations with the Affinity Partnership
over the credit card plan.''
Mr Mills claims that some sponsorship had been secured before their contract
was abruptly ended and that further fees could be sought from the festival
company in the coming weeks. It is understood that festival director, Mr John
Struthers, disputes the level of assistance given by Affinity
Continued on Page 4
Continued from page 1
and was dissatisfied with their work.
He was unavailable for comment yesterday but a spokesman for the festival
company said: ``We are somewhat surprised to hear this news as we have been in
discussion with our legal advisers with a view to seeking recompense from the
Affinity Partnership over what we believe may amount to a breach of contract.''
The 1996 festival has been beset by problems in recent months including the
news that neither comedian Billy Connolly nor rock group Runrig were aware that
they were taking part in the programme of events, despite Mr Struthers
announcing it to the media.
In addition, hints were dropped that opera singer Dame Kiri Te Kanawa would be
singing at a special open air concert at Rugby Park, Kilmarnock, in the summer.
Her personal manager told The Herald that only one tentative approach had been
made to him which was never followed up.
Local organisations have complained at the lack of consultation or involvement,
and Dumfries and Galloway Regional Council have set up what amounts to an
emergency contingency fund for the year to ensure some events take place in the
region.
It is understood substantial changes in the running of the festival, including
a revamped committee and streamlined organisation, will be announced within two
weeks and that a major brewer is to unveil a sponsorship package.
</TEXT>
