<HEADLINE>Outlook bleak for fixture officials</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MacLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667791</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHINTY
PLAYERS throughout Scotland face a bleak start to 1996, with the first day's
play after the winter closedown, due on January 6, already in jeopardy.
Many pitches across the country are under up to a foot of snow, and with the
hard frost which has penetrated the ground making flooding the first serious
problem to be faced, it looks as if the fixtures card will be placed under
immediate pressure.
Camanachd Association officials had been pleased with progress to date, with
only four matches lost in the national premier league programme up until the
last day's play.
The snow came almost immediately after that, however, and fixtures officials
can now look forward to the new year with more than one reason for a headache.
Several traditional new year matches, as well as the central district trial
match which was scheduled for Saturday at Drumnadrochit, are already off.
The pitch at Drumnadrochit is covered by almost a foot of snow and one other
likely casualty is the new year game between Lovat and Beauly.
That is due to be played at Kiltarlity on January 2, but there is little
prospect of play.
More eager to play perhaps are the masons of Lodges 43 and 1200 in Lochaber,
who have a score to settle after last year's 2-2 draw which ended in
hand-shakes all round.
They are due to meet for a rematch at the Fort William swimming pool park on
January 2, at 1pm and are believed to be willing to play whatever the
conditions.
Also due to play at new near are the villagers of Heaste, who have revived the
traditional seasonal game in Skye in recent years.
Road conditions on the island are bad, however, and the revelry may be limited
to a few hardy locals who will maintain the tradition, if possible.
The cold weather, with temperatures plunging to minus 20 in some places, has
also hit the Fort William club off the field.
Leaking water in the clubhouse at An Aird has caused thousands of pounds worth
of damage, although this hasn't been allowed to interfere with the Christmas
parties and other occasions planned at the venue.
More likely to succeed, however, is North shinty development officer Niall
MacLennan, of Inverness, who has announced plans for an indoor participation
course early in the new year.
The course, which will offer young children the chance to improve their skills
through ``First Shinty'', the modified indoor version of the game, will run for
12 weeks from January 12 to March 29.
Sessions cost 70p each, and application forms can be obtained from the venue,
the Inverness Sports Centre at the Bught Park.
Camanachd Association administrator Alister MacIntyre has confirmed that from
the new year, weather permitting, the number of matches scheduled for play on
any weekend will be limited to the number of officials available, in a bid to
ease the burden on club officials, who may be organising games for which there
are no referees available.
</TEXT>
