<HEADLINE>New flood warning for battered South African province</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN SECCOMBE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667792</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Durban
CIVIL defence authorities issued a new flood warning today as weary police and
rescuers warned the death toll could top 300 in the South African Zulu
homeland's     double Christmas tragedy of flooding and violence.
Heavy rain and hail fell again today and the Pietermaritzburg local authority
warned residents of the ravaged Edendale valley at nightfall to be ready to
flee at short notice if the swollen Umsunduzi River burst its banks for a
second time.
Civil defence officials said the Unsunduzi was in spate and the Henley dam near
Pietermaritzburg was overflowing, threateneing a new flood.
Families, rescuers and police waded through fields of mud in search of 62
people missing since a Christmas Day flood known to have killed 124 people in
the valley west of the Indian Ocean port of Durban.
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, standing in for President Nelson Mandela who is
on holiday, visited the region and declared it a national disaster area.
``It is disastrous. If you look at it all it is unbelievable. I think the most
important thing now is the upkeep of the survivors and the collection of bodies
for burial,'' provincial premier Frank Mdlalose told Reuters.
Heavy rain fell as Mbeki toured the area. An official rushed away saying he had
heard that the Slangspruit River had burst its banks a second time and he had
to check it out.
South of Durban, at Port Shepstone, police said at least 135 people had died in
political and criminal violence since last Friday and it was possible that not
all the victims had been found.
The twin Christmas tragedies seemed likely to have claimed at least 300 lives
with further rains possible and politically driven violence still unchecked.
Police Commissioner George Fivaz said in a statement today he had sent police
reinforcements and independent investigators to the Port Shepstone area, where
at least 19 people were massacred on Christmas Day.
Police said more than 600 Zulus armed with spears, axes and guns swept through
rural villages near Port Shepstone, burning, killing and looting in what
appeared to be politically-motivated attacks.
Survivors told reporters that as they fled from an ``Impi'' - a Zulu column -
advancing towards their village, they ran straight into another marching
towards them from the opposite direction in a traditional Zulu battle tactic.
At least 19 people died in the attacks on homes of families of supporters of
Mandela's ruling African National Congress. Two of the 19 bodies were found
this morning.
Political analysts and human rights monitors said tribal chiefs in the province
usually waited to settle old scores during the festive season when Zulu men
working in other parts of the country traditionally returned home for
Christmas.
The ANC's KwaZulu-Natal provincial spokesman Dumisani Makhaye yesterday blamed
Zulu chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi's Inkatha Freedom Party for the
massacre.
But an Inkatha spokesman, Senator Phillip Powell, denied the allegation, saying
Inkatha members had been ``subjected to a wave of killing in the past three
months''.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
