<HEADLINE>Oxygen back-up flown to villager</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667793</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GENERATOR was yesterday flown to a remote Lewis village, without electricity
since Saturday, to aid a man with breathing difficulties.
It was needed to power two pieces of electronic equipment used to treat Mr
Harley Gillies, 59, in Breanish.
The coastguard helicopter, based at Stornoway, with two Hydro-Electric
engineers on board, transported the generator.
The machine, loaned by the islands council, was lowered to waiting neighbours
of Mr Gillies.
After a spell of treatment on his oxygen enriching machine, Mr Gillies, who is
retired, said: ``I feel very much better already.
``I can't thank the coastguards, Hydro-Electric, and the council enough for
what they have done for me.''
The generator will also power another machine which helps Mr Gillies breathe
while he is asleep.
A coastguard spokesman said it was not a life-threatening situation, but was a
job well done.
</TEXT>
