<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>no headline present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Rusell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667794</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS they left what was clearly not the first pub, a man said to his friend:
``Will we go to the second pub first or the first pub second?'' Given the way
it is becoming difficult to tell one shopping street from another as the chain
stores take over, it was reassuring to realise that people are still different.
When you overhear a conversation like that there is only one country, one city,
that you can be in.
It's always refreshing to return to Glasgow. Mind you, when the taxi driver
asked to take one to Babbity Bowster's heads off for somewhere called Chappit
Munchkins, or something like that, you begin to wonder how refreshed you want
to be. It was when we drove up a flyover and the university loomed on the
horizon that I realised something had gone wrong since the journey had started
at Central Station. He was contrite, but unabashed. ``The first mistake
today,'' he said. ``I never make more than one.''
To be fair he had switched off the meter and when the magical mystery tour
ended he only charged the proper fare.
But I am whingeing. However, as I said, it's refreshing to be back in Scotland.
Had the Von Trapp family been Scottish Julie Andrews would have ended up
singing The Hills are Alive to the Sound of Whingeing. The best bit of that I
heard all week was the man in Shetland on the radio who, after castigating the
electricity people for failing to exploit a three-hour weather window,
complained that it meant the people there had missed out on Christmas Eve
television. No mention of freezing to death, or not having electric light. Just
missing television, something that most people over Christmas would have
considered a blessing.
Then there was the story in The Herald about the STUC asking Michael Forsyth to
do more to support the Scottish film industry. There is nothing wrong with
that, but what they were asking was for him to get the Heritage Secretary,
Virginia Bottomley, to think again about the Government's decision to withdraw
from the Euroimages scheme. The withdrawal was announced in the Budget and
under the scheme which we joined in 1993 some 56 films have benefited.
NATURALLY the new approachable Mr Forsyth is giving the request full
consideration. I hope that includes taking a look at some of those 56 films.
Any of this year's Europuddings, above all Innocent Lies and All Men are Mortal
would repay a look.
At the Franco-British Film Festival in Dinard I met a very high-powered French
lady lawyer who was something influential in the European Script Fund, a source
of EU lolly for co-productions. I had some difficulty in explaining the concept
of a turkey to her, but when she eventually grasped it she was not amused. But
what can one make of a committee doling out our money to film-makers which is
not interested in the script but only the business plan. Making films is a
business, but without a script there is no business.
Allan Shiach was right in his Herald article yesterday when he urged the
Government to come up with a coherent strategy for the film industry, something
it has never had and something even the blandishments of Lord Attenborough, who
daringly called her darling, failed to make Mrs Thatcher bring about. Part of
the problem, and this does not apply to Mr Shiach, is that the people Ministers
turn to for advice are the very people who take the Euro cash and make those
appalling Europudding films nobody goes to see. If they did, there would be an
outcry at the way the money was being wasted.
Ken Loach's Land and Freedom was a rare exception to the rule when it comes to
co-productions. Mr Shiach blames its lack of success here on its distributors.
Mr Loach and his producer Rebecca O'Brien have argued their case forcefully
enough, but the fact is that his previous film, Ladybird Ladybird, in spite of
glowing reviews, failed to attract an audience. In Europe they may go to see a
film on the strength of the director's name, but here people want film stars,
and Mr Loach is a prophet with honour but not much profit in his own country.
I don't have the answers, although Mr Shiach has suggested some, but neither do
the Europudding-makers who tend to end up on the advisory committees Ministers
insist on setting up. I suspect that had Land and Freedom starred Chris
O'Donnell and Winona Ryder it might well have been distributed rather more
widely than it was, but then it would not have been a Ken Loach film.
Anyway, that's the end of my whinge. It really is refreshing to come back home.
</TEXT>
