<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Another victim of the gunmen in Belfast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667795</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN was shot dead in front of his family in an attack on his house in west
Belfast last night.
Police said the 30-year-old man died when what appeared to be a shotgun was
fired through the window of the house in the republican Norglen Parade area.
The man's wife and children were in the house. They escaped without injury.
The murder follows two in the week before Christmas and another earlier in the
month.
The earlier murders were claimed by a previously unheard of group, Direct
Action Against Drugs, who warned more people were to be targeted.
The group is believed in security and political circles to be a cover name for
the IRA, being used to hold on to its control of republican areas.
The recent spate of murders have prompted calls from Unionists for the
Government to accept that the IRA ceasefire was at an end.
West Belfast MP, Dr Joe Hendron, SDLP, condemned the killing as ``a foul
murder''.
Earlier Sinn Fein warned that the Northern Ireland peace process was on the
verge of collapse and claimed the Government was anxious to return to war.
Peace could still be grasped but the hold on it was rapidly loosening, warned
party chairman Mitchel McLaughlin.
In one of the gloomiest assessments yet of the state of the peace process after
16 months of IRA ceasefire, he accused Britain of spoiling for a fight and not
being serious about a lasting peace.
Addressing a rally in the County Fermanagh border town of Rosea, Mr McLaughlin
said: ``It is becoming daily more apparent that the British Government has no
intention whatsoever of advancing, or, indeed, of maintaining the peace process
in Ireland.''
He accused some elements within the Government of being worried about their
slender parliamentary majority, preferring to cosset the Unionists rather than
address the issues necessary for lasting peace.
``Other members within the British Cabinet are undoubtedly seeking to force a
rerun of the war on terms which they imagine are much more favourable to their
side.
``We are, all of us, standing on the verge of a disaster created by another
lethal British miscalculation.''
He warned: ``The IRA has not surrendered. The conditions for peace are still
present, but so are the conditions for renewed war.''
The onus was on the Prime Minister, he said.
``Peace is still available and peace is still possible. Even at this late hour
John Major has the power to rescue both our peoples from looming disaster. A
short statement of serious intent, a simple phone-call, can pull us all back
from the brink.''
But he warned: ``The British Government, or for that matter any British
Government to come, will find that the nationalists of Ireland are not in the
business of surrender''.
What they wanted was the release of prisoners from British jails, the removal
of British injustice and inequality and the search for an agreement among all
the people of Ireland ``on how we govern ourselves''.
Matters are likely to come to a head next month when the international
commission produces its report on how to resolve the stalemate over the
decommissioning of terrorist weapons. Britain insists the IRA must start
getting rid of its weapons before Sinn Fein can enter the negotiations on
Ulster's future. The IRA refuses, insisting that could come about only as part
of a final agreed settlement.
