<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667797</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MP makes call
for beds inquiry
AN alleged shortage of intensive-care hospital beds throughout Tayside has led
to a call by the East Angus MP, Mr Andrew Welsh, for an urgent governmental
inquiry.
Scottish Health Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton recently denied there was
a problem, but a prominent surgeon is said to possess clinical evidence that
patients have suffered through the postponement of surgery. In demanding an
inquiry, Mr Welsh said the Government was putting people's lives at risk.
Men arrested
TWO men in their late teens and early 20s have been arrested in connection with
the Boxing Day mugging of an 83-year-old widow. Mrs Evelyn Stanford remains in
a critical condition at Wolverhampton's Royal Hospital.
Grand occasion
THE Princess Royal will be at Ayr Racecourse in April to open a #1.65m
extension to the Members Grandstand. The ceremony will take place during the
Scottish Grand National.
Generous offer
A CLYDEBANK councillor is urging community groups to apply for a slice of the
council's #600,000 general services surplus before it merges with Dumbarton in
the spring. But Labour councillors have toned down the offer by SNP Councillor
Jim McElhill, saying the money is not exactly surplus and has to last until
March 31.
Rape charge
A PLUMBER charged with raping a sex-change woman was yesterday remanded in
custody until January 3. John Mathews, 46, of Ufton Nervet, Berkshire, is
alleged to have raped the woman near Pangbourne, Berkshire, on Christmas Day.
Cliff search
SENIOR pupil Andrew Smith, 18, missing for more than two weeks, had been the
victim of classroom bullying, his father said yesterday. Police launched a
helicopter search yesterday after his bicycle and back-pack were found hidden
on a cliff-top at Swanage, Dorset.
Engineering rises
PAY settlements in Scotland's engineering industry averaged out at 3.5% for the
12 months to December, according to the employer's support organisation,
Scottish Engineering.
Parking fears
THREE in five Scottish women are afraid to park in multi-storeys, a survey to
find Britain's safest car park has found. It revealed that 10% of women were
concerned when parking in the street, 50% feared being stranded by a car
breakdown, and 20% wanted female-only parking.
</TEXT>
