<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RAC warning after jump-leads blind driver</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667798</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DRIVERS using jump-leads to start their cars have been warned to follow the
makers' guidelines with extra care by the RAC, after an accident left a
motorist blind yesterday.
The motorist was leaning over his battery holding jump leads when a spark
caused an explosion.
The RAC warned that during jump-lead starting, or battery recharging, explosive
gases can be given off. Yet 20% of motorists are unaware of the danger.
``Jump starting a car is not as simple as it used to be. Engine management
systems have become increasingly complicated,'' said RAC head of campaigns
Edmund King.
``By following manufacturer guidelines and the RAC's basic advice, motorists
can avoid thousands of pounds worth of damage or the risk of serious personal
injury.''
The RAC said cold snaps put a heavy drain on car batteries which operate best
at temperatures of 75F. In sub-zero temperatures, batteries work at only 80-85%
of capacity.
The warning is part of the RAC's national battery awareness campaign. It began
last month with an exercise in which more than 2000 discarded and potentially
dangerous batteries were collected.
The RAC last night also issued tips for motorists forced to travel during the
present record freeze-up.
Although they were advised not to venture out unless absolutely necessary, the
RAC said that a series of sensible precautions would lessen the hazards of
driving in ice and snow.
Many of the checks should be carried out the previous evening. They can be
doubly difficult in the dark, early hours of the morning.
q Make sure that you have the correct amount of anti-freeze in your cooling
system. A frozen engine can cause hundreds of pounds worth of damage. Always
check coolant when the engine is cold.
q Check the condition of all hoses. If they feel brittle or spongy, have them
replaced.
q Your battery must be in top condition. Even a reasonable battery can give up
when having to start a very cold engine.
q Fill the screen washer bottle using an anti-freezing agent.
q Tyres, including the spare, must be at their correct pressure. Deflating
them does not aid traction in snow. If tread depth is in any doubt, have the
tyres changed.
q Cover the windscreen with a bin liner or sheets of newspaper to stop the
worst of the frost overnight.
q Condensation inside the car can cause misting up and even icing inside. Keep
a chamois leather handy as well as a plastic scraper, both inside and out of
the car.
q Check all lights, replacing bulbs where necessary. Clean your number plates
and replace windscreen wiper blades if they have been in use for more than a
year.
q Make certain you have enough fuel to reach your destination and for the
return journey. Fewer filling stations are open over the holiday period.
q Keep warm clothing in your car - as well as a shovel, a tow rope, and some
old carpet - in case you become stranded.
q Drive slowly if conditions are at all suspect. Braking distances multiply on
wet or snowy roads. Watch out for black ice, usually impossible to detect until
it is too late.
q Use dipped headlights if visibility is at all impaired.
q If climbing a hill in the snow, use as high a gear as is practicable. In too
low a gear, the wheels will spin out of control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Twins' mischief-making means double trouble Chalk and cheese men of Campbells' kingdom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667799</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRIVIA quiz experts take note. Who in Scottish football are identical, yet by
their own admission, are chalk and cheese when it comes to the national game?
Who have played for, and now have management posts with, the same club?
We're not finished yet, by a long way. Their football careers have followed -
and it is hardly surprising - a parallel course. But there is the difference
that one of them battered in the goals, the other either created or stopped
them.
Off the field, one has his own business specialising in ``human resources.''
The other also has his own business - the Silver Tassie at Lochgelly - where
human resource or resourcefulness is put severely to the test, especially when
a good lady of one of the public house's customers inquired by telephone
whether he is present on the premises. The phrase ``porkie pies'' must have
taken root in such hostelries.
However, I digress. Let's talk about a kingdom - Fife; the Campbells' kingdom -
Dunfermline Athletic; and the cathedral city of Brechin.
Let's discuss Ian and Dick Campbell - twins, identical apart from the fact that
Dick wears a moustache, and Ian does not. Twins who have the same looks that
have driven picture caption writers to distraction trying to identify who's who
over the years. They have the telepathy associated with such a close bond, but
they treat the national game differently.
Ian is the calm side of the story. Dick - Richard, as his twin calls him -
almost happily admits to ``going over the top'' on occasions. An
understatement, believe me. While Ian sits in the stand taking a calm, almost
judicious view of what is happening on the park, Dick - the elder by 20 minutes
when they were born in November 22, 1953 - at times lets his assistant
manager's enthusiasm get the better of him.
Anyone who doubts this need only refer to standside linesmen for authenticity.
Mind you, a certain Bert Paton, chief at Dunfermline of the Clan Campbell,
occasionally makes visible reference to decisions he feels have gone against
his team.
He and the Campbells go back a long way. And, after all, they do share a family
connection. They're Fifers.
So to the brothers, born at Cowdenbeath as part of a family numbering seven -
four boys and three girls - to parents Elizabeth and Alex. Of the sons, Peter
at 48 is the eldest, then come the twins and then Duncan. Fitba daft, all of
them.
The twins several times have played in the same team - both amateur and
professional - beginning with Juveniles Townhill. However, in 1969, Dick moved
to Dundee United for a brief spell as a midfielder or defender, and as he
joked: ``I became home-sick.''
There followed five years or so with Cowdenbeath before he moved to Dunfermline
in 1975. Ross County in the Highland League beckoned under manager Ian McNeill,
then four or five more seasons - he admits that his memory for exact dates is a
bit iffy - at Brechin, back to Dunfermline, player-coach in the early 80s at
East Stirlingshire, at Raith Rovers when Gordon Wallace was manager, then back
to Brechin City where John Ritchie was in charge.
Pressure of business led him to go out of the game for six months before
joining Paton at Rosyth Juniors. He again returned to Dunfermline when Jocky
Scott was in charge, and then rejoined Paton when he was made manager at East
End Park.
When Dick Campbell reads this, he will feel uncomfortable. Those who know his
outgoing manner may find that difficult to understand, but he admitted: ``I
don't look back. It's incredibly unlucky. I'm quite a superstitious person.''
Over to Ian. There is a remarkable difference in style. Where Richard - as Ian
calls him - happily admits that he says what he thinks, but rarely thinks
before saying it, Ian has brought business management skills to his part-time
football career.
He attended Jordanhill College on a physical education course, taught at
Kirkcaldy High School, and throughout his football career, he has brought that
type of resource into the game, whether it be teaching youngsters, scoring 170
goals for Brechin - still a club record - being operations director at C R
Smith's double glazing company, where he worked for 10 years, or being managing
director now of his own company, Avenue Scotland.
``We are human-resource specialists,'' was his simple description. ``We manage
change in things like corporate services and recruitment.''
Perfect for a guy who still is part-time as far as football is concerned in a
career spanning spells with Dunfermline, Cowdenbeath, Brechin for eight years -
all as a player - eventually back to Dunfermline as a player-coach with Jim
Leishman in charge, during which time the East End Park side were promoted in
successive seasons from second to premier division.
As happens, when the poet Jim's famous words of half-time wisdom failed to
inspire, he went out the door. So did Ian Campbell.
Ian is back at Dunfermline as reserve team coach, happy with the memories,
especially those of when he played in the same teams as Richard. But as he
says: ``I prefer the low-key style. I'm passionate about the club, and only too
glad to help out.'' He's not doing too badly, either. His reserve side have
lost only once his season.
Mind you, like all families, even twins get up to a bit of mischief-making, and
in this case Richard has created his own wee bit of fun. Beginning on the
serious note of: ``It is magnificent to have Ian - he has strengths I don't
have, and ``Pink'' is not averse to giving me a slap over the head while
travelling back from a game when I have gone over the top.''
Pink? ``Oh, didn't you know that's Ian's nickname? When he was scoring all
those goals with Brechin, he was called after the Pink Panther, because the
opposition rarely could keep him down or even catch him.''
I may be wrong, but there could be another slap on the head for that one.
</TEXT>
