<HEADLINE>12 years for knife killing of teenager</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667800</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUTH who killed a 16-year-old with a stolen knife was ordered to be detained
for 12 years yesterday.
Only weeks after finishing two sentences for assault James Morrison, 19,
stabbed the boy six times.
He plunged the knife into Jamie Docherty's jugular vein and he bled to death
within minutes, the High Court in Glasgow heard.
Morrison, of Findlayson Drive, Kilmarnock, killed the boy with a knife he stole
during a housebreaking a week earlier.
He was originally charged with murder, but admitted a reduced charge of
culpable homicide yesterday.
Advocate-depute William Totten told Lord Hamilton that he accepted there had
been ``minimal'' provocation by the victim and another three youths.
A jury heard how Docherty, of MacNaughton Drive, Kilmarnock, punched and kicked
Morrison in the town's London Road in August this year.
Mr Totten said that Docherty bled to death in the street before ambulancemen
arrived.
He said that Morrison, who admitted two other assaults, had shown no remorse
for the killing and had told police a ``pack of lies''.
Mr Totten said that only days after completing nine-month and six-month periods
of detention in a Young Offenders' Institution Morrison attacked and robbed a
16-year-old boy.
Along with another youth he abducted the boy as he walked along the road and
forced him into a side street.
Mr Totten said: ``They made the boy sit on a wall and then Morrison punched him
in the face and robbed him of his watch, designer sweater, and #8.''
Mr Hugh Matthews, QC, defending, said Morrison had been placed in a home when
he was nine and had a ``terrible upbringing'' and had been assaulted by his
stepfather.
</TEXT>
