<HEADLINE>Korean storeowner jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667801</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Korean store
owner jailed
SEOUL: The owner of a South Korean department store which collapsed in June,
killing more than 500 people, was convicted yesterday for the country's worst
peace-time disaster and jailed for 10!s years. Lee Joon, 73, owner and founder
of the Sampoong Department Store, was found guilty of criminal negligence. His
42-year-old son, Han-sang, the store's president, was sentenced to seven years
on the same charge.
The court also sentenced Lee Choong-woo, a former chief administrator of the
residential area where the store was located, to three years in jail on bribery
charges. Relatives of the defendants wept as the sentences were read out.
Tribal feud
DARWIN: About 200 aborigines, some armed with boomerangs and spears, clashed
for several hours in a remote town yesterday as part of a tribal feud, police
said. Fighting broke out in Wadeye, about 140 miles southwest of Darwin, after
thousands of cans of beer were stolen from a local bar.
Mass poisoning
BEIJING: A mother and son were sentenced to death for the mass poisoning of
villagers in southern China, Beijing-backed newspaper Ta Kung Pao said
yesterday. Du Runqiong claimed she was driven by spirits to rid the world of
bad people, the court heard. Eighteen people died and 160 needed hospital
treatment.
Trekking on
OSLO: Borge Ousland, the Norwegian polar adventurer, who set a new record last
week by skiing alone to the South Pole, is not resting on his laurels. The
32-year-old skier now is ready to continue all the way across Antarctica,
alone, after digging up more supplies buried in the snow in 1990 by a previous
expedition, Norwegian media reported.
Pope `better'
ROME: Pope John Paul, whose Christmas was disrupted by a bout of influenza,
left the Vatican by helicopter yesterday for the papal residence of
Castelgandolfo south of Rome, Vatican officials said. The 75-year-old pontiff's
next public engagement is in Rome on December 31, when he is due to lead a New
Year's Eve thanksgiving service. ``He is better,'' a Vatican official said.
Waning support
CANBERRA: More than one in two Australians want an Australian head of state,
while only one in three want the British monarch to remain as Australia's
queen, according to a poll published yesterday.
</TEXT>
