<HEADLINE>Harry McLevy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIMMY REID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667803</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Harry McLevy, trade unionist; born August 28, 1936, died December 24, 1995
HARRY McLEVY was a fine human being. Kindness shone through everything he did.
He would remind me of good things I'd said, or written, a couple of years ago,
or 40 years ago, and yes, our friendship went back that long. He never seemed
to remember when I, or his other friends, had got it wrong. His judgment was
flawed by a generous spirit that looked only for the best in people. Oh that we
were all so flawed.
Harry's beliefs never degenerated into dogma which seals the mind within a
prison of our own making. When he died on Christmas Eve, Harry was Scottish
regional officer of the engineering union which, in its halcyon days, must have
been one of the most democratic institutions in the world. Every official was
elected and re-elected, or not re-elected.
The union had a national committee of 52 members, who took all policy and
strategic financial decisions, and was also the union's rules revision
committee. No full-time official, including the president, had a vote on this
committee.
It would sometimes meet for weeks at a time. In the 1970s Harry, Davie Todd
from Brechin, Jim Airlie, and myself, were members of the national committee,
then a battleground between the best-organised right and left-wing groupings in
the British labour movement.
The ongoing democracy meant there were always elections going on, without
respite. The right-wing and left-wing machines, by necessity, became
predominantly electoral machines. The union and its politics suffered in the
sense that living standards, the quality of life for all trade unionists and
their families, were now determined, as much by political decisions as by union
negotiations. Yet the union activists were too often immersed in internal union
feuding to see the wood for the trees.
This was put on the agenda very forcibly in Scotland with the UCS work in of
the early seventies. It inspired a political debate which transcended party
politics. About democracy not just being the right to a vote, but a right to
work, and other basic rights. This brought a cultural dimension to trade
unionism. Harry was in his element.
At that time left members of the AEU national committee were always booked into
some downmarket boarding house, which might have been all right for a night or
a weekend but harrowing when for longer. You know the kind of place. The
pervasive smell of left-over cabbage. An interior like the TV series Rising
Damp. The landlord might even look like Rigsby.
We rebelled. The four of us rented a flat, all mod cons. Davie had volunteered
to do whatever cooking was required. I best remember the meals at ``home''.
Davie's culinary repertoire was good but rather limited. Totties and mince was
his pice de resistance. We hammed it up. Candles. Wine. Mulling over the
problems of the world while dispatching a post-prandial brandy. As they say,
nothing is too good for the workers.
Harry revelled in the camaraderie. He was a Dundonian. Born in August 1936. His
father was a plater's helper in Caledon shipyards, later an engineer in Bonar
Longs. Harry became an engineer and his brother Frank a welder. Dad was a trade
unionist. His sons were too.
Harry from his apprentice days stood out. He became an outstanding trade union
leader. His vision of a wider role for trade unions found expression through
his work for the STUC, particularly in his work for a Scottish Parliament,
through which the Scottish people, he believed, could once again claim some
right of control over their own destiny.
Harry had been a communist. For years we had both been members of the party's
national executive. He was always in the liberal wing, and left the party in
the mid-eighties to join the Labour Party.
He was an utterly good man. His concern for others was manifest. His family
must be devastated, as are all his friends. Susan, Graeme, Sean, and Kevin,
their mother Susan, and Doris, who brought so much love to the last 18 years of
his life, might be able to draw some comfort from the knowledge that those of
us privileged to have known him, share their grief.
An appreciation by
JIMMY REID
</TEXT>
