<HEADLINE>The Mackintosh of Mackintosh</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667804</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lachlan Ronald Duncan Mackintosh, clan chief; born June 27, 1928, died December
25, 1995
THE Mackintosh clan were yesterday mourning the death of their chief. Lachlan
Mackintosh, who had been in poor health after suffering from kidney failure
earlier this year, died on Christmas Day at his home, Moy Hall, Tomatin,
Inverness-shire. The 67-year-old former naval lieutenant-commander had spent
most of his last months on a dialysis machine.
Lachlan Mackintosh was prominent in public life in the Scottish Highlands,
being Lord Lieutenant of Inverness, Lochaber, Badenoch, and Strathspey since
1985 as well as chief of the Mackintosh clan. The son of naval hero
Vice-Admiral Lachlan Mackintosh of Mackintosh, he was educated at the Royal
Navy College, Dartmouth, and succeeded his father as clan chief in 1957.
He was vice-president of the Scottish Conservative and Unionist Association
from 1969-71, a member of Inverness County Council from 1970-75, and a member
of Highland Regional Council from 1975 until his death. He was chairman of the
council's roads and transport committee from 1990 until he stepped down because
of ill health in the summer of this year. He also served as chairman, Inverness
Prison Visiting Committee, from 1973 to 1986.
Duncan McPherson, convener of Highland Regional Council, said of him: ``Public
life in the Highlands has lost one of its most distinguished representatives.''
</TEXT>
