<HEADLINE>James Edward Meade</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667805</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Edward Meade, economist and Nobel Prize winner; born June 23, 1907, died
December 22, 1995
JAMES Edward Meade, a Nobel Prize winner in economics, has died at the age of
88.
In 1977 Meade became the joint winner of the Nobel Prize in economic science,
along with former Swedish commerce minister Bertil Ohlin. They were honoured
for contributions to the theory of international trade. Meade had met Ohlin
just once, but some of Meade's studies had been viewed in the economics
community as sequels to Ohlin's work.
Meade was riding a bus to a university appointment when news of his prize
reached Britain. ``By the time I arrived, everyone seemed to know about the
prize but myself,'' Meade recalled.
After studying at Oxford and Cambridge, he lectured in economics at Oxford from
1930 to 1937. He worked in Geneva as a member of the economics section of the
League of Nations, precursor to the United Nations, from 1938 to 1940. He then
held several British government economic posts during the Second World War
until 1947.
Meade spent a decade as Professor of Commerce at the London School of
Economics, before working as a professor of political economy at Cambridge from
1957 to 1968. He also played a major role in GATT, the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, that has now been replaced by the World Trade Organisation
in Geneva; and he wrote extensively about economic theory.
His recent book, Full Employment Regained, published by Cambridge University
Press, suggested more economic planning might help undo some of what Meade
viewed as the negativism of 16 years of Conservative Party rule in Britain.
Meade is survived by his widow, Margaret; four children, Tom, Charlotte,
Bridget and Carol; eight grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
AP
</TEXT>
