<HEADLINE>Israel and Syria seek to complete Middle East jigsaw</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667806</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington
SYRIAN and Israeli diplomats were meeting today at a secluded conference centre
50 miles from here, hoping to complete the last major piece of the Middle East
peace process.
The American government chose the Wye Plantation, a group of houses on 1000
acres of farmland, because it is conveniently close to Washington and because
the press can be kept out.
The two sides have been talking on and off for years, ever since the Madrid
conference in October, 1991, when the Israelis first officially met Arab
delegations, including the Palestinians and Syrians.
That event was followed by fruitless meetings in Washington: the last round of
talks between Israel and Syria broke down last June.
Things have changed since 1991. Israel has made peace with the Palestinians and
Jordan, and Syria has been left behind.
After the assassination of Yitzak Rabin, President Assad seems to have realised
that the best hope for recovering the Golan Heights lay in cutting a deal with
the new prime minister, Shimon Peres, and acceded to American pressure to
resume the negotiations.
The proposal, once again, is that Israel give up the heights in exchange for a
complete peace agreement. In the past, the Syrians always insisted that Israel
must first withdraw from territory it occupied in 1967. It would then consider
whether or not to conclude a permanent peace treaty.
President Assad has now apparently conceded that the two agreements must be
simultaneous.
There remain considerable difficulties: what sort of international force will
police the Golan after the Israeli withdrawal, to ensure that it remains
demilitarised? Will that force be allowed to maintain Israel's elaborate
electronic intelligence apparatus now perched on top of Mount Hermon?
Where, exactly, is the boundary? After the 1948 war, the ceasefire agreement
designated certain areas as demiltarised. Israel subsequently occupied them,
and says they are part of Israel. Syria claims them now.
The 13,000 Israeli settlers who have made the desert bloom on the Golan would
have to leave. They are, of course, bitterly opposed to the suggestion. Israel
would also lose its only ski resort.
Peace with Lebanon would follow an Israeli-Syrian treaty, and then other Arab
states, led by Saudi Arabia, would be expected to recognise Israel and exchange
ambassadors.
The talks will last until the end of next week. Then there will be a pause, to
be followed, perhaps, by further American diplomacy and, if all goes well, with
another signing ceremony at the White House, with President Assad and Mr Peres
at last shaking hands on their peace treaty.
Meanwhile, Israeli troops in Ramallah ended 28 years of occupation in a matter
of minutes today, completing the handover to Palestinian rule of six West Bank
towns under a historic accord.
Hundreds of residents waved flags, cheered and hurled stones at departing
Israeli jeeps as Palestinian police entered the town's police station and
raised the Palestinian flag.
``We have taken over,'' the Palestinian governor of Ramallah, Abu Firas
Liftawi, said outside the police station.
In Gaza, PLO chairman Yasser Arafat told reporters: ``We praise the honest
implementation of the withdrawal process from the West Bank and I thank Mr
(Israeli Prime Minister Shimon) Peres for this.''
Israeli cabinet minister Yossi Beilin hailed the pullout as an important
milestone in Israeli-Palestinian relations.
Later today a contingent of 700 Palestinian police left the self-rule enclave
of Jericho to join the forces already in Ramallah, Palestinian sources said.
They said some 120 others crossed from Jordan to Jericho, the first contingent
of 5000 Israel has agreed to allow into the West Bank. In all there will be
12,000 Palestinian police in the West Bank. There are 18,000 police in Gaza.
The town of Ramallah, just eight miles north of Jerusalem, has extra
significance to many Palestinians.
``Redeployment from Ramallah has special importance. It has traditionally been
an economic and political centre and it is very close to Jerusalem,'' said
Marwan Barghouti, a prominent member of Arafat's Fatah organisation.
Ten minutes after the Palestinians took over the police station, they moved
into Ramallah's military headquarters, surprising everyone with the speed of
the takeover from Israel.
Earlier today the Israeli government said it would release between 1000 and
1100 Palestinian prisoners out of about 5000 it still holds. Israeli army radio
said they would be set free next week.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
