<HEADLINE>Worse still to come as Glasgow goes miles colder than Moscow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667807</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is no sign of a respite in the big freeze, with weathermen warning of
worse to come in the next few days.
The coldest place in Scotland yesterday was Altnaharra in Sutherland, where the
temperature plummeted to -20.7C and was expected to drop to -25C last night. It
was followed closely by Tulloch Bridge, near Fort William, at -20.5C.
Glasgow is also facing a deeper freeze with temperatures expected to drop to
20C below.
The city already suffered its coldest night on record when the mercury fell to
almost -19C on Tuesday night. The River Clyde froze in the city centre for the
first time since 1962.
The temperature was colder than Moscow's -15C, Kiev's -6C and New York's -9C
and even came close to Helsinki, which recorded -22C.
Weather experts blamed the cold spell on air currents from the Arctic Circle
and predict it will continue until the weekend.
A spokesman for Glasgow Weather Centre said: ``It is a legacy of very cold
northerly winds at the end of last week which came from the Arctic Circle and
probably the North Pole. There is very little wind and so there is nothing to
push the cold air away.''
He warned that temperatures of around -20C in Glasgow would again be felt
tonight and tomorrow night.
Forecasters also fear there will be a heavy snowfall in southern and central
Scotland during the weekend.
One resident of a remote area, preparing to face another night of freezing
temperatures, did not need a neighbouring building to tell her how cold it was.
Ms Anne Owen, of Burnside, Tulloch, lives near the automatic Met Office station
at Tulloch Bridge.
Tulloch, 22 miles from Fort William, traditionally features in the list of
extreme weather: this summer, it frequently boasted Scotland's highest
temperature, well into the eighties.
When Ms Owen, and her partner, Mr Dean Carpenter, returned from spending the
Christmas period with relatives in Fife, she discovered the mercury had dropped
to the opposite end of the scale and eight inches of snow had fallen.
``We found that all our bottled drinks had frozen solid, along with full hot
water bottles and the five gallon container of water we keep for emergencies.''
The couple, who are living in temporary accommodation on the site of the
derelict cottage they are planning to restore, donned several layers of
clothing and kept their gas fire on throughout Tuesday night and yesterday to
melt their water supplies.
Ms Owen, a craftworker who moved north from Wales three years ago, said:
``Every winter I have been here has been colder than the one before.'' She
added: ``We cannot do anything outside until the thaw comes.''
The Met Office prediction of even colder times ahead suggest she will have to
wait.
</TEXT>
