<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish negative equity total at #6m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON, FRANCES HORSBURGH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667809</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Labour Party yesterday claimed that a new survey carried out on its behalf
showed that 5000 people in Scotland now had homes worth, on average, #1200 less
than they paid for them.
In total the negative equity for houses in Scotland currently stands at #6m,
according to the study carried out by the financial institution, UBS Global
Research.
The average negative equity in Scotland of #1200 per household is more than the
North-west England (#1100); North of England (#800); Yorkshire (#700); and West
Midlands (#700). The 5000 people affected is 2000 up on a similar study carried
out last year.
The size of the problem north of the Border came as the Chartered Institute of
Housing predicted a rise in repossessions for home owners who lose their jobs,
but who in the past would have been covered by an income support safety net.
However a spokesman for the Conservative Party in Scotland took issue with the
new survey.
A party spokesman said: ``This survey disregards the fact that in 1979 a third
of the Scottish population were home owners. Now in 1995 over 55% of Scots own
their homes.
``We are pursuing policies of low inflation and low interest rates and this is
the best way to secure a long-term stable housing market for Scotland.''
However Labour's Shadow Housing Minister, Mr Nick Raynsford, warned that the
prospects of an improvement in the housing market next year were fragile and he
attacked Mr Major for presiding over record levels of repossession and negative
equity.
``Rather than helping homeowners in difficulty, John Major has cut mortgage tax
relief and reduced help to unemployed homeowners. This has thrown hundreds of
thousands of ordinary families out of their homes and chopped thousands off the
value of people's homes,'' said Mr Raynsford.
According to the survey Scotland, with #6m of negative equity, is the least
affected area of the country followed by Yorkshire with a total of #20m. Worst
hit was the affluent South-east of England with #2500m being wiped off the
house prices in the area. Badly affected also was Greater London where #1100m
was taken off the value of houses.
The end-of-year survey by the Chartered Institute of Housing showed a rising
number of houses being repossessed following the withdrawal in October of
income support for mortgage repayments from owners who become unemployed or
suffer long-term health problems.
Only three out of the 15 building societies questioned had already implemented
policies aimed at people previously covered by income support for mortgage
interest payments.
Two societies said they had not responded in any way to the income support
changes, while the remaining 10 acknowledged the Government's wish to promote
private provision and had informed customers about ISMI withdrawal although new
insurance packages were not yet in place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
