<HEADLINE>French face renewed condemnation over latest testing at South Pacific atoll Anger over fifth nuclear blast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667810</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
FRANCE staged the fifth in its series of bitterly-disputed nuclear weapons
tests in the South Pacific today, a Defence Ministry spokesman said.
The spokesman said the underground explosion took place at Mururoa Atoll in
French Polynesia. (21.30 GMT).
The blast, equivalent to less than 30 kilotonnes of conventional explosives,
was designed to improve France's ability to simulate nuclear tests on computers
It was the fifth in a series that broke a 1992 moratorium on French nuclear
testing. The first took place on September 5, the second on October 2, the
third on October 27 and the fourth on November 21.
Press reports have said the test had first been scheduled for December 22 when
it would have coincided with sensitive talks between the French government and
unions after a crippling three-week public sector strike.
The reports said Prime Minister Alain Juppe asked President Jacques Chirac to
delay it until after Christmas.
Chirac says the tests are needed to validate a new warhead for France's
submarine-based missiles and acquire the ability to simulate tests on computer.
He has promised to sign a treaty banning nuclear tests forever once the series
is completed.
Chirac says France will probably conduct six tests, down from the eight
originally planned, and Defence Minister Charles Millon has said the series
will end in February.
Chirac, who is to visit Washington on February 1, denies he is cutting short
the series because of an international outcry against the tests.
In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Julie Reside expressed
disappointment that France was continuing to conduct nuclear tests.
``We have supported a temporary ban on all nuclear testing and would like to
see other nuclear powers support such a ban as well,'' she said.
``We're disappointed that France does continue to conduct (nuclear) tests.''
A White House official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the test did
not come as a surprise.
``We have expressed our concern that they are going on with these tests, and
again we regret that they felt the need to continue their testing, despite the
fact that they have assured us that this will be terminated in the early part
of next year,'' the official said.
New Zealand said today that France's reputation in the Pacific had sunk to an
all-time low with the latest test in French Polynesia.
``France is its own worst enemy,'' Prime Minister Jim Bolger said in a
statement.
``France has defied world opinion through continued testing. Its reputation in
the Pacific is at an all-time low. When the tests are over, France will have to
rebuild its credentials in the region. It has a long way to go.''
France, despite a chorus of international condemnation, insists the tests pose
no danger to the environment. It says they are needed to validate a new warhead
for submarine-based missiles and improve the ability to simulate tests by
computer.
Bolger said French ambassador Jacques le Blanc would again be called in to
receive a strong protest, as he has after every previous test.
Officials said he would be asked to meet a senior Foreign Ministry
representative in Wellington tomorrow.
``We will remind France that the United Nations General Assembly, in a formal
resolution, has just deplored continued testing and called for its immediate
end,'' Bolger said.
``France's actions are unacceptable. This latest test flies in the face of
world public opinion which is moving, ever more firmly, towards the view that
nuclear weapons should be eliminated.''
New Zealand has helped to lead international opposition to the French tests. It
sent a small navy ship to Mururoa to shepherd protest yachts at the start of
the series and it launched an unsuccessful legal challenge in the International
Court of Justice.
Bolger again called on President Jacques Chirac, who has indicated there will
be six tests, to make this one the last.
``If France is to rebuild its standing in this part of the world, it must start
by announcing the end of its misguided testing programme,'' he said.
``I, and all New Zealanders, now call on President Chirac to take that decision
without further delay.''
A spokesman for environmental group Greenpeace in Tahiti said the latest test
was a fresh snub to the local population.
Marc Defourneaux told the New Zealand Press Association: ``The local people
feel totally humiliated.
"It is like they are in mourning for someone who has died. Every time there is
a test it is just another humiliation to them as an indigenous
people.''
The latest test was greeted with anger tonight by British opposition parties
and anti-nuclear campaigners.
Labour said the test was ``unnecessary'' and risked causing environmental
damage while the Liberal Democrats accused the French of ignoring world opinion.
Both parties attacked the British Government for its continuing refusal to
condemn the test programme.
Labour's Shadow Defence David Clark said that it was now time for the French to
draw a line under the current programme and declare it        over.
``It is a disgrace. These tests are unnecessary and can be simulated in a
laboratory. I would like to think the French would end 1995 by ending this
series of tests.''
He urged the British Government to add its voice to the worldwide condemnation
of the test programme.
The Liberal Democrats' defence and foreign affairs spokesman Menzies Campbell
said there was no scientific or military justification for the latest test.
``Jacques Chirac has yet again shown himself to be impervious both to French
domestic and international opinion,'' he said.--PA/Reuter
</TEXT>
