<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Death on Rock families paid legal costs Heseltine overruled by Majorp</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667812</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Major has overruled his deputy Michael Heseltine by insisting that #38,700
should be paid to cover the legal costs of three families of IRA terrorists.
They fought a case through the European Court of Human Rights on the grounds
that the SAS had acted illegally in killing their unarmed relatives in a
firefight in Gibraltar seven years ago.
The decision to pay the legal costs was being seen by right-wingers in the Tory
Party as a payout to extremists.
At the same time it was being regarded by others as an indication of how far
the Prime Minister is prepared to go to ensure the peace process in Ireland
should progress.
The money was quietly paid out only after the parliamentary recess began and
was leaked when cheques appeared amid the Christmas cards of those most closely
involved.
Family members of the dead terrorists - Mairead Farrell, Sean Savage, and
Daniel McCann - saw it as admission that their relatives were murdered by
British special forces.
Last night in Whitehall that interpretation was being totally dismissed.
Instead it was said there was a legal obligation on Britain to follow decisions
of the courts.
However, the Ministry of Defence has been ordered that it must pay the bill for
the costs out of its budget.
The collective Cabinet decision to pay up is an embarrassment for Mr Heseltine,
himself a former Defence Secretary. At the time of the original ruling of the
Court of Human Rights he declared: ``We will not be swayed or deterred in any
way by this ludicrous decision of the court.''
Confirmation that the Government had caved in and would pay the legal costs -
yesterday was the last day the court had given it - is a further indication of
how embarrassing all of this is for the Conservative Party.
Mr Heseltine branded the original judgment of the human rights court as ``a
disgraceful slur''. At the time journalists, briefed by high sources, predicted
that Britain might defy the ruling by refusing to pay the fine.
Some newspapers suggested the United Kingdom might even pull out of an
organisation it was instrumental in setting up in the first place. Yesterday
Government sources declared that this was pure speculation by the media at the
time. No Minister had suggested pulling out, not least Mr Heseltine.
The UK was the first nation to put its signature to the establishment of the
Court of Human Rights.
Last night it emerged it was argued in Cabinet that it would be perverse to
pull out at this stage when former Soviet Union states were considering joining
. . . even more so when there were indications that Bosnia too might eventually
accept the court's jurisdiction on human rights despite allegations of war
crimes against leaders.
</TEXT>
