<DOCNO>GH951228-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Floods wreak havoc on Nato troops in Bosnian peace drive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667813</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATO's Bosnian peace drive came under attack from the weather today when flash
floods hit a French Foreign Legion camp and threatened to delay the building of
a bridge crucial for a US troop build-up.
Helicopters plucked some 60 Legionnaires to safety when a tented camp for 1000
paratroops outside the southern Bosnian town of Mostar was engulfed by the
flooded River Neretva.
Nearby bridges were swept away and men of the renowned French fighting unit
were forced to take to nearby rooftops to await rescue, but no-one was reported
hurt.
It was the first natural disaster to strike the alliance's biggest military
operation in 50 years since it took over Bosnian peace enforcement from a
toothless UN organisation a week ago.
An Italian military policeman, working with a civil law-enforcement group in
Mostar, died when his car skidded off the road in a rainstorm, amid floods that
threatened villages in the surrounding area.
Driving rain also jeopardised plans by US engineers to throw two pontoon
bridges across the Sava River dividing Croatia and Bosnia by this weekend.
The bridges are intended for the bulk of America's 20,000-strong force to reach
their Tuzla headquarters in the north.
To be assembled from parts by US army engineers, the pontoons hold the key link
in a corridor for arriving American troops from rear bases in Germany to
Bosnia.
``If these weather conditions persist, the river crossing can be potentially
delayed,'' said Major Jerry O'Hara, a spokesman for the Nato-led Implementation
Force (IFOR).
``We are looking at the river very closely,'' O'Hara told Reuters by telephone
from his Zagreb headquarters.
But alliance officials said plans to keep the warring factions apart and police
the hard-won peace were going ahead across the divided country, where a
60,000-strong world army is being assembled in an unprecedented show of Nato
strength.
The alliance summoned rival military commanders to Porebrice, northern Bosnia,
for their first regional peace talks in a bleak no-man's-land of bunkers and
minefields chosen by Nato to drive home the horror of the 3!s-year conflict.
Major General William Nash, head of US troops in Nato's Bosnia peace force,
convened the gathering so the warring parties' commanders could discuss
implementing peace by removing millions of mines strewn across the country.
They met in the remains of a shelled restaurant straddling snow-covered front
lines in north Bosnia where Muslims, Serbs and Croats fought some of the war's
fiercest battles.
The grim battlefield zone was meant ``to symbolise the horror of war and get on
with the peace,'' Nash's aide, Colonel Henry Strathman, told reporters. Spanish
troops and armour crossed into Serb-held areas of southern Bosnia for the first
time to assert Nato's ``go anywhere'' peace mandate.
In driving rain, a column of a dozen vehicles, including BMR armoured cars with
25mm cannon and 12.7mm machineguns, headed east from a checkpoint outside
Mostar towards the Bosnian Serb town of Nevesinje.
Under the peace accords rival military forces in the capital, Sarajevo, were
required to pull back from designated sites along the confrontation line they
fought over by midnight.
``It's going pretty well but the local commander is allowed to be a little
flexible and we'll wait until midnight to make a judgment,'' said a Nato
sources who asked not to be named.
A nominal deadline of 11am had been set, but local French commander General
Robert Rideau decided to extend it to provide more time for the withdrawal and
evaluation.
``I think that by tonight all our objectives will have been met,'' said Nato
spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Richard Pernod.
``What is significant is that at midnight all the very important places on the
frontline will be vacated,'' he added.
Many of the frontline positions selected for troop withdrawals were the scene
of bitter hand-to-hand fighting during the war over Serb secession from
Muslim-led Bosnia.
The centre of the historic southern Bosnian city of Mostar was threatened with
serious flooding, a French police officer said.
``The city centre could be entirely flooded if a dam just north of the city
were to burst,'' said gendarmerie Lieutenant-Colonel Jean-Pierre Fournet.
American forces have set up ``Checkpoint Assassin'' to control the way through
an eerily becalmed Bosnian war zone for 20,000 US troops joining the Nato-led
peace force.
Six US Bradley armoured battle vehicles with crew that include Gulf War
veterans train their guns on serene snowbound fields in the Posavina Corridor
where separatist Serbs fought Croat and Bosnian government forces on either
side of them for 43 months. -Reuter.
Sarajevo
</TEXT>
