<DOCNO>GH951228-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The poisoned pen signs off for another year</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667816</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO: Time to clear out the rubbish (surely ``droll vignettes and witty
apercus''?) from the locker before we hand in the poisoned pen and the chainsaw
(surely ``bardic quill and limner's sable''?) and join the rest of you in a
seasonal stupor (surely ``quiet contemplation of the turning year''?).
Time for the stuff we were never desperate enough to use on any other Thursday
morning. Time for jokes so old they predate Tory government, for stories so
shaggy you could enter them at Cruft's. Time, in other words, for the
Highlights of the Year.
JANUARY: Tories knocking lumps out of each other while the weather provokes the
usual exodus. With it, a crop of travellers' tales.
We hear, first, of the notice in a Belgrade hotel lift: ``To more the cabin,
push button for wishing floor. If the cabin should enter more persons, each one
should press a number of wishing floor. Driving is then going alphabetically by
national order.''
Not to be outdone, an Athens hotel instructed: ``Visitors are expected to
complain at the office between the hours of 9am and 11am daily'', while in
Bucharest a sign announced ``The flattening of underwear with pleasure is the
fob of the chambermaid.''
To which add the plea of a Norwegian lounge bar: ``Ladies are requested not to
have children in the bar''; and the boast of a Copenhagen airline office: ``We
take your bags and send them in all directions.''
Finally, a Japanese booklet concerning a hotel's air conditioning: ``Cooles and
Heates: If you want just condition of warm in your room, please control
yourself.''
FEBRUARY: Nothing ever happens in February.
MARCH: In like a lion, whatever that means. Where, come to that, are all those
cloots actually cast when May is ``oot''? A ``reader'' volunteers equally
penetrating queries which we come to think of as Questions That Need Answering.
Why isn't ``phonetic'' spelled the way it sounds? How, if nothing sticks to
Teflon, do they make Teflon stick to the pan? Why, if black boxes on aircraft
are indestructible, don't they make a whole plane out of the same stuff?
APRIL: With the economic outlook worsening and the Tories knocking lumps out of
each other, heart-rending tales emerge from the welfare system. Did we believe
these? Did we care? Thus (allegedly) from an Edinburgh benefit office came the
story of the woman writing to explain that ``I am forwarding a marriage
certificate and six children. I have seven, one died, which are baptised on a
half sheet of paper.''
Another went straight to the point: ``I cannot get sick pay. I have six
children. Can you tell me why?'' Amid all this there were the little human
tragedies: ``I am glad to report that my husband, who is missing, is dead'';
``This is my eighth child. What are you going to do about it?''; ``You have
changed my little boy to a girl. Will this make any difference?'' Our
favourite, though, was simplicity itself: ``I am forwarding my marriage
certificate and five children, one of which is a mistake as you can see.''
MAY: Cloots officially oot. This does not prevent Tories from knocking lumps
out of each other.
JUNE: Warm and dry. Resolve to write no more about Tories.
JULY: Nothing of note save Tories knocking etc: the silly season. Ditto the ad
from a Midlands freesheet: ``Lost: small apricot poodle. Reward. Neutered. Like
one of the family.''
This was matched by an advertisement spotted in California: ``Now is your
chance to have your ears pierced and get an extra pair to take home, too.''
For our own part, we recalled the attempt at English of a French farmer:
``Wanted: Unmarried girls to pick fresh fruit and produce at night.''
AUGUST: We hear of the Glasgow solicitor who dies and, inexplicably, winds up
in heaven. At the Pearly Gates he is dismayed to find thousands in the queue to
see Saint Peter.
To his surprise, the saint leaves the gate and comes to greet McGrabbit
personally. Then St Peter takes the solicitor by the hand and guides him to a
comfortable chair.
The lawyer says, ``I don't mind all this attention, but what makes me so
special?''
St Peter replies: ``Well, I've added up all the hours you billed your clients.
You must be 193 years old!''
SEPTEMBER: Holidays over, the Diary finds itself in receipt of fresh evidence
that English is indeed, if paradoxically, the international lingua franca. This
time it's menus, or as one inventive Chicago burger bar had it, ``me 'n'
yous''. From Cairo came ``Muscles Of Marines/Lobster Thermos''; ``Prawn cock
and tail''; and, taking the piece without much resistance, ``French-fried
ships''.
From Europe we heard of ``Garlic Coffee''; ``Sole Bonne Femme (Fish
Landlady-style)''; and ``Dreaded veal cutlet with potatoes in cream''. All this
rounded off with ``Sweat from the trolley''.
It was from the mystic east, nevertheless, that the best fine-food sightings
arrived. From Japan there was ``Strawberry crap'', the mouth-watering
``Buttered saucepans and fried hormones'', and delicious ``Teppan Yaki - Before
Your Cooked Right Eyes''.
We also heard tell of a Japanese mineral water called ``Kolic''; a Chinese
adhesive named ``Ass Glue''; an Austrian VCR known as a ``Hornyphon''; a Greek
soft drink called ``Zit''; a Ghanaian pepper sauce named ``Shitto''; and a
Spanish detergent called ``Colon Plus''.
OCTOBER: We are asked how many supermodels it takes to screw in a light bulb.
Answer: One. She just stands there, holding the bulb, and the whole world
revolves around her.
While waiting for the Tories to stop knocking lumps out of one another, we are
also asked how many Real Men it takes to change a bulb.
Answer: None. Real Men aren't afraid of the dark.
Then: how many thriller writers does it take to screw in a light bulb? Answer:
Two. One to screw it almost all the way in, and the other to give it a
surprising twist at the end.
NOVEMBER: Road safety campaigns begin, coinciding with the usual slew of
(probably) apocryphal tales from the insurance industry of statements made on
claims forms. Thus: ``Coming home I drove into the wrong house and collided
with a tree I don't have.''
``I thought my window was down, but I found it was up when I put my head
through it.''
``I pulled away from the side of the road, glanced at my mother-in-law and
headed over the embankment.''
``I told the police that I was not injured, but on removing my hat found that I
had a fractured skull.''
DECEMBER: On Christmas Day, according to the Associated Press, three men steal
the proceeds from a Belgrade branch of McDonald's. The burgers are left
untouched.
Meanwhile, a correction appears in the New Yorker. The note explains that one
William Bennett had criticised presidential candidate Patrick Buchanan's
politics as ``a real us-and-them kind of thing'' and not, as the magazine had
previously reported, ``a real S&amp;M kind of thing''.
Back home, the news is of the Shetland blizzards and their devastating effect
on power supplies. On ITN the bulletin concludes with the usual weather
forecast and the usual word from the usual, though not strictly applicable,
sponsor. Something about Powergen serving us ``whatever the weather''.
Thus the very last Question That Needs Answering: How does the man who drives
the snowplough get to his work?
IAN BELL
</TEXT>
