<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Top adviser to premier seconded to British Gas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TOP adviser to Mr Major is leaving Downing Street early in the new year to
work for British Gas's controversial chief executive, Mr Cedric Brown.
Former diplomat Roderic Lyne, 43, who for the last three years has been one of
the Prime Minister's private secretaries, will work alongside the privatised
company's international team.
Mr Lyne, who played an important behind-the-scenes role in Northern Ireland
handling sensitive negotiations leading to the IRA ceasefire, will remain an
employee of the Foreign office and return there when his period of secondment,
six months to one year, is completed.
Whitehall sources stressed there was ``nothing significant'' in Mr Lyne's
departure.
But last night Labour MP John McFall, Shadow spokesman on Scottish Affairs,
including employment, said: ``Surely someone could have been found from outside
Government providing a job for someone more in need of it, especially at a time
when British Gas are still planning to shed thousands of jobs?''
A British Gas spokeswoman said: ``Secondments like this are routine as part of
the Government/industry exchange programme designed to broaden experience and
understanding of the way each works.''
Over the last year the public image of British Gas has taken a nosedive in a
series of public relations disasters.
</TEXT>
