<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Public pay rise pressure grows</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667818</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was last night facing new pressure over public pay with an
expected recommendation that 1.4 million workers should receive inflation-plus
rises.
The five independent review bodies, covering teachers, doctors and dentists,
nurses and allied professions, the armed forces, and judges and senior civil
servants, were reported to have recommended rises at or above the current 3.1%
inflation rate.
The recommended awards, due to be presented to the Cabinet in the new year,
will add to the pressure on Chancellor Kenneth Clarke who is determined to keep
a tight rein on public spending.
At the same time, they are unlikely to go far enough for the unions, with
teachers and health service representatives warning of deepening recruitment
difficulties unless they receive significant increases.
The teaching unions are today expected to submit their claim for a 4% rise amid
claims there could be a 30,000 teacher shortage by the end of the decade unless
action is taken.
Although Mr Clarke allocated an extra #774m to improve education in the Budget,
relaxing capping limits to enable local education authorities to fund it, a 4%
increase would absorb almost the entire rise.
The pressure for substantial rises is likely to be even more acute in the
health service where there are severe staff shortages in professions such as
physiotherapy, occupational therapy, and psychology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sri Lankan officials bid to straighten out problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SRI Lankan officials are considering asking for a meeting with Australian
umpire Darrell Hair as they try to salvage the Test career of off-spinner
Muttiah Muralidharan.
The 23-year-old bowler's future is in doubt after he was no-balled for throwing
on Tuesday during the Australian first innings in the second Test in Melbourne.
Anura Tennekoon, secretary of the Board of Control for Cricket in Sri Lanka,
said yesterday that it was essential to discover exactly what Hair finds
illegal about Muralidharan's style of delivery.
Tennekoon, a former Sri Lankan captain, said the team management were in the
process of reviewing the videotapes of Muralidharan in action during the overs
in which he was called for throwing.
``We want to find exactly from the umpire why some (deliveries) were called and
some weren't,'' he said.
Tuesday marked only the ninth occasion in Test history that a player has been
deemed to have illegally delivered a ball.
Muralidharan had not previously been no-balled for throwing in a 59-match
first-class career, but on Tuesday the highest wicket-taker in his country's
short Test history was no-balled seven times in the space of three overs.
On Wednesday, Muralidharan operated entirely from the Members' End under the
gaze of New Zealand umpire Steve Dunne, who did not no-ball him at any stage.
Umpire Hair was silent as he looked on from square leg.
Dunne's lack of action meant he ruled that Muralidharan bowled legitimately,
without straightening his arm while releasing the ball, although there was no
apparent change to his bowling action.
Muralidharan, who has taken 81 Test wickets, finished the day with unflattering
figures of one for 124 from 38 overs. But at least he bowled 20 overs without
censure on the second day.
But that was the only good news for the tourists, who suffered for a dismal
three sessions as Australia moved from their overnight 234 for three to declare
at 500 for six.
At close of play, Sri Lanka, trailing 1-0 in the three-Test series, were 29 for
one after losing Roshan Mahanama for three.
AUSTRALIA v SRI LANKA
</TEXT>
