<DOCID>GH951228-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Killers flee with cash after rocket attack on security van</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667821</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lille
HOODED robbers attacked an armoured security van with a rocket launcher and
machineguns in northern France early today and killed one of its crew before
escaping with a large sum of cash, police said.
Two other Brink's employees were shot in the leg in the attack at about 1am in
Lesquin, about nine miles from the Belgian border. The exact amount stolen was
not disclosed.
Police said that more than 10 armed and masked men had taken part in the
attack, which appeared to have been carefully planned.
About 60 spent shells were found on the ground afterwards.
The armoured van had left Lille after collecting the day's receipts from
supermarkets when its way was blocked by two cars.
When the guards refused to leave the van, the thieves opened fire and blew up
the van's security door with a liquid explosive.
A 35-year-old guard, father of three children, died in the blast, police said.
Two other employees were in hospital in Lille.
The driver of a photo delivery van which had stopped behind the Brink's vehicle
said the thieves ordered him to get out and flee on foot.
``I ran, I heard several shots and I saw flames,'' he said. ``The robbers told
the guards to get out of the van. Hearing a refusal, they didn't hesitate and
fired point blank.''
The 10 men had used a roadblock to stop the armoured van near Lille airport.
After the three security guards in the Brink's van refused to flee, the
assailants - wearing hoods and black clothes - opened fire on the van with
assault rifles and used a rocket launcher to open the car's door, the delivery
van driver said. He fled into nearby bushes and witnessed the attack.
He said the heist lasted 15 minutes and the assailants calmly left in two cars.
``We're clearly dealing with a team of really professional bandits,'' said
Lille police commissioner Alain Epstein.
He said the assailants were ``determined, organised and without scruples.''
He said he did not know how much money had been stolen from the armoured van.
Police recovered about 70 shells from Kalashnikov assault rifles.
The armoured car was riddled with holes and its side door was blown out. Four
bags full of money were left behind.
Police were investigating the possibility that the attack was carried out by
the same gangsters who committed a similar heist in Belgium several days ago.
Five people, including two gendarmes and a child, were injured just outside
Brussels when thieves in two large trucks attempted to hold up two armoured
vans.
More than 50 armoured vehicles have been attacked in Belgium this year, many by
heavily-armed groups of about 10 men.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
