<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glasgow shivers into the record books</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STARRS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667823</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW was today expected to wake up even colder after shivering its way
through the lowest temperatures ever recorded in the city.
Weathermen predicted that a new minimum of -18.7C recorded at Glasgow Airport
yesterday morning would drop further overnight, possibly to as low as -20C.
They said the Arctic conditions would continue for the rest of the week and
warned of more snow to come at the weekend, bringing with it a bleak and bitter
Hogmanay for party revellers.
The coldest place in Scotland on Tuesday night was at Altnaharra, Caithness,
where the temperature plummeted to -20.7C. It was followed closely by Tulloch
Bridge, near Fort William, at -20.5C.
The freeze continued in Grampian with a temperature of -20.1C in Braemar at 9am
yesterday, the coldest for 11 years.
In January 1985, the temperature in Braemar dropped to -23C and there is
speculation in the Deeside town that the British record of -27.2C, set in 1982,
might be challenged overnight.
The -18.7C recorded at Glasgow Airport warmed up to a high of -9.6C yesterday
afternoon. Edinburgh shivered in a high of -4.6C, and the coldest place in
Scotland at 2pm yesterday was at Loch Glascarnoch, Caithness, at -12C.
Mr Tom Keenan of the Glasgow Weather Centre said a combination of Arctic winds,
snow on the ground, clear skies at night and Glasgow's position in a valley
were all helping to produce the unusually low temperatures in the city.
Edinburgh's proximity to the Firth of Forth helped keep temperatures to a
relative high of -12C yesterday morning.
Mr Keenan said: ``For the past few days we have been getting winds coming right
down from the North Pole, so obviously they are very, very cold.
``They have then dropped off over central Scotland and there haven't been any
clouds at night, so the temperatures have dropped even lower.
``Glasgow also gets cold air seepage which spills down off the hills.
``The temperature is getting off to a very low start. It dropped 13 degrees on
Tuesday night, so if it goes the same way again it will be heading towards -20C
overnight.
``It becomes progressively colder each night. It's going to last for the rest
of the week with things taking a turn for the worse during the weekend.
``We are expecting a fair bit of snow to come up from the south-west. The
timing is a bit up in the air, but at the moment we think it will be in the
second half of Saturday or the first half of Sunday. There will be significant
snowfalls in central Scotland and it will be fairly disruptive as well.
``There is an increasing risk of getting some freezing fog because the air is
becoming very stagnant, it's picking up smoke and pollution which all helps fog
to form. Once it fogs out, the temperature can't fall any lower.''
He said a thaw could come at the start of next week, but added: ``Our
confidence isn't particularly high on that scenario at the moment.''
Social services chiefs in Strathclyde have appealed for people to check on
elderly neighbours struggling to keep warm in the arctic temperatures.
Two OAPs were taken into care yesterday because of burst pipes in their homes
and Scottish Gas engineers struggled to clear a huge backlog of calls for help
from people left without heating or hot water.
A spokeswoman for Strathclyde Regional Council's social work department said:
``People seem to have been coping remarkably well, but how long that can go on
is another matter.''
She said many elderly people were worried about their water pipes bursting
because of the weather.
</TEXT>
