<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Singing the praises of real stinkeroos</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIMMY REID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667824</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN 1996 I would like to record, with full orchestral backing, the world's 20
worst songs. An inspiration prompted by your response to my strong views of
what might loosely be called a song, I Believe, which does for believing what
John Wayne did for acting.
Real stinkeroo songs are so bad they become good in a perverse sort of way.
Take Nobody's Child. It plumbed the depths of bad taste and then went further.
A blind orphan with no mother's kisses is an image which would normally reduce
me to tears, but I kept thinking of hard-bitten writers cynically wringing out
the pathos. ``Let's make her blind. That will really have them bubbling in the
streets of Govan tonight.'' And it did, yes it did, in spades, with knobs on.
Hollywood, when making The Jazz Singer, sent for some of Tin Pan Alley's best
songwriters. Al Jolson, a monster according to those who knew him, whose mania
for himself was boundless, demanded a show-stopping song. Buddy De Sylva, Lew
Brown, and Ray Henderson were credited, if that's the right word, for what they
considered, and meant to be, the biggest ever load of songwriting manure the
world had ever seen or heard. A monstrous song for a monster, Sonny Boy.
Jolson loved it, so did the public, thus giving birth to the still prevailing
wisdom of tabloid thinking: ``You can't lose by underestimating the taste of
Joe Public.'' Talking movies were off to a low-flying start and have plunged to
the depths ever since.
But wait a minute. Think of the fun we've had with Sonny Boy. The many
parodies. ``Climb upon my knee sonny boy, though you're six foot three, sonny
boy. There's no way of knowing, just how fast you're growing, or what you mean
to me, sonny boy.''
I remember being taken to the Glasgow Empire by my Dad when but a child. Top of
the bill was Izzy Bonn, who revelled in schmaltz. My Yiddish Mamma was his
theme song. He would come to the front of the stage and belt it out, right to
the gods. Unashamedly trawling for emotional responses.
It was during or just prior to the festive season. He sang a song which went
roughly as follows: ``He's the little boy who Santa Claus forgot, and goodness
knows he didn't want a lot. He sent a note to Santa for some soldiers and a
gun. It broke his little heart when he found Santa hadn't come. In the streets
he envied all those lucky boys, and wandered home to last year's broken toys.
I'm so sorry for that laddie, for he hasn't got a daddy. He's the little boy
that Santa Claus forgot.'' All around adults were howling, and not wanting to
be left out of this mass outpouring of grief, I started howling as well.
I have never forgotten, when still just a child, Tommy Morgan throwing down the
gauntlet to the leader of the Third Reich, at the height of the last war, from
the stage of the Glasgow Pavilion. ``There'll always be a Rothesay at the Ferr.
There'll always be a Rothesay at the Ferr. Hitler thinks he's very, very cute,
but he'll never spend his holidays on the dear old Kyles of Bute. He'll sink a
few more sma' boats I suppose, but he'll never sink the Duchess of Montrose. He
may bomb and bomb and bomb us, but we'll never turn a hair, for there'll always
be a Rothesay at the Ferr.''
Nor will I forget Sammy Murray in the Queen's Theatre singing ``Orra King's
horses, Orra King's men, Marching up the Gallowgate, and marching back again,
orra King's horses and orra King's men.''
Our very own, multi-talented, eternally effervescent Cliff Hanley could write a
bad song or two, very deliberately, and I'm not thinking of Scotland the Brave.
I have an LP of Fran and Anna singing a song written by Cliff entitled Voulez
Vous Ra Noo. Lorenz Hart would have proudly laid claim to the lyric. And Fran
and Anna, Scotland's answer to the Andrews Sisters, did it justice.
Jack Short, Jimmy Logan's dad, dabbled in song writing. During the shooting of
the movie Rockets Galore, the crew and stars were based on the island of Barra.
Half of Scottish Equity seemed employed on the project. Some of the old acting
hands, as was their wont, did severe damage each night to the whisky stocks in
the hotel's residents' bar. Except Jim's dad.
One morning at breakfast he looked round his fellow thespians, whose heads were
down, eyeing suspiciously the fried eggs on their plates, and said something
like this: ``While you lot were belting the bevvy last night I was getting tore
intae writing a song,'' which he then sang. It was called Effie O'Hara fae
Barra. I would dearly love to get my hands on that song. It seems a prime
candidate for my LP.
But what about, ``A you're adorable, B you're so byootiful, C you're a cutieful
of charm.'' Come on admit it. It's trite, trivial, and altogether tremendous.
And there's, ``If you walk through a storm keep you're head up high, and don't
be afraid of the dark.'' I tried it one night, and nearly broke my neck. Songs
like that should come with a health warning.
Tom Jones had some really rotten songs, like Delilah and, It's Not Unusual, To
Be Loved By Someone Else. Which begs the question, who else can love you, if
not someone else?
You can have some fun with good songs. There is a vandal in Glasgow by the name
of Lex Kelly who re-writes Sinatra standards in Glasgowese. One of his lines
was, ``And tell me whit street, compares wi' Pitt Street''. This got me going
and I penned, ``I get no kick from champagne, wood alcohol never thrills me at
all, won't you tell me just how it can be, that I get a kick from VP?''
But when it's good songs you're mucking about with you feel guilty. It's kind
of sacrilegious. Deliberately mocking rotten songs is counterproductive. You
cannot make them any worse.
The best way to bring out their inner meaninglessness is to sing them straight,
particularly if you have a rotten voice. The mawkishness can then become
magical. You don't believe me? Just listen to me singing A You're Adorable in
5/4 time. A one, a two, a three, four, five. ``A you're `effin' adorable, B
you're so effin' byootiful . . .'' Convinced? Happy New Year to you all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
