<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A winter wonderland on the slopes for thousands of skiers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667825</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a winter wonderland yesterday for thousands of skiers and snow-boarders
enjoying Alpine conditions on Scotland's slopes.
Temperatures at the five winter sports centres remained well below zero all
day, with clear blue skies and calm winds.
Access to all the resorts presented no problems other than drivers having to
take extra care on the icy roads.
But some of the centres still remain a bit short of snow and the White Corries
Centre in Glencoe has yet to open for the season.
More than one thousand people flocked to the Cairngorm slopes, near Aviemore,
where seven lifts out of 17 were in operation.
Ms Tania Adams, of the Cairngorm Chairlift Company, said: ``Overhead conditions
here are perfect. There is hardly any wind and the sun shone throughout the
day. Our snow-cover is still a bit lighter than we would like, but the pisting
machines have been in action giving us some good complete runs.''
At the Lecht Ski Centre all but one of the 12 lifts were working.
Temperatures there did not rise above -8C but blue skies and sunshine were
enjoyed by the 900 skiers.
At Glenshee the chairlift company had three upper lifts and six lower ones
working at Cairnwell, near Braemar.
Some of the Glenshee runs were complete with packed snow. But cover is thin on
others and limited nursery areas were available.
Temperatures there peaked at -9C, and around 2000 people were out on the slopes.
Around 1000 people were on the slopes at Scotland's newest winter sports
centre, Nevis Range, on the 4006ft Aonach Mor, near Fort William.
The resort, which underwent a #750,000 expansion in the close season, is still
a bit short of snow.
There was ample snow on the nursery slopes, but the slopes available for
intermediate-level skiers were ``a bit limited'' said Nevis Range spokeswoman
Cally Fleming.
But there was still no action at the White Corries Centre at Glencoe, which
needs a heavy snowfall to fill in the big gullies.
Mr Ian Symons, of Castle Douglas-based Weather Watchers, says there is a good
chance of fresh heavy snowfalls on the slopes tomorrow. The cold snap is
expected to last at least until Hogmanay.
Meanwhile, insurers are warning skiers who suffer injury on the slopes abroad
that they could face soaring hospital bills.
The cost of treating ski injuries at top winter sports destinations is climbing
rapidly, said one travel insurance company.
Worst places to have a spill in the snow are Switzerland and America, while the
most frequent types of ski injuries are to the soft tissues of the lower limbs.
``The cost of medical care in ski resorts is racing away, leaving behind a lot
of skiers who are seriously out of pocket,'' said Ms Sarah Joannides, marketing
manager for the insurance company, Home and Overseas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Harkess fights to keep speedway dream alive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIGEL DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667826</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SPEEDWAY:
ALEX Harkess was born an optimist and it is this quality that is being tested
to the full as he fights to keep speedway alive in Edinburgh.
Monarchs' co-promoter makes car number plates by day, and by night attempts to
figure out how to work a miracle. For the axe hangs over their traditional home
at Powderhall Stadium, which once used to ring to the cheers of up to 11,000
fans as the kings of two-stroke careered around the shale track at speeds of up
to 60mph.
Those heady days are long gone. Last season, crowds averaged around 1200 for
Friday race nights and the English-based businessmen who now own the 10-acre
site want to turn it into housing and offices.
Monarchs entertained arch Scottish rivals Glasgow Tigers in a Premier League
derby - billed as the Farewell to Powderhall meeting - last October and the
famous Edinburgh club are set to become homeless after 19 years at the track.
If the lights go out it could bring the curtain down on a capital sporting
tradition which stretches back to 1928.
But so many objections have been received to the plans that the issue will not
now come up before Edinburgh District Council planners until next month - a
delay forced by the weight of public opinion and paperwork, and a delay which
increases the anxiety of the club's chiefs.
Naturally, Harkess is delighted that more than 1000 objections have been backed
by a 10,000 signature petition but the extension has caught him between the
rock and the hard place. For he has been forced to kick-start team-building so
as not to be left at the tapes if Monarchs are allowed another year at
Powderhall, or talks for a new site on the capital's outer-city by-pass bear
fruit.
Last night Harkess revealed: ``We couldn't wait any longer to start talking to
riders. If we had, they could be gone and we would have been left with nothing.
``Certainly, the weight of public opinion is a boost but it's a double-edged
sword. We won't know what's happening until mid-January and we'll have to get
things sorted out, otherwise we won't have a team to race with.
``It's a difficult situation but you've got to look positively at things and
the solicitors for the new owners say that if there is a planning delay then
they'll look at speedway at Powderhall for another season.''
Harkess, who has been involved with the shale sport for more years than he
cares to remember, said: ``Sure, it will be a major blow if we go to all the
trouble of fixing a team and find we have nowhere to race but we can't sit
around waiting. We've got to get out and do something.
``Everybody connected to the club is pleased that so many people have come out
and supported the Hands Off Powderhall move. Some of these people are greyhound
racing fans, but many also support speedway.''
Edinburgh's speedway heritage goes back almost 70 years. Portobello's Marine
Gardens housed the first meeting. Now, it's a garage and diesel fumes from the
city's bus fleet filter forth instead of the intoxicating two-stroke mixture.
Never-say-die speedway fans uprooted in 1948 to Meadowbank, where around 25,000
people crammed the terracings as Britain got back to normal after the Second
World War.
Meadowbank still houses sport but now it's the human variety rather than
mechanical version which rules at the Commonwealth Stadium, the home of the
1970 and 1986 Comonwealth Games.
Powderhall revved up for its first meeting in 1977 and the arena, once also
Scotland's No.1 greyhound racing venue, has been its permanent home ever since,
even staging the wedding of one of its former favourite sons one rainswept
night.
Last night, the defiant Monarchs' chairman refused to admit defeat and said:
``We will not allow the club to die. One option is at the Royal Highland
Showground at Ingliston on the western outskirts of Edinburgh and, to be fair
to them, they've always said that they could not accomodate us until 1997, when
they will have completed their new showground.
``Another is a new site on the city boundary near the by-pass but I can't say
any more about that at the moment.''
Ironically, the curtain could come down as Monarchs are riding high in the top
10 of the Premier League, their highest standing in British speedway for years.
Monarchs are unbeaten at home in the country's elite league from early May, and
their results on the road last season exceeded expectations.
The pulse still beats strongly even though they might be running out of road
and Harkess said: ``Our crowds might average around 1200 but thousands more are
still interested in speedway, and preserving it as a spectator sport in the
city. We're not buried yet, not by a long way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheik buys  contents of store</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667827</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SALE-happy sheik bought a store's entire contents for #350,000 yesterday to
please his third wife. Everything from furnishings shop Charlotte's at London's
Marble Arch - including the wallpaper - will now be shipped to Dubai in the
Arab Emirates.
The sheik, a member of the Qatar ruling family, will use his purchases to
recreate the store in his own shopping     centre. Mr Martin Barnett, owner of
the soft furnishings and embroidery centre, said: ``The sheik came in with his
entourage after seeing the sale signs up. He thought the shop was for sale but
I told him it wasn't. He bought nine sofas and then asked me how much for the
whole lot.
``Apparently, his third wife had been in during the summer and he said she
liked the concept. He owns the equivalent of Brent Cross from what I can make
out. He gave me some cash and later I received a fax from his bank and a cheque
for the remainder of the deposit.
``There was a crowd of people waiting for my sale to start and everyone was
astonished. Now I will have to find new stock.''
Mr Barnett said the Arab, who lives in Dubai, had asked for his identity to be
kept secret.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess off for sun and sea, minus sons</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667828</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales and a female companion were on their way from ice-bound
Britain to the Caribbean last night as her two sons continued to spend the
Christmas break with their father.
Her departure has ended speculation over whether she would choose a skiing or
beach holiday to follow her home-alone Christmas at Kensington Palace.
The British West Indian Airways International plane was heading for Antigua in
the Leeward Islands. There was no confirmation of which island the princess had
chosen, but speculation centred on Nevis, a small island a 20-minute plane ride
from Antigua.
The princess visited Nevis three years ago, within weeks of the announcement of
her official separation from Prince Charles.
On that occasion she was with Princes William and Harry but this time she
decided to leave them with their father for both Christmas and New Year.
Under the terms of agreement between the prince and princess in the wake of
their separation, the boys share their holidays between their parents.
It was the princess's turn to have the boys for Christmas this year but she
announced that she wanted them to join in the traditional royal family
Christmas at Sandringham in Norfolk. At first she said she would be there too,
but later changed her mind.
She is reported to have had a cold Christmas lunch, left for her by staff who
had been given the holiday off.
On Boxing Day, Diana spent more than an hour visiting her bulimia therapist, Ms
Susie Orbach, according to the Sun and the Daily Mirror.
Both had pictures of her smiling as she left the 49-year-old feminist writer,
who had counselled her about her problems with the eating disorder several
years ago.
Diana was also reported to have visited the clinic, at Ms Orbach's home in
north-west London, on Christmas Eve.
Meanwhile, Princes William and Harry spent yesterday pheasant shooting with
their father, and their grandfather, the Duke of Edinburgh.
At the weekend they are due to leave Britain with their father, bound for his
favourite ski resort, Klosters.
Yesterday a palace official said she had no information about the princess's
Caribbean trip.
``All holiday arrangements are private and they are not something we give any
guidance on,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tables are turned on Argentine judges for wild party</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667829</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Buenos Aires
TEN high-spirited judges, including one investigating the bombing of a Jewish
centre in 1994, were fined today over a wild Christmas party held at a
courthouse, an Argentine court tribunal president said.
Juan Jose Galeano was one of 10 federal judges fined one third of their monthly
salary for conduct inappropriate to the rank of magistrate, Judge Horacio Raul
Vigliani told Reuters.
``(This is) the maximum penalty the tribunal can apply,'' Vigliani said.
Galeano is famous in Argentina for leading the investigation into a
still-unresolved bomb attack against the Buenos Aires Amia Jewish community
centre, which killed 86 people in July 1994.
Another high-profile judge, Adolfo Bagnasco, who is investigating alleged
corruption over a $250m contract awarded by the state-owned Banco Nacion to
computer firm IBM, was also among those fined, Vigliani said.
More than 100 judges and court workers attended the party last Friday in a
Buenos Aires courthouse where revels included squirting fire extinguishers,
local media reported.
Complaints were made about loud music and howling sounds coming from the
courthouse. Legal employees fled down staircases when another judge,
accompanied by police, tried to restore decorum.
The judge was sworn at and one of his colleagues tried to punch him, according
to local media reports.
The tribunal said the judges had given ``laconic'' and ``evasive'' replies to
questioning over the incident.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arctic weather brings road crashes in the ice and death by hypothermia Freeze takes its toll</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON, CHRIS STARRS, LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667830</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE freezing weather yesterday claimed five lives, including two children and
two teenagers. An Ayrshire boy died from hypothermia, a teenage girl was killed
in a car crash in Renfrewshire, and doctors lost a battle to resuscitate a man
who had been trapped for 30 minutes under ice in a lake.
John Colquhoun, 16, of Barbieston Avenue, Drongan, and a friend had abandoned a
car which had left the road at 3am on Christmas Day.
John set off in shirt sleeves on his own to walk the four miles home, but
travelled only half the distance. His friend, who had been driving, had set off
in another direction.
The Colquhoun family contacted the police after hearing a radio report about
the discovery of a body.
John's sister Mandy, 19, said last night: ``On Christmas Day dad was preparing
Christmas dinner. We got worried when John wasn't home by noon.
``Then we heard on the radio that a body had been found near Mauchline. It all
happened very quickly after that.''
Miss Michelle Anderson, 18, of Burnside Road, Elderslie, died and a 19-year-old
youth was seriously injured yesterday when their car hit a lamppost on the
Johnstone bypass, near the St James interchange, Paisley.
Driver John Watson, of Willow Avenue, Elderslie, was taken to Glasgow's
Southern General Hospital where he was described as ``critical''.
Two children died and their three brothers and sisters were injured when a
lorry collided with their stationary car on a dual carriageway near Easington,
County Durham.
The youngsters who died were Oliver Stephen Docx, 15, and four-year-old
Alexandra. Hannah, 10, was seriously injured; Samuel, 17, suffered bruising;
and Stephen, 13, a leg injury. Their parents, Stephen, 43, and Joanna, 42, of
Heaton, Newcastle upon Tyne, were treated for severe shock.
Shetland's Coastguard helicopter took five patients for emergency treatment.
A nine-year-old boy had suffered convulsions. He was picked up from his home at
Dunrossness and taken to Clickimin emergency landing strip, Lerwick, at 9pm
where an ambulance was waiting to take him to hospital.
The helicopter then went to Sumburgh airport to take four seriously ill
patients from Gilbert Bain Hospital to Aberdeen. The mission was the twelfth
for the Bristows-operated Shetland helicopter in two days.
A major police hunt involving a helicopter and police dogs was under way last
night for a man seen wandering wearing little more than pyjamas in East
Kilbride.
Police Inspector Caroline Scott said: ``Our concern is growing as time goes by.
Anyone spending the night in the open in such clothing may well be dead by
morning because of the extreme cold.''
The man wearing striped pyjamas and either a sweater or dressing gown was first
seen at lunchtime leaving the grounds of Hairmyres Hospital.
Although a check with the hospital revealed no patients were missing, he was
later spotted by two motorists crossing the town's Eaglesham Road, heading
towards the local railway station.
Police, who had received no missing person report, were about to call off the
search as darkness fell but the man was spotted again in Peel Park, half a mile
from the hospital. Policemen with dogs combed the area, but found no sign of
him.
They appealed to local taxi firms, bus companies, ScotRail and local publicans
to keep a lookout for the man and urged members of the public to check on
vulnerable relatives.
A medical team last night lost a fight to bring back from the dead a man who
dived into an ice-covered lake to save his dog.
Mr Robert Giles, 25, of Andover, Hampshire, was officially pronounced dead
after being trapped under the surface for more than 30 minutes before rescuers
pulled him to safety.
Then doctors realised his body temperature had plunged to just 18 degrees -
less than half the normal human temperature - slowing his heart and other
organs. This drastically reduced oxygen requirements, meaning there was a
chance Mr Giles could be revived.
The medical team immediately went into action again, and at first thought they
had saved Mr Giles, but his condition deteriorated and he died.
The incident took place at
Continued on Page 2
CRAIG WATSON,
CHRIS STARRS,
LACHIE KENNEDY
Continued from page 1
Anton Lake in King Arthur's Way, where Mr Giles and his West Highland Terrier
were out for a run.
Inspector David Waller, spokesman for Andover police, paid tribute to the
bravery of a member of the local coastguard rescue team and Detective Constable
Tony Hewitt, a diving enthusiast, who rescued Mr Giles from the lake.
Mr Giles had thrown a stick for his dog which ran on to the two-inch thick ice
to retrieve it. The dog slipped beneath the surface as the ice cracked.
``The dog owner ventured on to the ice to try to rescue his pet but fell in and
disappeared beneath the frozen water,'' said Mr Waller. ``He was seen to
disappear by a member of the public who raised the alarm and a call for help
went out.''
Firefighters arrived but did not have the equipment to wade out into the water.
Mr Hewitt, a member of Andover sub-aqua team, heard the radio call and ran home
to get some equipment.
Mr Waller explained how the diver and a coastguard found the man on the bottom
of the lake.
``The man was not breathing and appeared to be dead,'' he added. ``He had been
under the water for the best part of 30 minutes. Ambulancemen gave him
resuscitation and he was then airlifted from the banks of the lake to
hospital.''
The dog managed to scramble out of the water to safety.
Doctors in the intensive care unit at the Royal Hampshire County Hospital in
Winchester battled to revive Mr Giles. A hospital spokesman said: ``Because of
the man's body temperature we believed there was a chance we would be able to
revive him and therefore continued to resuscitate him for some time.''
Residents living near the lake said two other dog walkers had drowned there in
recent years.
The man who fell through ice at Threipmuir Reservoir, Balnerno, on Christmas
Eve was last night said to be ``critical but stable''.
Mr Fraser Millar, 29, of Bughtlin Park, Corstorphine, Edinburgh, was detained
in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary. He had been trapped for an hour in the reservoir
after ice gave way under him as he was trying to rescue his dog.
Two Hydro-Electric linesmen managed to restore power to the island of Bressay
after struggling through deep drifts. After the supply was reconnected to the
remaining five houses, which had been blacked out for 79 hours, they had to
back their van for two miles on snow-packed roads.
Last night the P &amp; O cargo ferry diverted from a planned shipyard visit for her
annual refit and sailed from Aberdeen to Shetland with supplies of gas
cannisters.
Staff from the island Calor gas depot, on a hill outside Lerwick, were flown by
helicopter from their snowbound homes on the west side of Shetland.
British Gas engineers also struggled to cope with a huge backlog of calls all
over the country from people left without heating or hot water after their
central heating systems broke down.
The transport system throughout Scotland was in chaos. Rail passengers in the
central belt faced long delays after trains froze to tracks in depots and
others suffered mechanical breakdowns caused by ice and freezing pipes.
Scottish Office Minister George Kynoch said the Government was monitoring the
situation in Shetland closely and was ready to call in the military if
necessary. However, he had been told by Shetland Islands Council that the
situation was under control.
RAC members asking for help at home faced delays of up to 11 hours, while AA
Home Start members were kept waiting for up to four hours. Both organisations
called in all available staff to take telephone calls and attend roadside
breakdowns, which were treated as priorities.
The AA had 150 outstanding calls in Glasgow yesterday morning from people who
had called the night before. Taxis were despatched by both organisations to
take people to work or home, but anyone whose car would not start was advised
to sit tight at home if possible.
The RAC said it had received 5000 calls yesterday, up 250%.
Frozen rolling stock prompted Railtrack and ScotRail to reduce most train
services in Strathclyde to hourly departures. ScotRail staff were last night
working on an emergency cold weather timetable for today.
There were severe delays in the Aberdeen area after two trains blocked the main
line into the city from the south. Commuters and shoppers going home from
Glasgow faced delays of two to three hours on most routes last night.
The Glasgow to Edinburgh route was today due to be continued on an hourly basis
instead of half-hourly, with trains leaving Glasgow on the hour.
ScotRail has opened a recorded information line on 0141 226 4023.
ScottishPower reported a 25% increase in demand for electricity yesterday.
</TEXT>
