<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prescott challenges Tories to stay put</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667831</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR deputy leader John Prescott yesterday reminded 16 Tory MPs - rumoured to
be thinking of joining the ``chicken run'' to safer seats - of the loyalty they
owed to their constituents.
He warned voters in the 16 seats to be on ``chicken alert'' - to watch whether
their sitting Tory MP deserted them as the General Election drew near.
Mr Prescott challenged the 16 Tories, including Scottish Secretary Ian Lang,
Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley, and Transport Minister John Watts, to
give an undertaking they would stand as the Tory candidate in the seats for
which they were elected.
Ten Tories have already switched to safer seats, including Tory party chairman
Dr Brian Mawhinney and Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell.
Some of the 16, and the 10 who have already switched, are doing or have done so
because their seats are subject to boundary changes.
So far 50 Tory MPs have announced they will either retire or leave the Commons
at the next election.
Mr Prescott said: ``Voters prefer loyal and long-standing MPs and that
incumbency factor is worth thousands of votes. It means the new Tory candidates
in those seats will have an even harder time holding them.
``These chicken-run Tories are giving John Major a double helping of stuffing -
admitting they expect to lose the seats and making it even more likely in the
process.''
</TEXT>
