<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Family are devastated by tragic end to 16-year-old's Christmas night out Youth freezes to death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667832</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SIXTEEN-year-old Ayrshire youth died from hypothermia on Christmas Day after
abandoning a car and trying to walk four miles home early in the morning.
John Colquhoun, of Barbieston Avenue, Drongan, was a fit and healthy young man
and a keen footballer who had won a number of trophies and trained with Ayr
United. There was talk of him joining Rangers Boys' Club, the family said.
His family said last night they were shocked and devastated by the tragedy.
John had been out with friends at a Christmas Eve disco. He and another friend
visited friends after the party and eventually headed home via Mauchline. But
at 3am their car slipped off the road in the icy conditions and ended up in a
ditch.
The two friends decided to walk different routes home. John, who was said to
have been wearing just a shirt, walked two of the four miles to his house
before stopping. He had been drinking and it is thought he might have stopped
to rest and fallen asleep.
His family became more worried about him on Christmas Day. They contacted
police after hearing a radio report about a body being found near their home.
His sister Mandy, 19, a VDU operator in Ayr, said last night: ``My mum is very
upset and we are all shocked.
``On Christmas Day dad was preparing Christmas dinner. We got worried when John
wasn't home by noon. Then we heard on the radio that a body had been found near
Mauchline. It all happened very quickly after that.
``John had been hyper about going out on Christmas Eve. He was 16 and this was
his first real Christmas out.''
Mandy said John had been drinking and that he had maybe fallen asleep after
taking a rest at the roadside. She said: ``The cold has just got him.''
John, who had started working as an apprentice roofer in Drongan four weeks
ago, had two other teenage sisters, Lorna and Tracy, and a 22-year-old brother,
Robert.
His mother Elizabeth, 39, and father John, 41, both unemployed, were distraught
last night.
Friend Kirsty Broadfoot, 19, said: ``He was a good fun-loving person who always
enjoyed a laugh. He had a lot of friends in the village. Everyone knew his
face.''
Kirsty, sister of John's girlfriend Kim, said the two had been going out
together for a year and had known each other since primary school.
The Broadfoots were fellow schoolmates of John at Auchinleck Academy.
A post-mortem examination was held yesterday and his father also identified the
body.
Strathclyde Police said the public should take suitable precautions against the
cold.
They said John had been taken to Ayr Hospital where he was found to be dead.
There are no suspicious circumstances and a report has been submitted to the
procurator-fiscal.
The funeral is due to be held at Shaw Kirk on Saturday.
</TEXT>
