<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lifeboat delivers urgent supplies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667833</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHETLAND lifeboat was pressed into service yesterday to carry coal, milk and
bottled gas to snowbound villages.
The lifeboat Snolda, based at Aith on the west coast of the islands, was making
a 140-mile return trip to Lerwick.
Lifeboat secretary Alan Norris said coxswain Hilton Henry and his five-man crew
were calling at the isolated villages of Walls, Brindister and West Burrafirth
on the return journey last night.
Three families in Brindister had run out of food and were to collect emergency
rations from the lifeboat. Bottled gas was urgently needed for the old people's
sheltered housing in Walls and Aith, which had been cut off from the rest of
Shetland since Christmas Eve.
The lifeboat is due to visit Clousta and the island of Papa Stour today with
supplies.
The day dawned sunny and calm over much of Shetland - ideal weather for a three
helicopters to fly Hydro-Electric engineers and replacement power poles to
isolated areas.
Power was restored to all but 375 houses.
Three people were airlifted to the Gilbert Bain Hospital in Lerwick with
suspected hypothermia, although one case was a false alarm.
All main roads were passable, but only by four-wheel drive vehicles and the
ferries were managing to run a skeleton service.
All scheduled flights to and from the islands remained cancelled.
Meanwhile, more than 150 British Airways passengers were given an unexpected
sail yesterday after snow and ice closed Stornoway airport on Lewis.
The airline chartered Caledonian Macbrayne's newest ferry, the Isle of Lewis,
to make an extra sailing from Stornoway to Ullapool where a fleet of buses had
been laid on to take the passengers to Inverness or Glasgow.
The passengers included Western Isles MP Calum Macdonald and his colleague from
Cunninghame North, Mr Brian Wilson.
In the Western Isles all main roads were open but there were 90 engineers
working trying to restore power to 584 customers.
The 220 customers on the island of Berneray were reconnected in the middle of
the afternoon. The major remaining fault was at Uig on the west of Lewis but it
was hoped to have it repaired last night.
</TEXT>
