<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Security-camera system could close as Lally says new authority might not meet cost Business fails to back City Watch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW'S City Watch closed-circuit television cameras, credited with cutting
crime and making the city centre safer, could face a financial crisis in the
spring.
Of the estimated 2000 businesses covered by the cameras only 250 have forked
out to help with the system's running costs of around #250,000 a year. Among
the non-payers are some of Britain's biggest high street names and several of
Glasgow's flagship companies.
The initial cost of City Watch was #1.1m, including CCTVS, fibre-optic ducting,
monitoring equipment at Stewart Street Police Station, and employment of 14
observers. Funding runs out in March, leaving City Watch, the charity which
owns and runs the system, facing possible closure unless the local authorities
come to the rescue.
Negotiations are in progress with the new Glasgow Council, Glasgow Development
Agency and others to secure the system's future. City Watch is also approaching
Strathclyde Police and the procurator-fiscal's department to raise funds.
Glasgow's CCTV system has won widespread acclaim, despite question marks over
whether such systems cut crime or merely displace it.
The Home Office, its Local Government Information Unit, and the Scottish Office
have all praised the system. Glasgow's code of conduct, designed to meet civil
liberties' misgivings, is set to form the basis of a national code for the UK.
Retiring Chief Constable Leslie Sharp of Strathclyde Police, who created the
code of practice, has been enthusiastic about the Glasgow system, emphasising
how it has allowed his officers to observe incidents as they happen.
He is convinced it has made the city centre safer for everyone.
Councillor Pat Lally, leader of Glasgow District Council's Labour
administration and planning convener of the new Glasgow Council, yesterday
agreed with The Herald that it might finally fall to the new council to pick up
the tab for the CCTV system.
``I am afraid that these things always seem to end up with us. It is a fact of
life. We all extol the fruits of partnership but there are times when I despair
of the commitment of commercial community, particularly in the city centre and
particularly for matters such as this,'' he said.
In the last two years the district council had offered additional resources to
promote the city centre at Christmas provided the business community also
responded. But, said Councillor Lally, members of the business community had
not taken up the offer.
``There seems to be a tendency to regard partnership as a good idea as long as
they do not have to contribute,'' said Councillor Lally, ``but it does not work
that way.''
It was not a foregone conclusion, he added, that the new Glasgow Council would
pay to keep the system running.
``We are entering a period when local government is being squeezed by central
government. Resources are going to be very thin on the ground. Apart from the
public at large the major beneficiaries are the business community so it is
regrettable that some of them regard the cameras as a present from Santa
Claus,'' he said.
The new city council faced the possibility of compulsory redundancies among
staff, meaning that the Glasgow CCTV system might be regarded as a luxury.
``CCTV is an additional burden which may be placed on us and we are not sure
that we will be able to carry it. At present we are simply unable to commit
ourselves but it would be a tragedy if the cameras were lost,'' Councillor
Lally said.
City Watch manager David McKay said yesterday that it had made intensive
efforts to persuade business to contribute.
``Some have given very well but many of the major companies say to us that they
are not empowered to contribute, that it is a decision for their head offices
in London. When we ask them they say it is a policy matter not to contribute
because if they gave to Glasgow they would have to give to every city-centre
scheme in Britain where they have outlets.
``But we have reached an important point where it has to be acknowledged that
these schemes are going to increase tenfold. Everyone is going to be looking to
the local authorities and asking them to fund the running costs. We have had a
12% response from Argyle Street, which is more or less typical of the city
centre as a whole.
``Yet in Aberdeen the traders alone have contributed #240,000 to start a
scheme. Glasgow is being parsimonious at a time when phenomenal sums are being
made in retail turnover in the city centre,'' Mr McKay said.
Mr Bill Neish, general manager of Marks and Spencer, which has contributed
substantially, said that one excuse offered by others was that their heavy
business rates should help provide a safe ambience in the city centre,
including the cameras.
``Perhaps it is time to include a security element in the business rates
collected by the city and to ring-fence that element for cameras,'' he said.
</TEXT>
