<DOCNO>GH951228-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ministers urged to change system Cold weather cash scheme under attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667836</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government came under renewed pressure last night to change its system for
making cold weather payments through the Social Security scheme as Scotland
continued to freeze.
The Department of Social Security said that cold weather payments to people in
large parts of the country had been triggered by the Arctic weather and would
be received within days.
However, Opposition MPs, many of whom were freezing with their constituents in
some of the worst weather conditions Scotland has seen for 40 years, said the
Government action was not enough.
The DSS said it had made weather checks with the Meteorological Office and the
payments - of #8.50 a week - would be made across much of the country. A
spokesman said: ``The Met Office say they now anticipate cold weather payments
have been triggered in a large number of areas.''
Details of temperatures nationwide are fed to the DSS by a network of 55
weather stations. Payments are made locally, depending on weather reports for
each area, but are triggered automatically when temperatures fall or are
predicted to fall to freezing or below for a seven-day period in a specific
area.
They are only paid to three groups - income support families with children
under five; the disabled and long-term sick; and pensioners.
For Labour, Mr George Foulkes, MP for Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley, and a
former director of Age Concern Scotland, said: ``The weather is so severe that
there ought to be some consideration about a double premium for when it gets
below -10C.''
His Labour colleague, Mr David Winnick (Walsall North), said: ``The Prime
Minister should intervene to authorise payments in all areas of the country.
The weather is sufficiently harsh, and therefore these payments are certainly
justified, modest as they are. It is also unfortunate that anyone just above
the level of income support won't be receiving a penny.''
Scottish Liberal Democrats' leader Jim Wallace, speaking from snow-bound
Kirkwall, said he was concerned about a system whereby one geographical area
might qualify for help on the basis of a forecast while another would not.
He said he would be raising the matter in correspondence with Ministers and on
the floor of the House when the Commons resumed, adding: ``The drawback of the
present formula is that it leads to uncertainty over whether people will
qualify or not. I am concerned there will be a number of cases where people
still do not know whether they can afford to heat their homes.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said there should be an automatic payment to vulnerable
groups for the winter months, and he claimed there would have been uproar if
Whitehall had been without electricity for three or four days. He joined the
queue of those pledged to raise the issue with Ministers when the House returns
after the Christmas recess.
For the Government, Social Security Minister Andrew Mitchell promised that the
cold weather payments scheme would be kept under review.
He told BBC Radio 4's Today programme: ``The Government recognises that hearing
a Government Minister talking about cold weather payments when you have
temperatures of -15C in the north of Scotland can be rather irritating for
those who are battling against those conditions and we do recognise the
importance of an annual review.''
Pressed about situations where the weather had been cold for a prolonged period
but did not meet the Government criteria exactly, he said: ``We have to take a
prudent view. These payments are meant to deal with very severe weather.
``Normal heating costs are met already by income support, so these special
payments deal with exceptional circumstances and we have to take a prudent view
as to what is the right use of taxpayers' money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nan Whyte</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nan Whyte, violinist and teacher; born May 4, 1922, died December 24, 1995
NAN WHYTE, one of Ayrshire's best-known musicians and a leading light in the
women's Burns movement, died peacefully after a short illness at Crosshouse
Hospital on Christmas Eve, aged 73.
Originally from the Riccarton area of Kilmarnock, she moved to Irvine when the
Caldwell family took over the town's Eglinton Arms Hotel in 1959, and for many
years helped in the day-to-day running of the hotel with her brother Joe.
She quickly became prominent in many of the town's affairs and was, with Anne
Gaw, a founding member of Irvine Lasses' Burns Club. But although Burns was one
of Nan Whyte's great passions, her life revolved around her love of music.
After gaining her LRAM and an MA in English and history at Glasgow University
in the same year, she taught her academic subjects in Kilmarnock. However, she
also continued studying the violin with the celebrated Max Rostall and Alfredo
Campoli and was persuaded to join the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra by its
founder-conductor Ian Whyte. Through him she met and married his son, Don, who
worked with the Scottish Daily Express. The couple had three children.
After her playing days, she taught history and English at Irvine Royal and
Kilwinning Academies, and eventually became a peripatetic music teacher to a
group of Ayrshire schools. She continued to give private lessons up to the time
of her death, but she took most pleasure from striking up a tune at family
gatherings, or accompanying generations of youngsters who took part in
recitations at Irvine Burns Club.
Nan Whyte was also a leading figure behind the Scottish National Youth
Orchestra, and every year travelled to St Andrews and other locations where she
worked with the cream of the country's young musical talent as they prepared
for their annual concert.
She is survived by her children, Iain, Stewart, and Eileen, and grandchildren.
A service will take place on Tuesday at Irvine Old Parish Church (1.45pm) -
when some 20 of her musician colleagues will play in her memory - and the
funeral will follow at Masonhill Crematorium, Ayr (3pm).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Winning start for holders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOCKEY
JOHN Christie, the Insights Menzieshill captain and sharpshooter, last night
drew a blank when the Dundee side began the defence of the trophy in their own
international invitation indoor tournament at the city's Dick McTaggart Sports
Centre but Kevin Squire was on hand to get them off to a winning start.
The former Scottish under-21 internationalist scored four goals in a 9-3 defeat
of Bett Inns, after having hit he target three times in the opening eight
minutes.
Bett Inns got themselves back into the game with two goals from Neil Devine and
Graham Storrie but this merely prompted Menzieshill to lift their game and by
half-time they had restored their three-goal advantage with strikes by Kenny
Stibbles and Gary Cosgrove.
In the second half, Menzieshill were put under little pressure and they did
just enough to stretch their winning margin to six goals.
Torbrex Wanderers completed a double for the Taysiders when they saw off the
challenge from North American touring side Dita Travellers. The Dundonians ran
out 11-6 winners with Ian Strachan, Paul Dailly, and Steve Gellatly all scoring
hat tricks.
A third Scottish first-division side, Touche Ross Gordonians, lost out in their
confrontation with English champions Old Loughtonians. They were beaten 6-3 but
kept the pressure on the London side to the end. Results:
Insights Mezieshill 9, Bett Inns 3; Dita Travellers 6, Torbrex Wanderers 11;
Touche Ross Gordonians 3, Old Loughtonians 6.
</TEXT>
