<HEADLINE>Bargain hunt that brings out killer instinct</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667839</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anne Johnstone discovers how the sales season appeals to the same primitive
urges which were part of the psychology of Stone Age man, and woman
IF SUNDAY was the nightmare before Christmas, Boxing Day was surely the
nightmare after it. Most of the stores which bulged and groaned with Christmas
shoppers right up to close of play on Sunday, were back in business by
lunchtime on Boxing Day, bursting with equally fanatical bargain-hunters.
After losing the fight for the last snowsuit for a three-year-old in C&amp;A in the
Trongate, I mused ruefully on how my rugbyless female state school education
had left me miserably underqualified for the scrum of the Boxing Day sale
scene. I'd fared little better last week. So why do we do it? Are we mad? No,
more like temporarily deranged, according to Glasgow psychologist, Dr Prem
Misra.
Dr Misra says people can develop ``a transient obsession'' with a particular
item, believing it can somehow transform their lives for the better. The
longed-for object may be an electrical item or a piece of furniture but is more
likely to be clothing. ``In extreme circumstances the person obsessively
searches for the item and will go to great lengths to get it, including camping
out on the pavement in sub-zero temperatures,'' says Dr Misra.
When the store is about to open, their autonomic nervous system starts to
produce a rush of adrenalin. They begin to sweat and feel extremely alert even
if they're physically exhausted. Of course, if someone gets to the quarry
first, these feelings can turn into aggression. In other words, the
psychological armoury we use for shopping in the sales is exactly what our
Stone Age ancestors employed for hunting and fighting: the thrill of the chase.
John Davies, professor of psychology at Strathclyde University, says it's the
competitive element in us which drives us back out to the sales so soon after
Christmas. ``It's like a sport, where it's as important to win as to get the
object desired. There's a particular type who are drawn to them: the Attila the
Hun of sales. I'd probably class them as neurotic extroverts.''
Psychologically speaking, different impulses drive us into the shops before and
after Christmas, says Dr Misra. In the run-up to Christmas, he says, a ``siege
mentality'' develops in which people stock up with enough food to last weeks,
even though they know perfectly well that all the basics will be widely
available from Boxing Day onwards. It's an extension of our most basic human
instinct: survival. Hence the Bedlam-like scenes in M&amp;S foodhalls last weekend
with angry shoppers seizing items from each other's trolleys and stampedes to
snatch the final turkeys and mince pies from the shelves.
``People remember when the shops were closed for days, so they retain the
instinct to hoard. Also, this year there was a lot of anxiety about the weather
and fears that it could disrupt food supplies, as well as a lot of concern
about drinking and driving, so people imagined themselves marooned in their
homes for days,'' says Dr Misra.
A different kind of dementia infects the business of Christmas gift shopping,
something which afflicts women much more than men. Women shell out the lion's
share of the #7000m spent on Christmas gifts each year in Britain, and they
start shopping much earlier than men. However, generally they don't finish
earlier. They are just as likely as their men to be queueing at the last till
open at 5.35 on Christmas Eve. They're there clutching that last garland for
the mantle.
That's because many women suffer from a kind of ``Yuletide fantasy''. This is
the myth that there is such a thing as the perfect family Christmas, of the
type depicted in seasonal editions of women's magazines. They go to
extraordinary lengths to fix every last detail, every cashew nut, every gift
tag, every fairy light, in the desperate hope that if all the physical details
are right, they will somehow avoid the family tensions which so often erupt to
spoil the big day.
Ironically, of course, this merely adds to the tensions of Christmas, making a
conflagration all the more likely. More divorce proceedings are instituted
immediately after Christmas than at any other time of year.
But John Davies, an expert on addiction, dismisses the idea of
``Christmasaholics''. ``You've got to draw the line somewhere between what's
addictive behaviour and what isn't. The language of addiction used to be used
for hard drugs and not much more. Then it started spreading to soft drugs, then
things like chocolate and now even Christmas shopping. That's ridiculous. It's
just an excuse for people spending more than they should. As someone who likes
to be out of a shop three minutes after going in, I find it hard to
rationalise.''
While most women expect to enjoy Christmas shopping, most men don't even
pretend to. Few things throw up the difference between the genders more
sharply. While women join with friends and neighbours to make it a fun day out
and may try several stores before selecting the item they want, men prefer to
shop alone. Purposefully they walk into a store, make their choice and are out
again in two minutes, regardless of whether they've made the right choice, let
alone whether it's the right size.
Men's down-to-earth attitudes to seasonal shopping are reflected in a recent
survey, which showed that on a range of virtually identical items for men and
women, those for men were invariably cheaper. According to one psychologist,
women are often buying hope or a promise of glamour and this is reflected in
the price tag. This is the psychology which controls high margins in the
perfume market.
Such differences also explain why husband-and-wife shopping trips rarely work
and why salesmen have such a hard time trying to sell something to a couple
shopping together. Observer columnist Katharine Whitehorn recently suggested a
creche for husbands in every shopping centre.
Of course, even the most reluctant shopper gets there eventually. Dr Misra says
the last-minute shopper is under increasing pressure in the last couple of
weeks, bombarded with more and more images of Christmas, and a mounting tide of
advertising. The result, he says, is that items which nobody would dream of
buying during the rest of the year sell like hotcakes. Will 1995 be remembered
as the Christmas of the foot spa?
Finally, here is a message for the big woman with the sharp elbows who filched
that last toddler snowsuit: I hate you.
</TEXT>
