<HEADLINE>Construction bucks slowdown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667840</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rate of profits growth enjoyed by Scotland's leading companies has almost
halved in the past 12 months, according to a study published in next month's
Scottish Business Insider magazine.
Surprisingly, it was construction and development which bucked the slowdown,
with the major players achieving a 153% hike in combined profits.
This was largely a result of a turnaround in the fortunes of property
investment company Scottish Metropolitan, although this was based on figures
only for the year to August last year.
The recently-floated Morrison Construction Group increased its latest annual
profits by 50% to #7.63m. And Cala more than doubled its profits in the year to
June to #6.89m.
In spite of the slowdown in overall profits growth from 29% to 15% this year,
many of the big players are recording their best-ever absolute profit levels.
This is particularly true of banks, which together with the life and composite
insurers dominate the top 10 of the leading Scottish companies making up ``the
insider 500''.
And the rate of increase in dividends rose from 13% to 23%. Employee numbers
rose 5.2%.
Stakis and Gleneagles were ahead in the hotels and leisure sector and Dawson
International turned a #98m loss into a #1.7m profit in the year to March to
lead textiles.
Meanwhile, Brewer Scottish &amp; Newcastle - fresh from its #425m acquisition of
Courage from Fosters of Australia - increased its payroll by 7426.
Perth-based bus giant Stagecoach, expanding on to railways next year, took 5529
employees under its wing.
Royal Bank of Scotland added 3374 staff as its Direct Line insurance
diversified.
Stagecoach's rapid expansion allowed it to enjoy the largest profits hike among
companies with annual turnover of over #300m. Its top line increased by 77% to
#337m, with pre-tax profits up 72% to a record #32.6m in the year to end-April.
</TEXT>
