<HEADLINE>Director focuses on the closing credits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667841</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gus Macdonald is to relinquish the chair of Drambuie Edinburgh Film Festival.
Keith Bruce profiles the man who brought the event back into the black
THE question posed in this newspaper when Scottish Television managing director
Gus Macdonald was appointed chairman of the Drambuie Edinburgh Film Festival
was: ``Can he restore the festival's reputation?''
It was not the question at the top of Macdonald's mind. The champion of tabloid
television, who has drastically reduced the workforce at the station's
Cowcaddens HQ, maximised profitablity, defended Scottish from predators in the
new open market, and who tells me that ``a well-informed seven-year-old can
make a passable television documentary'', was more concerned with restoring the
festival's fortunes.
Quiet satisfaction is not something Macdonald indulges in. He's pretty upfront
about those things in which he takes pride and for which he expects credit. As
far as he is concerned, he has done the job at the DEFF and is moving on. He
has attended his last board meeting and relinquishes the chair at the end of
the year. Company secretary Glasgow lawyer Douglas McKerrall and the board
financial mind, Edinburgh accountant Michael Davidson, are searching for a
successor, and it will be a major surprise if that person is not from the world
of television.
Much concern was expressed among Scotland's cinema intelligentsia at the time
of Macdonald's appointment that TV executives were taking over the festival.
Sitting alongside him on the festival board were Steve Morrison from Granada,
Caroline Thomson from Channel 4, and John McCormick, controller of BBC
Scotland. Under Macdonald's regime, the board was slimmed down to a mere nine
souls, so the dominance of the television appointees was undeniable.
However, the misgivings failed to recognise the parallel dominance in the
funding of British film, with Channel 4 the largest movie producer in Europe.
If television has shown itself committed to the sustenance of a British film
industry, it has also proved useful to Edinburgh's festival.
Macdonald - who acknowledges the work done in sorting out the festival's
working structure by previous festival director Penny Thompson - says he wanted
``a board of heavyweights who can deliver support and leave the director and
producer to get on with their jobs''.
That has been achieved in a remarkably short time. A festival with a #150,000
deficit is now in the black and last year's event was a considerable popular
success.
On the funding side, Macdonald identifies three key meetings which changed the
festival's fortunes. Drambuie had been on the point of pulling out of their
sponsorship, but he persuaded then managing director Peter Derbyshire not only
to stay in but increase the commitment in cash and in kind to #200,000 a year -
in return for headline billing.
Lothian Region agreed to a substantial contribution to reduce the festival's
deficit, following a meeting with councillor Eric Milligan, and a chat with
Michael Grade produced more committed support from Channel 4, whose head of
film acquisition, Mhairi Mac-Donald, now sits on the DEFF board. Head of
corporate affairs at Scottish, Dave Whitton, joins on Macdonald's departure.
The new board can now be no more than 12 people, half its previous size, and
there is agreement that any member should resign when they leave the position
that led to their initial appointment. Edinburgh councillor and Filmhouse
chairman George Kerevan left under that rule.
When Macdonald says that he leaves the film festival in the black ``for the
first time in my memory'', he has considerable experience to call upon. He was
deputy chair between 1975 and 1984, and founding chairman of the television
festival in 1976. He still sees the television festival as the offspring of the
film event, something that was set up to demystify television and in no way a
threat to film.
He points to the transition made to the mid screen by directors like Mike (Four
Weddings) Newell. ``We had a slogan in the 70s that British film is alive and
well and it is called TV and we try to make sure there is an overlap, but we
don't want to see TV movies and there is a stubborn cultural difference between
the two.
``The last two years should have dispelled any doubts that we could be on the
point of turning the film festival into a television event. Why? We've already
got one.''
What the television contingent has brought to the festival, he contends, is a
sense of realism and a commercial base. He sees it as desirable that control of
the festival is not in the hands of the movie-making practitioners themselves,
when it becomes a vehicle for their frustrations. Besides, he adds, there is no
independent film-making sector to contest control.
``I hope we have taken it away from the cultish exclusivity of the film people
who take refuge in the theory and aesthetic of film without the industrial
reality,'' he says.
He sees change on the horizon and trusts the new generation personified in
Cousins and Atkinson to make the most of it. ``Penny was at the end of my
generation,'' he said. ``We need to give them the floor and let them dance.''
Advances in technology - and dramatic reductions in costs - are producing a
``wonderful confusion'' in visual story-telling, according to Macdonald.
``You don't have to be Noam Chomsky to know story-telling is innate but a small
country like Scotland couldn't afford to tell stories to itself, so you end up
looking glum and factual. The new economics will allow fiction to be made.''
Macdonald believes that it is in this area that television people have much to
learn from those in the film industry, and he is encouraging colleagues to come
to Edinburgh earlier than their own event in order to attend the film festival.
There is talk of a showcase of the top talent from both.
What of the future for the man himself? With the agreement of the May annual
general meeting he steps into Bill Brown's position as chairman of Scottish
Television at a time when the industry is in the throws of enormous change.
This more strategic role is consistent with his ambitions to expand the
company's interests into England.
Scottish has forged a number of ``alliances'', like that with Scottish Telecom,
that will see it moving into cable and narrowcasting. The company is working on
an association with Hallmark Entertainment in New York to make six children's
films over three years.
Then there are the implications of the Broadcasting Bill and the possibility of
future takeovers, about which Macdonald is prepared to say absolutely nothing,
unsurprisingly. Perhaps it is also unsurprising that he feels the time is right
to clear the decks of other commitments.
</TEXT>
