<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tomorrow's world on film</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667842</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.What lies ahead in '96? Here are some of the films you can look forward to
over the next four months.
JANUARY
Seven: a brilliant but very nasty film about a serial killer who bases each
crime on one of the Seven Deadly Sins. Morgan Freeman and Brad Pitt star as the
investigating cops. If you thought Silence of the Lambs gruesome, prepare to be
appalled.
Mute Witness: a very funny horror movie set in a Moscow film studio where the
mute props girl working on an American film gets locked in after hours and
finds the Russian crew are making snuff movies on the side. Can she be allowed
to live? There is a surprise guest star.
Heat: Robert de Niro and Al Pacino in a polished thriller about a cold
professional thief and the cop determined to catch him.
FEBRUARY
Les Miserables: the book, not the musical, reset in the present century and
starring Jean Paul Belmondo and pretty well everyone who is anybody in French
cinema.
Sabrina: a remake of the old Audrey Hepburn/Humphrey Bogart comedy with Julia
Ormond and Harrison Ford.
Loch Ness: the one they spent last year making about Nessie with Cheers star,
Ted Danson, giving it transatlantic box-office clout.
Sense and Sensibility: Emma Thompson's version of Jane Austen's novel directed
by Ang (Eat Man Drink Woman) Lee.
Casino: Martin Scorsese, Robert de Niro and Joe Pesci get to grips yet again
with the wise guys, this time in Las Vegas, with Sharon Stone as an alcoholic
slut. It seems the Mob run it no longer. Now the big corporations do. But who
runs them?
MARCH
Money Train: Woody Harrelson and Wesley Snipes rob the New York subway. The
film features a scene in which a cashier in a booth is torched with an aerosol,
which happened recently in reality provoking much anguish from the film-makers.
Beyond the Clouds: a collection of short stories directed by Michelangelo
Antonioni sensitively linked together by Wim Wenders. Rich in atmosphere, it
stars several of the loveliest young women in European cinema and John
Malkovitch. Antonioni is still one of the masters of the cinema.
Copycat: more serial killing, this time with Sigourney Weaver and Holly Hunter
doing the chasing. You have been here before, but the stars lend it the
necessary freshness.
Smoke: Wayne Wang's charming look at working-class New Yorkers centred on the
neighbourhood cigar store with Harvey Keitel in a rare sympathetic role.
Stockard Channing is stunning as a tart with a heart.
APRIL
Broken Arrow: John Travolta and Christian Slater star as Stealth bomber pilots,
once close friends, now deadly enemies, who are involved in one of those
no-holds- barred races against time to stop a nuclear weapon from being used
against an American city.
Nelly and Monsieur Armand: Emmanuelle Beart in a Claude Sautet film about a
loving friendship between an old man and a beautiful young woman.
Safe: The talented Julianne Moore as a woman who finds she is allergic to
today's world and ends up trapped in one of those sinister New Age centres.
</TEXT>
