<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First-class flyte for the bard</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Donny O'rourke</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
When academic minds join with Burns enthusiasts next month it's bound to be an
amazing event, says DONNY O'ROURKE.
WHATEVER isn't happening amid the recriminations surrounding the bi-centenary
of the Bard's demise, the world's biggest Burns Conference will take place at
the University of Strathclyde on January 11-13.
Every major authority on Burns will be in attendance. The poet's life and work
will be approached from just about every angle imaginable. Paticipants will
gather from all over the world to celebrate the poems and songs. And I do mean
celebrate.
These aren't the witterings of boring jargon-infected academics. The six
previous conferences have been notable for the entertaining elegance of the
presentations. Constructive controversy and down-to-earth accessible
scholarship have characterised the contributions.
It is to be hoped that Burns himself would thoroughly have enjoyed them. Who'd
pass up a talk entitled No More Potted Houghmagandie, even if the Gaelic poet
Aonghas Macneacil weren't giving it. Who wouldn't want to hear Tom Wright talk
about how John Cairney galloped away with Burns, after he'd written There Was a
Man.
The perspective of other writers, of those working in the media, in advertising
and tourism, of schoolteachers preparing pupils for the new Higher syllabus
(which includes Burns for the first time), of farmers, ministers, masons,
``ordinary'' readers of his work - all these will be on offer.
With biographies of Burns by Messrs McKay, MacIntyre and Bold to argue over, we
have never been in such firm, clear and stimulating possession of the facts.
First the writing: then the flyting. Good natured vituperation has always been
a feature of the proceedings. Facts may be ``chiels that winna' ding'' but
opinions flow fiercely.
A panel format ensure vigorous discussion among speakers. The seminar's theme
is then opened up to audience participation. The conference was dreamed up and
is run by Dr Ken Simpson, director of the Centre for Scottish Studies at
Strathclyde and himself an eminent critic of eighteenth-century Scottish
literature.
Since, from its inception in Glasgow's annus mirabilis 1990, the centre has
been committed to providing a public forum for the dissemination and discussion
of ideas, Dr Simpson is keen that members of the general public sign up for and
take an active part in the Burns event.
``Burns isn't just a Scottish phenomenon, he's a poet of world-class stature
and iconic significance who demands to be taken very seriously indeed. But this
conference is also fun.''
Simpson has assembled a team of participants, including J Ross Roy, Donald Low,
and Thomas Crawford, who are all scholars of long and distinguished standing in
Burns studies. Among the younger speakers are Liam McIlvanney, son of poet and
novelist William; and Kirsteen McCue, whose father is the singer Bill McCue.
Liam McIlvanney, a post-graduate student at Oxford, will discuss Burns and
religion; and Ms McCue, who is director of the Scottish Music Information
Centre, and completing a doctorial dissertation on Burns songs, will talk about
his songwriting.
Other highlights will include John Purser on the musical life of the period,
and Valentina Bold on images of Burns.
Sixty speakers will give papers. Most days' sessions will run in parallel so
that participants can choose one seminar from the three on offer. In this way
it is possible for everyone to compile their own personal programme - to
explore feminism and Burns, say, or specialise in the songs or nationalism, or
the satire.
``When Burns died in 1796, the whole town of Dumfries turned out to honour him.
`Who will be our poet now,' they asked? The conference affirms the importance
of Burns to all Scots. It aims to penetrate to the complex core of an immensely
talented poet, a poet of many and diverse voices.'' So Ken Simpson hopes.
Simpson is impatient with the hoary dichotomies of Burns scholarship. Rather
than set up a slanging match on Art Song vs Folk Song, for example, the
conference will examine the songs from both vantage points, scholar and singer
Adam McNaughton and his colleagues in the group Stramash will let us hear a
Burns who listened to and loved all the music available to him.
The Burns who will emerge from these three days of celebration and deliberation
will be as good a likeness to the real Robert Burns as we are entitled to
expect, given the poet's literary, political and psychological complexity.
And it is apt that Burns, the intellectual self-improver is being feted in the
bi-centenary of the institution that was to become Strathclyde University.
1796: a death and a birth - two centuries of useful learning indeed.
The whole event will be a kind of Burns supper writ large, a ceilidh of ideas.
But on the Friday evening there will be a real ceilidh with some of Scotland's
finest writers and singers, including Jo Miller, Tom Leonard, Carl McDougall,
Edwin Morgan, and McIlvanney pre. Iain Crichton Smith will premiere an
ambitious long poem in Burns's characteristic standard-habbie stanza form.
Tickets for the ceilidh and for the conference as a whole are still available.
There won't be a better Burns event in 1996.
</TEXT>
