<HEADLINE>Forte sells restaurants to Whitbread Granada attacks `modest' #1050m deal which is conditional on its #3300m takeover bid failing Main disposals by Forte</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667844</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORTE has decided on a fast track approach to becoming a purely mid to upper
market hotels company by selling its restaurants and the Travelodge budget
hotels to Whitbread for #1050m, conditional on a #3300m Granada bid failing.
The original plan was to demerge the restaurant business, which takes in Happy
Eater, Little Chef, Welcome Break motorway service areas and a similar motorway
service chain in France. Sir Rocco Forte, chairman, believes Whitbread is
offering a premium price.
``It is ahead of the values which the board considers would be created through
demerger and represents the best outcome for shareholders,'' he said.
Granada begged to differ, proclaiming that the price was ``modest'' and was tax
inefficient. Chief executive Gerry Robinson thundered: ``Forte's break-up plan
is an admission of its management's failure to obtain a reasonable return on
its assets.
``Shareholders should question whether it serves their interests to sell a
major part of the group in a hurry, at a time when it is performing badly,'' he
added.
With January 2 being the last date Forte can add new items to its defence,
further news will come out shortly, including a valuation of the hotels and a
dividend forecast, which could include a special payment following the sale to
Whitbread.
Since Forte announced the demerger plan early in December, it has received a
number of approaches for the restaurants.
Analysts suspected that Bass would also have looked at them, but Forte itself
considers Whitbread to be the obvious buyer, given its existing interests,
which include Pizza Hut, Beefeater and 1600 pubs, and expansionist aims in the
sector.
Sir Rocco noted: ``Whitbread is the best buyer, quite simply because it has the
best business fit so it can offer the best price and is not financially
constrained.''
The sale will almost eliminate Forte's gearing enabling it to develop its
remaining hotel brands, Posthouse, Heritage, Meridien and Exclusive, which
includes the Grosvenor House in London.
The chains to be sold made trading profits of #82m on sales of #590m in 1994/95
and Forte has already indicated that in the current year second half profits
would be below the comparable period.
The price represents an exit earnings multiple of 17 times, which Mr Robinson
noted was lower than similar quoted company shares were trading at and
represented no premium for control.
For its money, Whitbread would get 430 Little Chef and Happy Eater restaurants,
26 Welcome Breaks and 127 Travelodge hotels, which are closely associated with
the roadside restaurants. The group expects significant integration benefits.
Chief executive Peter Jarvis said: ``A major attraction to Whitbread is the
synergy which exists between our current businesses and those we are acquiring.
``The combination of activities will provide benefits in areas such as food
procurement and distribution, information systems and customer services,'' he
added.
Whitbread would develop branded restaurants and retail concepts within Welcome
Break and build on the French chain. The Travelodge hotels are a good fit with
Whitbread's Travel Inns. The group says the purchase would be earnings neutral
in the first year.
The deal would reduce Whitbread's brewing activity to a small proportion of the
total group, raising renewed speculation about its long-term future within the
group, which really sees itself as a retailer.
However it appears it wants to retain the business, which is strongly cash
generative, at least for the time being.
