<HEADLINE>Sparkling trading from Goldsmiths</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667845</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPARKLING Christmas has been had by Goldsmiths Group, Britain's leading
specialist retailer of up/mid-market jewellery and watches.
The month to Christmas Eve saw sales growth of 15.9% in total and 8.7% on a
like-for-like basis compared with those achieved in 1994. Sales for the 11
months to 24 December 1995 rose by 18.8% in total and 7.7% on a like-for-like
basis. Goldsmiths trades primarily under the Walker &amp; Hall and Goldsmiths name.
In looking for Christmas presents this year consumers generally appear to have
focused on quality rather than quantity. Clothing, household goods and
investment items such as silverware have proved popular.
Hugh Clark, trading policy director of the British Retail Consortium, which
represents over 90% of British retailers, said that overall Christmas had been
``a tough one but a reasonable one''. The trend towards shopping closer to 25
December itself continued, helped in England and Wales by official Sunday
opening by stores.
London stores also benefited from advantageous exchange rates with foreign
tourists snapping up British bargains, particularly designer clothing.
Food stores are thought to have traded particularly well with some superstores
having to close their doors to customers at times last Friday and Saturday
because of overcrowding and hour-long waits at the checkout. This despite the
fact that many stores were open on Saturday until 10pm and for several hours on
Sunday.
The strong Christmas trading may not compensate for a poor start to the autumn
season as unseasonably mild weather depressed clothing sales. However, the
traditional January sales have got off to a good start in amongst others Marks
&amp; Spencer, Debenhams, MFI and Selfridges.
Consumers are unlikely to have lost their desire for good value and so well
known brands of clothing and household goods will be snapped up at discounted
prices. Most retailers publish official statements on Christmas trading in
mid-January.
</TEXT>
