<HEADLINE>History takes a back seat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Following a year of movie disasters and the odd celluloid perfection,
William Russell takes a look back at the best and worst in cinema
THE year's end is a time to look back; a time for hurling brickbats and sending
bouquets; for giving the Willies, as my annual awards are known, to those who
have done good work. For the critic, it is that most thankless of tasks to
decide the 10 best films of the year - thankless because, invariably, one
leaves out those films people have enjoyed most and stands accused of elitism,
snobbishness, and generally not knowing what one is talking about.
However, the giving of pleasure does not necessarily mean something is any
good, only that it has given pleasure, which has nothing to do with taking a
critical view.
My film of the year is Il Postino, Michael Radford's moving account of the
friendship between a young Italian fisherman and the exiled Chilean poet, Pablo
Neruda (played by Philippe Noiret). Impeccably acted, written, filmed and
directed, it is as near perfection as it is possible to be, and should stand
the test of time. What makes the film so rewarding is that it is about how
friendship can liberate somebody trapped in an inhibiting environment, and how
people who offer friendship must also accept the responsibilities entailed.
Noiret is one of French cinema's finest actors, but the actor and comedian,
Massimo Troisi, who played the fisherman, Mario, relatively unknown outside his
native Italy, proves a revelation. An actor of immense distinction and patently
unplumbed potential, he died shortly after completing the film.
The trouble with picking a top 10 is that over the year I have seen nearly 200
films, not counting those at film festivals and, even being ruthless, it is
hard to whittle them down to 10. I ended up with a list of some two dozen
titles, most of which I was reluctant to discard.
There were also the ones I could not stand at any price. The two reviews which
provoked the most ire among readers were Rob Roy and Braveheart. Both films
treated history with contempt. There is no need to be totally faithful -
historical writing is something of a movable feast, the past being open to many
interpretations - and dramatic licence permits changes, but one must be true to
the spirit of events and neither bothered to do so.
In the case of Rob Roy, a costume drama with few pretensions other than to
entertain, although it did that only fitfully, the inaccuracies did not matter
greatly. The wooden performance from the leading man, Liam Neeson, did. But
Braveheart aspired to higher planes and the fact I dared suggest Emperor Gibson
had no clothes provoked the first anonymous abusive phone calls I have ever
received. That is worth reflecting upon.
There are always films which will receive no prizes in anybody's list, but
which are worth mentioning. Meryl Streep's successful foray into the world of
the adventure thriller, River Wild, is a case in point, as was Tony Scott's
masterly job in transforming a bunch of underwater cliches into a tense,
exciting tale in his film about a nuclear submarine, Crimson Tide.
It was a good year for the antipodean cinema with Le Tamahori's powerful, but
hysterical, Once Were Warriors, which dealt with the problems faced by Maoris
in present day New Zealand, P J Hogan's hilarious, but bleak black comedy,
Muriel's Wedding, and Peter Jackson's devastating tale of two teenage killers,
Heavenly Creatures.
Sophistication is rare these days in the cinema, but Fred Schepisi brought it
to the screen perfectly in his treatment of John Guare's play, Six Degrees of
Separation, which boasted fine work from Donald Sutherland - rare these days -
and Stockard Channing recreating her original role, as did Robert Redford with
his highly polished film, Quiz Show, in which Ralph Fiennes made a weakling
interesting while Paul Scofield created a believeable academic, a man of
integrity and intelligence.
It was a year for lavish costume dramas, apart from the two set in Scotland.
From France came the blood-drenched La Reine Margot, in which Virna Lisi did
the full Bette Davis as Catherine de Medici, while from British cinema came the
film director debut of the theatrical wunderkind, Nicholas Hytner, The Madness
of King George, in which Nigel Hawthorne gave the performance of a lifetime.
Over the span of a year, films released early can slip from memory which is why
I plough through my year's reviews, alhough even then things can go astray. Two
which must be mentioned are Lee's Eat Man, Drink Woman, which looked
perceptively at the relationship between an old man and his daughters, and
Burnt By The Sun, Nikita Mikhalkov's story about Stalin's purges in which the
smiles of a summer day turn into a nightmare.
Atom Egoyan's Exotica was a fascinating thriller, in hindsight the more so
because of the fuss due next year over Showgirls, an adult look at the bizarre
phenomenon of lap dancing. Two films worth seeing in tandem were Vanya on 42nd
Street, the late Louis Malle's last film, in which Chekhov's play is performed
under rehearsal conditions in a derelict New York theatre, and the evocative
Country Life directed by Michael Blakemore. Blakemore secured performances one
did not think capable from Sam Neil and Greta Scacchi, did a memorable turn
himself, and provided Kerry Fox with a role which suited her to perfection,
unlike the vamp in Shallow Grave. He translated the setting to Australia just
after the First World War giving the story fresh resonances which did not
detract from the original.
In the age of the Europudding, Ken Loach showed how to make a multi cultural
film with his Spanish civil war drama, Land and Freedom, although whether
anybody in Brussels, where the European script fund throws cash about, has
taken note is another matter. It may not make a star of Ian Hart, but the film
confirmed Loach's range is far greater than one imagined. Nor should one omit
mention of Goldeneye, directed by Martin Campbell, who breathed new life into
the corpse of the Bond series.
The year began with the hugely successful Scottish film, Shallow Grave. It will
be interesting to see whether the director, Danny Boyle, has managed that
fiendishly difficult trick and made a second film worthy of note when
Trainspotting arrives in the New Year. A clutch of young British actors and
directors also made their mark, and with luck more will be heard of Georgina
Cates (An Awfully Big Adventure), Kate Winslett (Heavenly Creatures), Hugh
O'Connor, star, and Benjamin Ross, director (The Young Poisoner's Handbook),
Linus Roach (Priest) and Minnie Driver (Circle of Friends).
Four Rooms was the last film released in 1995. It opened on Boxing Day and
should have closed on Boxing Day. It comprises four stories set in different
rooms of the same hotel on New Year's eve, directed by Allison Anders,
Alexandre Rockwell, Robert Ridroguez and Quentin Tarantino which explodes the
myth that any of them have talent, other than for obscenities and incompetence.
FILMS OF THE YEAR
Il Postino
The Madness of King George
Six Degrees of Separation
Burnt By the Sun
Land and Freedom
Once Were Warriors
Country Life
Vanya on 42nd Street
The Bridges of Madison County
Eat Drink Man Woman
Heavenly Creatures
ROLL OF HONOUR
Best Actor
Tie: Massimo Troisi and Nigel Hawthorne
Best Actress
Meryl Streep
Worst performance, male
Richard Gere in First Knight
Worst performance, female
Jennifer Saunders, In The Bleak Midwinter
So bad it is good film
Walk in the Clouds
The Big Stinker
Four Rooms
</TEXT>
