<HEADLINE>Moves to get them rolling in the Isles</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Last week's National Lottery award of almost #400,000 will realise the dream of
a mobile cinema for the Highlands and Islands
CHRIS Ealand clearly recalls the circumstances when he watched Kennedy being
shot. He had been shopping in Inverness with his family and stayed on to watch
the Kevin Costner movie JFK. He remembers it well because it was the last time
he - a self-confessed film buff - was inside a cinema.
Ealand used to run the North West Skye Film Club, but it folded because of
dwindling interest. The club could once depend on around 30 locals to pay to
watch 16mm art house movies in a local hall and latterly a restaurant in
Dunvegan. Gradually, however, the novelty of the projector making more noise
than the movie wore off and increasing costs drove more and more to the video
store.
The choice for Ealand and the rest of the island population is between joining
the video queue or face a round trip of more than 200 miles to the nearest
cinema in Inverness or Fort William.
It is this audience-in-waiting in Skye and other peripheral areas of Scotland
that Hi Arts and the Scottish Film Council are targeting with their plans to
put Hollywood on the road in the Highlands. The mobile cinema project hopes to
emulate the success of the French Cinemobile which is attracting audiences of
30,000 annually in rural areas.
Consultant Dick Penny carried out a feasibility study into the prospects of a
high quality, 100-seater, air-conditioned, cinema, showing the latest
blockbusters on 35mm film rolling into neighbourhoods in Dumfries and Galloway
and the Highlands and Islands. He identified at least 27 possible sites where
the moving cinema could be parked.
Although mobile cinema is not a new concept, the technology available in
France, which will be developed for the UK rather than imported directly, makes
it unrecognisable from its predecessors.
Kevin Cowle, development officer of the Scottish Film Council said: ``What we
have is a 40-foot articulated lorry which opens up like a butterfly into a
luxury cinema. The vehicle ends up three times its original width and has all
the comforts of a normal cinema.''
While Hi Arts Ltd has been the vehicle for the northern project, which will be
commissioned in March and should be operational by September, the ultimate plan
is to build two mobile cinemas in Scotland, and the Scottish Arts Council's
National Lottery committee is expecting an application to cover the Border and
the South West. For the moment, however, it appears that only the Highland
mobile cinema will be operational during cinema's centenary year.
Kevin Cowle says the project has met with nothing but enthusiasm. A visit by
the French vehicle to Moffat first whetted the appetite and was followed by the
vehicle's use at the Celtic Film and Television Festival in Fort William. He
has received a constant stream of correspondence from rural film societies ever
since.
``This is a project which will open up cinema to areas previously deprived of
its riches,'' he says.
Dick Penny is keen to emphasise the mobile screen's potential. ``We are talking
about a high quality cinema experience. It could not be further from the image
of the portable 16mm flickering pictures shown to people in plastic chairs with
the sound booming around a village hall. It is a commercial cinema exercise,
but its also a cultural and social service.''
He points to the growth in cinema audiences, while the number of cinemas has
dropped, although the advent of the multiplex has meant there has been a 45%
increase in the number of screens. The lack of conventional cinemas is felt
particularly in the Highlands and Islands which can boast only three cinemas
and five screens in the entire region - three of them in Inverness.
Paradoxically, the National Lottery is held responsible for a recent slowing in
the increase in cinema attendances as people spend their movie cash on a ticket
and sit in of a Saturday to watch the numbers come up instead. Now the proceeds
of that process are fuelling the mobile screen.
Chris Ealand welcomes the idea, but believes the younger generation may need
convincing. ``The only problem I can see is that we have a video culture
nowadays. Nearly every home has a VCR and it's so easy to pick up films at the
village store. People have been without it for so long in these areas that they
are not used to going to the cinema any longer and so it may need a bit of
re-education about its attractions.''
</TEXT>
