<HEADLINE>Too many champions in the battle for peace of mind</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mike Dailly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
There is demand for improvement in the care of the mentally ill, but there is
no agreed method of achieving it, finds Mike Dailly
HEALTH care standards at the Royal Edinburgh Hospital were highly criticised
this month with the publication of a leaked report. As Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth faces calls to launch a full inquiry, the Government has
announced a Patients' Charter for the mentally ill. But is the charter what
patients need?
A key area of concern at the Royal Edinburgh was that psychiatric patients were
being discharged too quickly, with a resultant breakdown of care as they
returned to the community. The new charter seeks to ensure that the system of
care does not break down and that patients do not have to leave hospital until
it is appropriate to do so.
Many working in the field of mental health may think that the Patients' Charter
is simply tinkering with the system. Earlier this month more than 300
psychiatrists, solicitors, judges and social workers met in Edinburgh to
consider whether the time had come to review fundamentally the 1984 Mental
Health (Scotland) Act.*
Adrian Ward, convener of the Law Society's mental health sub-committee,
believes we should start again from scratch. He says: ``The 1984 Act is hung up
on buildings; that is, detention in hospital. But people shouldn't be
institutionalised. I think compulsory medical treatment should only be looked
at as a last resort.''
Ward is an international expert who can cite European examples which suggest
Britain is lagging behind in mental health law. For example, this year the
courts in Switzerland upheld a woman's right to refuse treatment involving
psychotropic drugs. In Scotland, there is no such choice.
Social policy has changed drastically since the 1980s. Services are now
delivered in a different way, with the emphasis on participation, choice, and
care in the community.
In an attempt to reconcile difficulties, the Government introduced the 1995
Mental Health (Patients in the Community) Act. This legislation creates a new
community care order, which can be granted by the court at the request of a
consultant psychiatrist in order to allow a patient to return to the community
under certain conditions.
But the community care order has more critics than friends. Many believe it
will not be used in practice because it has no legal teeth. The order cannot
impose compulsory medication and if a condition is breached it is not clear
what will happen.
Dr James Dyer, director of the Mental Welfare Commission for Scotland, thinks
the community care order has impaired the current legal position.
Dr Dyer says: ``In Scotland we have 123 patients on leave of absence longer
than one year. The majority accept their treatment in the community because if
they don't they can be recalled to hospital.
``I agree that the law is too hospital-orientated, but the 1995 Act sets things
back as it restricts leave of absence to a maximum of 12 months.
``There are people whose illness is such that they don't recognise they are ill
- no amount of improved services would get them to consent to treatment. To say
there should not be a compulsory treatment power in the community is to deny
this fact.''
Yet Dr Tony Maden, a forensic psychiatrist working with criminals who are
mentally ill, is opposed to any extension of psychiatrists' powers.
He says: ``I have a problem with labelling someone living in the community
unfit to decide whether they need treatment. If they can't decide themselves,
shouldn't they be put in hospital?
``I don't think present legislation has been given sufficient time: it's the
application of the law that's a problem. I believe psychiatrists should be more
practical and flexible.
``If you study inquiries into homicides by schizophrenic patients you find
examples of cock-ups by psychiatrists and the tribunals. For example, I can
recall cases where patients on restriction orders in the community were taken
off medication on the advice of psychiatrists and later killed members of the
public.''
Many in Scotland are equally concerned about the idea of compulsory treatment
in the community. As solicitor Hilary Patrick of the Scottish Association of
Mental Health says: ``Is this just care in the community on the cheap? A
compulsory treatment order would presumably say `take x milligrams of
tranquillisers or present yourself at the hospital for an injection'. You would
then be expected to stagger off into the sunrise. How would it be enforced?''
Although there may be differing views as to the best way to deal with mental
illness, there seems to be a growing consensus that fundamental change is
necessary. As Lynn Welsh, mental health solicitor at the Legal Services Agency,
says: ``The Mental Health Act needs to be completely rethought. The Act should
be scrapped and we should start with the presumption that someone should not be
detained. That presumption could be rebutted with appropriate evidence. If the
Government does agree to a fundamental review, then substantial input should be
sought from groups other than just psychiatrists.''
q The Mental Health (Scotland) Act: Consensus for Change? is organised by The
Law Society of Scotland, Royal College of Psychiatrists, Scottish Association
of Mental Health and Legal Services Agency Ltd.
</TEXT>
