<HEADLINE>Good and bad in everyone</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dr David Delvin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>man alive</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Q. I see you've been talking about cholesterol levels in The Herald. My problem
is I have absolutely no concept of what this stuff is! Does it float around in
your blood like icebergs? Is is true there is ``good'' cholesterol and ``bad''
cholesterol?
A. Cholesterol is actually a kind of fat which is carried around in your
bloodstream. It's rather like those greasy dollops you can sometimes see in
thick cream. And if you've got too much, it rapidly starts silting up your
coronary arteries - which is very bad news indeed.
In most people, the amount of cholesterol in the blood can be reduced to
healthy levels just by eating a more sensible diet - that is, one which
contains little animal fat, plus a reasonable amount of fibre. Exercise also
helps get it down.
Now sir, you're quite right in saying that there are ``good'' and ``bad'' types
of cholesterol. Most of the cholesterol in your blood is the bad kind which
helps cause heart disease. But a wee bit of your cholesterol is a different
sort, ``high density'', and is actually quite good for you. So, anyone who goes
to the doc for the result of a cholesterol test should ask whether the high
density portion is okay, as well as enquiring about the total reading.
Q. My son, aged 16, tells me he has had a pain in one testicle for a day or
two. He did not like to mention it initially, because of embarrassment. Should
I send him to the doctor's?
A. Immediately! Unfortunately, very few people realise there's a serious, and
not uncommon, condition called ``torsion of the testicle''. What happens is the
testicle becomes twisted on its ``stalk'', causing pain. All too often, the
victim ignores the symptom because of embarrassment,          and just puts up
with the pain for several days.
Sadly, the result may well be gangrene - and the testicle may have to be
removed. To prevent such tragedies, all males should be taught from an early
age that unexpected pain in one testicle is a good reason for an urgent
examination by a doctor.
Q. How often should a man have his blood pressure checked? I have been told I
suffer from low blood pressure, but I don't know how often to get it measured.
A. In Scotland and the UK generally, low blood pressure is not regarded as an
illness, but as a cause for congratulation - since it's associated with long
life and a low risk of heart disease! Things are different on the Continent,
where many physicians view low blood pressure as a disease, which they think
should be treated. I'm afraid you just have to accept that different countries
take different attitudes.
Now, how often should a male get his BP checked? It depends on age; when a man
is young there's really little point in having your blood pressure checked. In
a chap of (say) 25, the chance of it being significantly abnormal is remote.
I'd suggest male readers should follow this plan: age 30 to 39, BP check every
three years; 40 to 49, BP check every two years; 50 or over, BP check every
year. Obviously, any man whose pressure turns out to be raised will need more
frequent checks.
Q. I have been suffering from the most horrible tension at home over the last
week or so. I'm ashamed to admit it, but I could very easily belt my children,
and also my wife. Being cooped up with them in the same room for even a few
minutes seems to drive me into a fury, mainly because the noise the kids make
is absolutely unbearable. Am I going mad?
A. No, but you're clearly showing symptoms which could develop into a
full-blown neurosis, if you don't take action fast. I don't know why you're
reacting this way, but I'd guess there have been some major stresses in your
life in recent months.
The important thing to do now is to take the pressure off yourself. Do not let
yourself get ``cooped up'' with your children or your wife. If you feel
yourself getting irritable, go out: for a walk, or to the pictures, or anything
(but preferably not down the pub). Finally, if your GP has an appointment free
today, please go along and get some counselling.
Q. My wife and I have had trouble conceiving a baby, and it turns out this is
due to the fact I have a low sperm count. Is it true I can improve our chances
by keeping the lower part of my body cool? I'd do anything - even wear a kilt!
A. Well, it is true a hot environment lowers a man's sperm count. That's why
guys who do a lot of driving sometimes have fertility problems, because the
scrotum gets decidedly overheated during long journeys. Similarly, males who
wear tight, ``jockey-style'' underpants may find their fertility is a little
impaired.
In general, a man can help ensure maximum fertility by keeping his personal
parts reasonably cool. For instance, you can wear boxer shorts instead of tight
pants. A lot of chaps try to improve their chances by dipping their testicles
in cold water just before they make love. But there's no point in this, because
the process of sperm-manufacture takes around six weks.
My best advice is to wear loose clothing at all times. I'm a little doubtful as
to whether wearing the kilt would help, because from personal experience I can
tell you it's a surprisingly warm garment.
Q. What is a hernia? Is it the same thing as a rupture? I've noticed a bulge in
the lower right-hand side of my tummy for several months. When I mentioned it
to a nursing friend, she said it might be a hernia. Is is true that they can
affect your sex life?
A. This swelling must be checked out by our doc to see if it really is a
hernia. A hernia is exactly the same thing as a rupture. They can occur in all
sorts of places, but by far the commonest site is the groin. I'm assuming
that's where your particular swelling is.
Men are much more liable to groin hernias than women, because the male
abdominal well has a weak spot where the spermatic cord goes through.
A rupture is a bulge through the abdomen wall, rather as if the stuffing was
trying to escape from a sausage. People tend to blame ruptures on lifting heavy
loads, but there are many factors which can cause them: a congenital weakness,
being overweight, being pregnant (not in your case, I pressume), and coughing
heavily over a long period of time.
The best treatment is to get it operated on - in case it causes trouble and
pain as it gets worse. To get the best advice about choice of surgeon and type
of operation, consult your GP. Finally, you ask if a rupture will affect your
sex life. No, it won't.
Q: I'm 19 and I like to have one cigarette a day with my pals. Am I right in
thinking this couldn't possibly do me any harm?
A: Well, you're absolutely right, young sir. A single cigarette per day cannot
have any effect on the health of a fit man. But - and it's one of those big
``buts'' - the trouble with cigarettes is they contain the highly addictive
drug nicotine. So in a little while your brain may start urging you to have
another..... and another. Prenez garde.
n.If you have a query about your health, write to Dr David Delvin at The
Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow G1 1QP. Dr Delvin cannot reply in person,
but he will try to respond in this column. Your name will not be published.
</TEXT>
