<HEADLINE>Cracks in ANC alliance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Laurence</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Patrick Laurence, in Johannesburg, examines the divisions emerging in the ANC's
broad alliance, which could prove costly in a future South Africa without
Nelson Mandela
NELSON MANDELA's African National Congress stands over South Africa like a
political colossus, having trounced its rivals in the November local government
elections to record its second emphatic electoral triumph since April last year.
Its dominance is due in part to its success in forging a broad alliance. But
even now, only 20 months after the ANC's decisive victory in the 1994 General
Election, there are unmistakable signs of stress within the alliance.
At its core, the alliance consists of the ANC, its long-time ally the South
African Communist Party (SACP), and South Africa's largest trade union
federation, the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
But attached more loosely are a series of ANC-aligned organisations, including
the South African National Civic Organisation (Sanco) and the Congress of
Traditional Leaders of South Africa (Contralesa).
The most audible dissonance comes from Cosatu, which has objected strenuously
to ANC plans to ``restructure state assets'' by selling some of them, in part
or whole, to private investors.
Expressing dismay at ANC plans, Cosatu has already organised a two-hour work
stoppage to signal its opposition to ``unilateral restructuring'' and announced
its intention to launch a one-day national strike on January 16 to underline
its resistance.
SACP leader Jeremy Cronin has accused the press of misrepresenting the
situation, of ``restructuring the truth'' by exaggerating the divergence
between the ANC and Cosatu. He predicts that Cosatu's objections will be
addressed in discussions aimed at forging an agreed ``national framework'' for
restructuring.
While Mr Cronin's criticisms of press coverage of ANC-Cosatu differences may be
justified in part, there is no doubt that Cosatu has serious misgivings about
the process of restructuring or - to use the label favoured by the press -
``privatisation''.
The alternative is to view the work stoppages - which began with wildcat
strikes within four days of Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's announcement of ANC
plans to sell state assets - as a charade put on by Cosatu secretary-general
Sam Shilowa to impress his followers and to camouflage his own complicity in
ANC ``privatisation'' plans.
Mr Cronin's prediction that a unifying consensus will emerge may be proved
correct. Both sides have too much to lose from a major fallout. The ANC is
reluctant to relinquish its image as the champion of black workers. Cosatu
still wants the ANC to remain in power, whatever anxieties it may have over
restructuring.
But there is no denying that the once-cosy ANC-Cosatu relationship has come to
an end. The coalescence of aims - ending rule by the white minority and its
black auxiliaries - no longer exists.
As the dominant party in the government of national unity, the ANC finds itself
playing the role of employer in the public sector and thus is in an adversarial
relationship with public sector unions, most of which are Cosatu affiliates.
The ANC has had to resist demands for wage increases to fulfil its commitments
to reduce the public service bill and balance the budget.
The relationship is influenced adversely by another factor. The new, emerging
elite of black entrepreneurs and moguls increasingly has the ear of ANC
ministers. Their agenda is necessarily different from that of Cosatu as the
voice of its 1.6 million members in mines, factories, offices and shops across
the land.
Mr Shilowa recognises that, as his condemnation of black entrepreneurs who
favour privatisation shows. After castigating the International Monetary Fund
and the World Bank for ``prescribing a remedy of doom'' to the ANC government,
he says: ``The same goes for the emerging black elite which is also fighting
for the handing over of state assets . . . In the name of black economic
empowerment, they wish to steal public resources and put them in the hands of a
few black individuals.''
Similar though less vocal discord emanates from Sanco. Formed out the civic
associations which emerged in black townships in the 1980s, Sanco branches are
meant to provide local leaders to seek redress for local grievances and
fulfilment of local aspirations.
But according to Ivor Chipkin, of the Centre for Policy Studies, local leaders
are often shoved aside at election time in favour of party loyalists nominated
by the ANC leadership.
Thus in Phola Park, a strongly pro-ANC squatter settlement located on the
fringe of the Johannesburg megalopolis, dissatisfaction continues to simmer
over the failure of the local Sanco chairman and the local ANC chairman to
secure nomination as ANC candidates in the November 1 election.
A recent outburst of violence in Phola Park, in which five people were killed,
is attributed to discontent over the selection of candidates for the local
government election. It is seen as a bloody manifestation of intra-ANC violence.
Tom Lodge, professor of political studies at the University of Witwatersrand,
warns against interpreting rivalry over places on the ANC list of candidates -
Sanco agreed that its members should stand under the ANC banner in the local
government elections - ``as profound ideological disputes''.
But, he predicts, the ANC's control over local government structures will bring
it into conflict with sections of the black community on issues such as the
refusal to pay for municipal service charges or the eviction of squatters from
municipal ground.
Tension is also brewing between the ANC and Contralesa over the ANC's failure -
as many chiefs see the situation - to safeguard the interests of traditional
leaders in the new order.
The great strength of the ANC has been its ability to mobilise the black
community as a whole and to subordinate incipient class conflicts, whether
between workers and capitalists, commoners and chiefs, to the greater cause of
ousting white minority government.
Now that a predominantly black government is in power, cracks are emerging as
the disparate allies pursue different agendas. President Mandela, aged 77, has
prestige and charisma to hold the alliance together. But after he goes it may
slowly start to break up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
