<DOCNO>GH951228-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#60 fee makes it Sterling County</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TANGIBLE professionalism has arrived. The Diary can reveal that Stirling
County, who narrowly failed to retain the championship this season, have agreed
to pay their players #60 a game, to be backdated to the start of the season,
with a bigger sum to be given to the players depending on how far they progress
in the Tennents Cup. The club also have decided to pay the coaches for their
contribution to the team's effort this season.
Surprisingly, that hasn't pleased everyone at Stirling. Club second row Stewart
Hamilton said in confirmation: ``I am actually against rugby being
professional, but yes the club have said that we are to be paid and we would be
getting more if we had won the league. There is a bonus system in place, and
the coaches are to be paid too.
``It has now gone so far that you can't stop it. I really think that we have
the type of game that would be best left unpaid because it is just so physical.
We understand that two other clubs in the first division, Melrose and Heriot's,
are getting money also. As I understand it, County are fairly well off at the
moment because of the Barbarians game at Forthbank and some healthy gates.''
Forwards coach Jim ``Muff'' Scobbie says it's good news. ``I get expenses at
the moment. I think that the coaches should be in line with the players, but I
haven't heard directly from anyone that Brian Edwards and I are to get paid
like the players,'' says the former Glasgow prop.
``There's no doubt that the players should be getting paid, and all you have to
do is look at our last few crowds to realise that. The players are now taking
the field in front of in excess of 4000 spectators at times.''
But Melrose, one of the clubs mentioned by Hamilton, say they are not parting
with any money at the moment. ``Nobody at Melrose is being paid,'' says
secretary Stuart Henderson. ``But we are, of course, considering it because of
the threat to our players from down south.''
All of which means that any lingering possibility of an amateur club base in
Scotland will fade into the mist. Earlier this week the international players
signed contracts with the SRU which granted possible earnings of #23,000 in the
season, but the Stiring County move now sets a benchmark of the order of #2000
per season for the other clubs in Scotland to follow. None of which matches the
#50,000 reported to be coming the way of Newcastle's players annually.
The City of Glasgow's clubs, among them second division West of Scotland, see
County's approach as logical. ``It was always going to come,'' says club
president Alasdair Burnet. ``We haven't got the money to do the same, but we
have been trying to look after our players as best we can. We are very
conscious that our talented youngsters might be attracted away by #60 a week,
and they have been approached by other clubs already. We have a players' fund
ourselves where we ask our club members to contribute and the cash goes to the
players. We have also said that all the money we get from the cup will be
spread among the players. But club loyalty is definitely going to suffer.''
Stirling County are one of the big clubs wanting to play in Europe, which would
no doubt put more lolly on the table, but the Diary understands that there are
many in Stirling County who do not agree with that stance. They say that no
Scottish club is strong enough, or has enough strength in depth, to take on top
class foreign opposition and so districts should represent Scotland.
So, a club in Scotland is to play its players #60 a week as a basic weekly
wage. Handy pocket money? Well, it's worth pointing out that a single person's
old age pension for 1995/96 is #59.15 a week. It's a funny old world isn't it?
The Diary suspects that the government has it wrong, but then we should never
mix politics and sport they say. Money talks, that's what we say, and there
will be a few steps taken in Stirling's direction over the summer if this keeps
up - or if other clubs fail to do the same.
q THIS little Diary had awarded Stirling County with the No Foreigners prize
for doing so well without resorting to the import of a few Antipodeans in
pursuit of short-term success.
We said they were the only side without them. But John Thorburn, the Hawick
secretary, phoned up to put the record straight.
``After having some in the past we have no foreigners in our team this year,''
says Thorburn. ``In fact we don't even have any Dundee players in the squad
either.'' Ouch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
