<HEADLINE>Bogus posters</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bogus posters
J
JIMMY Reid claims that there are ``existing photographs, taken this century, of
official British posters in the coastal towns of China which state, `Dogs and
Chinese not allowed on these premises' '' (December 23).
Not only would I query the validity of such photographs but I can assert that
they were most certainly not ``official British posters''.
On April 13, 1994, the Daily Telegraph carried a report from a Chinese magazine
called Century which admitted that the infamous signs said to have been erected
in front of Shanghai's waterfront Huang Pu Gardens were made for propaganda
purposes by the Communist Party after the 1949 revolution.
This lie obtained further publicity in the West through a Bruce Lee film and,
unfortunately, continues to do the rounds.
Alistair D McConnachie,
1 Tay Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
