<DOCNO>GH951228-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ministry defensive on  Beaufort's `bombs'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLAIMS that a survey has shown that more than 4000 phosphorus bombs washed
ashore on Scottish beaches came from the Beaufort's Dyke munitions dump were
stonewalled by the Ministry of Defence last night.
The official report of the survey carried out by scientists at the Scottish
Office marine laboratory in Aberdeen will not be published until next month but
it is believed to state that the devices orginated from the Dyke, a trench in
the North Channel between Stranraer and Belfast.
The scientists who took part are understood to have decided it is ``now beyond
reasonable doubt'' the bombs were dislodged by British Gas pipe-laying
operations.
The Ministry of Defence dismissed the claims as ``pure speculation''. However,
it said earlier this year that more than one million tons of explosive and
chemical weapons had been dumped in the Dyke.
An MoD spokesman said: ``The report into the Government ordered survey is not
due out until the middle of next month. Any comments regarding the situation on
what may have led to explosives appearing on beaches, or where they came from
is pure speculation at this stage.''
About 4400 highly flammable phosphorus sticks were washed on to beaches in
western Scotland in October, arousing claims that they had been disturbed by
British Gas contractors who had begun digging a 6ft deep trench for a
cross-channel pipeline in the sea bed north of the Dyke.
The MoD said last month that the devices came from decayed 30lb incendiary
bombs of a kind dropped by British aircraft in the Second World War. It was
suggested that they could have been dredged up from another underwater
explosives dump at Birch Point, two miles east of Arran.
The marine laboratory report into the Birch Point dump says, however, it was
not used for MoD disposals, but for commercial explosive waste from the
ICI/Nobel's works at Ardeer, Ayrshire.
Mr George Foulkes, Labour MP for Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley, has called
for a halt to all commercial activity near the Dyke until a detailed survey of
the area has been completed.
Mr Foulkes has written urging Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to stop
further consideration of the proposed electricity Interconnector linking the
Scottish grid with Ulster until the present surveys of the seabed in the North
Channel are completed and given careful consideration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
