<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sharp buy-out doubles funds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW-based stockbroker Stirling Hendry and fellow broker Brown Shipley have
been acquired by Albert E Sharp, the Birmingham based broker. The #6m deal will
double the size of Sharp's funds under management to #4000m. This makes it
arguably the UK's largest private client stockbroker.
Sales on a high
FIGURES published by the Association of Unit Trusts and Investment Funds show
net sales of unit trusts at a seven month high in November. At #335m, compared
to #291m in the previous month, it brought the average net retail sales figure
for the whole year to over #250m per month.
Lamont moves on
FORMER Chancellor Norman Lamont has left the investment bank NM Rothschild,
where he became a director in 1993,it was announced yesterday. Mr Lamont is
joining Jupiter Asset Management, where he will revive his skills in asset
management learned before he joined the Government. He is already a director of
five Jupiter funds.
PA wrangle ends
A SIX-year long wrangle between Inland Revenue and the Press Association has
ended with a #19m payout to shareholders. The special dividend payment follows
protracted talks over how much tax was due on the PA's former 41% stake in
Reuters.
Report delayed
THE US Labour Department said yesterday it will be forced to delay reports on
December employment and consumer prices scheduled for release in early January.
The ongoing partial shutdown of the government due to a budget impasse has been
blamed for the delay.
Fraud charges
FORMER Japanese labour minister Toshio Yamaguchi and members of his family,
were yesterday indicted on embezzlement and fraud charges after a year-long
scandal linked to a scheme to bail out two credit unions. The charges, also
including perjury and breach of trust, involve 270,000m yen.
</TEXT>
