<DOCNO>GH951228-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charter aims to reassure on mentally ill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is to introduce a Patient's Charter for the mentally ill to
overcome growing public concern about schizophrenics involved in vicious
assaults.
Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell said yesterday he would set tough new
standards designed to make the streets safer by reducing the threat to the
public from attacks by severely disturbed psychiatric patients.
The Mental Health Patients Charter will ensure:
q Patients get help from nurses or social workers, if they need it, after
discharge.
q Home visits within four hours for urgent cases and within two working days
for non-urgent cases.
q Patients will not be sent home if it is thought there could be the slightest
risk to carers, relatives, or the public.
q Tough new time limits for assessing a patient's illness to reduce waiting
lists.
q Information on the effects of drugs and alternative treatments will be
available.
q Patients will be allowed to wear their own clothes, have personal
possessions, and have more privacy in hospital.
q Patients can expect access to a lawyer if necessary and will be able to
choose the gender of their key worker.
q Explanation of diagnosis.
q Anyone detained for 28 days or more has the right to apply to a Mental
Health Tribunal and get a medical opinion from an independent doctor.
Mr Dorrell hopes the charter consultation, to start in the new year, will go
some way towards quelling public fears about schizophrenics which began in 1992
when Jonathan Zito was killed by Christopher Clunis at a tube station.
Last August Health Minister Gerald Malone warned NHS chairmen to improve
standards and stop patients falling through the Care in the Community net.
They were asked to review their services and report back to the Secretary of
State. He is due to announce the outcome of this exercise shortly.
But there is no doubt the Government's policy of allowing patients more freedom
has been fraught with difficulties.
Mr Dorrell said: ``When there's public comment about the mental health
services, people often latch on to the phrase `Care in the Community' and say
this means the Government is not interested in hospital care, which isn't true.
``The phrase has become misleading because it has come to imply that the only
type of mental health service we are interested in delivering is one based on
community health and that is not the case.''
The mental health charity, Mind, said schizophrenics needed more help, not a
charter. Spokeswoman Kate Harrison also pointed out that there was no evidence
of an increased risk of violence to the public from such patients.
She said: ``It is the case that services for people with schizophrenia are not
good enough.
``We need more resources across a spectrum of services from decent housing and
occupations to social support.''
Too many champions 12
Stealth claim
THE Government was yesterday accused of the underhand privatisation of NHS
medicines by a health management expert.
Escalating prescription charges, the ``blacklisting'' of drugs, and the removal
of medicines from the prescription register all add up to a form of
privatisation, according to Mr Alan Earl-Slater, a research fellow at the
Health Services Management Centre, Birmingham University.
Writing in Public Money and Management, published by the Chartered Institute of
Public Finance and Accountancy, he claimed the Government was following the
policy ``without either admitting it or having the mandate to do it''.
</TEXT>
