<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Check-up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>check up</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.AT last men are beginning to take their health, and drinking habits,
seriously. The current issue of Men's Health magazine gives a stern warning:
``Drink according to your size. A 10-stone man can only handle about half as
much alcohol as an 18-stone one.''
It offers further hints on good drinking habits including the following:
``Drink slowly on a full stomach. This means the alcohol is metabolised before
it can build up in your bloodstream and start attacking your brain.
``Avoid drinks containing `congeners' - substances that add flavour and colour
to alcohol but increase the agony of excess. Vodka is kindest, while Cognac,
brandy, whisky and champagne are the worst transgressors. Avoid red wine, it
produces a killer of a headache. Take a herbal supplement containing
`Silymarin' (Milk thistle). Clinical trials show this stimulates protein
production in liver cells and hastens regeneration of liver cells poisoned by
alcohol and other environmental toxins.''
n.CHILDREN born to older fathers or coal-miners are at increased risk of
developing Alzheimer's disease, according to a major research project which
looked at the risk of the disease in Scotland. The study, carried out by
Professor Lawrence Whalley and colleagues at Aberdeen University, found the
disease was more prevalent in Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and Edinburgh.
This is the largest, and only national, sample so far in the world and involved
450 Alzheimer sufferers and 1784 early dementia cases recorded between 1974 and
1988.
Jan Killeen, Director of Public Policy for Alzheimer's Scotland, Action on
Dementia, welcomed the results: ``One part of the study suggested there were
clusters of people with Alzheimer's in highly urbanised areas, while the other
linked dementia with diet and deprivation in coal mining areas. This is the
first time this link has been made and a lot more research is needed to look at
other incidents in other occupational groups in order to make comparisons and
to explore more of the links betwen occupation and environment.''
n.PERSONAL development guru Jack Black urges charities to ``positively think
bigger''. He says that in today's fast changing world no company can afford to
keep cynics on board. ``Cynics are yesterday's men and women,'' he told a
champagne breakfast organised on behalf of the Scottish Council for Spastics'
Business Breakfasts in Edinburgh. This was the first of four events sponsored
by Scottish Airports aimed at raising #36,000 to fund the society's work in
providing a range of services for children and adults with cerebral palsy and
other disabilities.
n.THE festive season can be a lonely time when you are recently bereaved or
missing someone who has died, and it is important you do not neglect your
health. Free and confidential advice on dealing with grief and bereavement is
available from the NHS Helpline on 0800 22 44 88 any weekday between 9am and
5pm. The counsellors can also help ease any other health worries with
information on a wide range of topics.
n.MAKING New Year resolutions should be positive and not a source of guilt,
otherwise they can lead to feelings of guilt and depression - the last thing
you need during the dreich days of January and February. This advice comes from
ARISE, the Association for Research into Science and Enjoyment, a non-political
body of scientists and academics.
``Denying yourself your favourite treat at a time when you are already feeling
low potentially increases stress and encourages depression. This is made worse
by feelings of guilt when you break a New Year's resolution,'' says Professor
David Warburton, director of the Human Psychopharmacology Group at the
University of Reading and co-ordinator of ARISE.
n.STRESS can increase a woman's risk of breast cancer. For a long time it has
been suspected that stress can induce physical ill-health but this has been
mostly unproven. However, a new study, reported in the British Medical Journal,
focused on 119 women who were being investigated for breast disease. It was
found that events such as divorce, the death of a parent, or loss of a job
during the five years prior to diagnosis increased the risk of breast cancer
approximately three-fold. But this factor increased to nearly 12-fold after
adjustment for age, menopausal status, and other potential factors. Lesser
adverse life events were also found to be strongly linked to breast cancer.
n.Yesterday's ``Those falling spirits'' story in Wednesday Extra was wrongly
attributed to Kennedy Wilson. The article was written by Nicholas Powell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
