<HEADLINE>Top flight training for chefs on menu</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARAH URQUHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S culinary record is about to improve with plans to set up the first
chefs' training school north of the Border.
The Scottish Chefs Association plans to open the centre within the next 18
months at a city venue.
The school will train chefs on all aspects of cooking, from breakfasts to
advanced dinners, as well as running courses on meat, fish, game, and
vegetables.
It will also have a separate training kitchen for patisserie and chocolate work
and will house a recipe book library and a cooking careers centre. The
association, set up two years ago by a dozen top Scottish chefs, now has about
300 members.
It has conducted almost 50 training courses so far and the first three-day
residential course for young chefs will begin in February.
Mr Nick Nairn, a chef and member of the association's advisory board, said:
``Setting up a training school has been one of our aims from the beginning. It
is the logical extension of two years of running training courses.''
Mr Brian Hannan, the association's organiser, said: ``We want to create for
cooks a similar level of training that is available for musicians. Scotland has
spent millions of pounds on improving the food business infrastructure but
virtually nothing on improving cooking.
``It has great potential to be a force on the global culinary scene. The school
will be a huge practical step towards fulfilling that potential.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why was the church collection so easily stolen?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS indeed sad to read about the two masked men with axes who stole a church
collection. The housekeeper and the assistant priest have my sympathy. I trust
the thieves will soon be caught and I hope the Lord will change their minds and
make them repent of their deeds and return the money.
However, what was the money doing there anyway? It is beyond belief that the
money was kept in eight carrier-bags, and even more so that it was in the
possession of a priest and not in a bank night safe.
Surely the Roman Catholic Church does not normally work this way. If so it is
time it changed its procedures. In Presbyterian churches the offering is
counted immediately after the service and it would then go straight to the
night safe where possible. It would certainly not go anywhere near the manse.
John S Biggam,
17 Stirling Street,
Tillicoultry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Highlands seek EU cash for coastal management</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Regional Council is bidding for a share of #150m of European funding,
for developing a coastal zone management scheme.
The bid, which will be based on exploratory studies carried out in the Skye
area, comes after the issue was given a high profile for the first time by the
European Commission this autumn.
A paper from the commission notes that the European Union has 89,000km of
coastline, with a significant proportion of the population being dependent on
the coastal zone, but that over the years, habitats, dune systems, wetlands,
and other environmentally important features are disappearing, and that the
quality of coastal waters is declining.
The commission admits that while many measures have been taken to protect the
environment, nothing has been aimed specifically at the coastal zone, and it
blames this on a ``lack of co-ordination between the numerous actors
influencing the development of the coast''.
While there are many areas in Britain, and in the Highlands especially,
considered worthy of protection and management, areas in Spain, Greece, Italy,
France, and Germany especially, are keen on getting coastal zone management
schemes, and the attendant funding in their area.
Highland Regional Council has already begun a coastal zone management study in
Skye, covering an area described as ``a box drawn around Skye, and extended
until it touches the mainland''.
This has already yielded 12 ``position'' papers, setting out a baseline of
uses, prepared by agencies ranging from the Ministry of Defence to ferry
operators, fishermen, aquaculture, and tourist operators.
So far, however, there has been no money available to take the study on to the
next stage - a pilot project on how the different agencies could co-operate to
manage the area of the coastal zone in which they are involved.
Highland regional officials see this as a chance to bring more money into the
area, and have put in an initial bid for studies that would involve Skye and
the Cromarty Firth, which has been designated as a Special Area of Conservation
under the EC Habitats Directive, and a Special Protection Area under the EC
Birds Directive - both of which could cause conflict with the existing and
developmental potential of the area in relation to oil and heavy industry.
The EU paper makes it clear that several pilot studies could be undertaken in
different countries facing different problems in the coastal zones. It notes
that funds could be made available under EU programmes already up and running
in the Highlands and Islands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United reduce Premiership lead to seven points Cole applies brakes to a runaway Newcastle train</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Manchester United 2,
Newcastle 0
ANDY Cole picked the perfect time to justify Alex Ferguson's faith in him and
hit Kevin Keegan where it hurts by gunning down his former club to breathe new
life into the title race.
Doubts had been raised over Ferguson's #7m gamble after last year's title
disappointment and this season's goal famine. The question marks were made even
bigger by the stunning form of Cole's St James' Park replacement, 21-goal Les
Ferdinand.
But on a night when Old Trafford's biggest crowd of the season knew that only a
win was good enough, it was Cole who set Ferguson's men on their way with a
glorious goal.
With Roy Keane capping his own non-stop display with a decisive second after
the break, United deservedly cut the gap to seven points as Newcastle slipped
to only their third defeat of the season.
Cole's goal was everything Ferguson had demanded of him. Just six minutes had
gone when a Newcastle attack broke down, and as they struggled to reorganise,
Ryan Giggs floated down the left.
Cantona - inspirational as skipper for the day - drew the Newcastle defence
like moths to a flame with a sublime dummy run, but that was surpassed by
Cole's emphatic, first-time finish, the ball nestling in the bottom corner
within a fraction of a second of leaving his right foot.
It was a goal that summed up the innate touch of the master-goalscorer, who had
netted 68 times as a Newcastle player.
Try as Newcastle - hampered by the early departure of the man who moved the
other way in January, Keith Gillespie - did, they were always second best from
then on, the victory margin no more than the home team deserved.
Cantona's captaincy was a consequence of the absence of Steve Bruce, and with
Gary Pallister also injured and Paul Parker ill, Gary Neville was drafted in
alongside David May at the heart of the defence.
It was a change that worked in United's favour, for Dennis Irwin, switched to
the right to accommodate Philip Neville, handled David Ginola with surprising
ease, while Ferdinand was unable, in the first half, to put the central
defenders under pressure.
Ferguson had bemoaned his crop of injuries, but the return of Giggs gave them
pace on the break, and Keane's power in midfield had Rob Lee and Peter
Beardsley forced on to the back foot.
Even so, after five games without a win, Ferguson's team needed a vibrant
start, and that was exactly what they made.
In 53 minutes, the die was cast. Newcastle seemed to have cleared the danger
when a corner was worked out as far as Philip Neville, but that was discounting
Keane's attacking instincts.
Neville did see the Irishman stealing forward, delivering the perfect diagonal
ball and as Newcastle looked for the flag Keane controlled and lashed home.
