<HEADLINE>EconomyConsumer confidence falls in US</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US consumer confidence fell in December as the holiday season failed to
brighten Americans' outlook for the economy, the Conference Board said
yesterday.
The research and business group said its US consumer confidence index fell to
98.7 from a revised 101.6 in November.
The widely watched expectations component of the index fell to 91.7 from a
revised 92.5 in November. The present situation component slid to 109.2 from a
revised 115.3 in November.
``Overall, the consumer confidence index has hovered around the 100 mark
throughout the year,'' said Edgar Fiedler, vice president at the Conference
Board.
Less than 17% of consumers expect fewer jobs to be available in the next six
months, down from more than 18% in November, while fewer respondents expect
their family's income to increase.
About 23% of survey respondents say that business conditions are ``good'', down
from almost 28% in November.-Reuter
</TEXT>
