<DOCNO>GH951228-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Korean conundrum Military build-up could be cry for help</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE North Korean army appears to be massing close to the frontier with the
South amid mutterings about relations between the two states. Such military
demonstrations and veiled threats have become an annual event, but the balance
of probability remains that any sound and fury will be verbal only. Indeed, as
the North usually deploys up to 70% of its armed forces alo
Even during the nuclear dispute, when the North Koreans appeared to behave most
aggressively, the eventual consensus of opinion was that they were making a
plea for help. That may be the case again: the threat is a kind of blackmail
designed to elicit help in the most direct form of aid to compensate for the
failure of the Northern economy to deliver the sort of consumer products,
including food, which the South manages with ease. The logic of this situation
is the re-unification of the two Koreas, difficult though that will be for the
North's rulers to stomach. Much as German unification imposed a huge burden on
West Germany, a united Korea would be an enormous expense for the South. It is
well placed to bear it. The real trick will not be economic but diplomatic, as
the present situation shows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Costs compared</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE lather that politicians have got into over HCI is extraordinary when the
cost is minuscule in comparison to Trident.
When the Israelis are prepared to contemplate giving up nuclear weapons it
makes British retention of Trident all the more difficult to justify.
HCI is an unfortunate episode. It should be remembered, however, that hospitals
are there to treat people. Nuclear weapons are weapons of mass destruction.
Billions have been squandered on Trident. The Public Accounts Committee should
take a look at the justification for such expense.
Andrew J T Kerr,
52 Castlegate,
Jedburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Currency gesture</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667865</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DO NOT understand why the mark was not chosen as the name for the proposed
common currency. Would this not make economic sense as at least one country
would be saved the expense in any changeover?
It would also have been a nice gesture if perhaps war veterans were invited to
perform any naming ceremony. I am sure they would appreciate being involved in
some way and they may just forget why they made so many sacrifices protecting
the very freedom that some are so determined to give away.
So much is talked these days about the economical advantages to be gained by
further European integration (or should that read interference?) that the main
point is being overlooked.
This is one of principle, which should always take precedence over selling our
freedom for a quick buck. Principles are all too easily abandoned nowadays for
fear of being made to look stupid.
The lack of a ``feel-good factor'' may have something to do with the present
trend of bending over backwards to appease the French and Germans. In
surrendering our currency we are not simply giving our freedom away but are
paying an indecently large amount of money for the privilege.
Gordon Bannatyne,
8 Rowan Avenue,
Milton of Campsie.
</TEXT>
