<HEADLINE>State of roads cuts number of breath tests</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE drinking then driving on the treacherous icy roads in Scotland over the
three-day Christmas period have been strongly criticised by top police
officers, who said their actions ``bordered on lunacy''.
The comments from the Association of Chief Police Officers came as it was
revealed that the number of people who tested positively during this time had
fallen to 30 compared to 69 last year.
Seven people refused to take a test, compared with three people last year. In
Strathclyde 14 drivers tested positive. There were 24 last year.
The spokesman for ACPO said: ``Drink driving even in the best conditions is
dangerous, selfish, and irresponsible. To knowingly get behind the wheel in the
conditions we are experiencing at the moment and with too much alcohol in your
system is bordering on lunacy.''
The severe wintry weather meant a fall in the number of drivers breath tested
in Scotland over this Christmas period compared to 1994. Last year 2614 were
tested, with 1824 this year, a drop of around 30%.
Scottish Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton welcomed the fall but said
there was no room for complacency.
Lord James said: ``This was a difficult period for the emergency services and,
in many areas of the country, resources were used to their limits. This is
reflected in the fall in the number of breath tests carried out.
``The police will continue to operate a high level of testing and motorists
must realise there is a good chance that they will get caught if they choose to
drink and drive.''
He repeated the message that drinking and driving wrecked lives, and strongly
urged ``all motorists to heed the message and not to drink and drive over the
New Year holiday period''.
In Strathclyde, police stopped a total of 974 drivers for breath-testing, a
drop of 21%, with 1233 tested in the same period last year.
Snow and ice played a significant part in the decreased number of tests carried
out, with traffic lighter because of road conditions.
Leader comment.........14
</TEXT>
