<DOCNO>GH951228-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Films sell Scotland to the tune of 10m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE power of the movie industry is selling Scotland across the world and
benefiting tourism to the tune of #10m, new figures reveal.
The success of films such as Braveheart and Rob Roy has attracted hundreds of
foreign travel journalists.
The Scottish Tourist Board said stories had appeared in travel magazines and
newspapers around the world and provided Scotland with around #10m worth of
editorial coverage.
More than 573 travel journalists visited Scotland over the summer in a
programme organised by the Scottish Tourist Board.
Now tourist chiefs hope that the next blockbuster out of Scotland, Loch Ness,
starring Ted Danson, which is premiered in Inverness in February, will provide
a similar lift.
Mr Graham Birse, director of public relations for the Scottish Tourist Board,
said: ``The boost to Scottish tourism provided by the recent kilt movies looks
set to continue next year.
``When you have a fairly limited marketing budget, the editorial generated by
these kinds of visits helps reinforce campaigns and, most importantly, has a
strong influence on the armchair traveller.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six months for heroin addict who stole floral tributes and stone angels from cemetery Sentence marks public revulsion</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF yesterday refused to show mercy to a heroin addict who robbed graves
to maintain his habit.
Thomas Cryans, 32, was given a maximum sentence of six months when he admitted
numerous thefts of flowers from six graves in Glasgow's Linn Cemetery over a
four-month period.
Mrs Gillian Mawdsley, prosecuting, told Glasgow Sheriff Court how police found
a cupboard full of artificial flowers in Cryans's home.
She said the value was not as substantial as the distress caused to relatives.
Last night it was revealed that Cryans sold stolen floral tributes and stone
angels at car boot sales and at Paddy's Market in Glasgow.
When he was arrested he told police it was easy money.
But behind him he left a trail of hurt for relatives who found the graves of
their loved ones desecrated.
Yesterday some of the relatives sat in court as defence solicitor Tom Fields
revealed that Cryans, of Ardencraig Road, Castlemilk, was a drug addict trying
to regain his health through treatment.
They shook their heads in anger as the lawyer appealed for him to be placed on
deferred sentence.
As Sheriff Kenneth Maciver pronounced sentence they thanked him for putting the
father of two behind bars.
One woman shouted to the sheriff: ``My wee wean will be at rest now he's off
the streets.''
The victims heard Sheriff Maciver tell Cryans that his crimes were examples of
the depths to which drug addicts stooped.
He said a jail sentence was required to express public revulsion and added:
``These crimes involved stealing items lovingly placed on the graves of the
deceased by relatives, and the effect on the relatives, is understood by not
only you but by the court.''
Outside the court, 27-year-old Mrs Karen Cairns, of Downcraig Road, Castlemilk,
described Cryans as ``scum and the lowest of the low''.
Cryans repeatedly stole flowers from the grave of Mrs Kairns's daughter Ashley,
who died in 1988 aged two.
She said: ``I'm glad he got a jail sentence, but even then six months isn't
long enough.
``I just hope he gets it in prison.
``When he was arrested police were investigating the thefts from 28 graves. He
was charged with 10 and when he finally appeared in court it was whittled down
to six.
``He told the police it was easy money and we heard later that he was selling
them in Paddy's Market.
``With flowers disappeared from Ashley's grave so often I used to sit up at
nights watching for the thief from my window, which overlooks the cemetery.
``I even put a note on a new batch of flowers saying they were put there for my
two-year-old daughter, but the next day the flowers were gone and the note was
all scrunched up at the graveside.
``Even since his arrest I've been checking on Ashley's grave - sometimes two or
three times a day, and I was there last night to make sure her flowers were
there.''
Wheelchair-bound Patricia Hanlon, 25, who was also in court, told how she
identified one of two stone angels stolen from the graveside of her
four-year-old son, Tony.
Ms Hanlon said: ``Cryans was never charged with the theft and we could never
understand why.''
Tony died in 1991 in a fire in his mother's home at Skerryvore Road, Cranhill.
Ms Hanlon, who was paralysed as a result of jumping from the blazing house,
said: ``We could never blank out little Tony's memory, and on his birthday and
at Christmas would buy him presents which were placed on his grave.
``Two stone angels and all his presents and flowers went missing. We were just
devastated.
``The police showed us an angel. It was definitely from Tony's grave because we
have photographs of it.
``We were told someone had bought it from a car boot sale.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>singer's Gambian son-in-law escapes deportation under tightened immigration rules Hogmanay reprieve for visitor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A THREAT to deport the Gambian son-in-law of Scottish folksinger Hamish Imlach
brought a last-minute reprieve by immigration officials yesterday, hours before
he was due to board a flight to Norway.
However, it emerged last night that the airline which allowed the
nursery-school teacher to enter the UK on Boxing Day without a visa is to be
fined several thousand pounds.
Yusupha (Jo) Bojanj arrived in Glasgow on Tuesday night on a SAS/British
Midland flight from Oslo via Copenhagen.
He had come to join his Scottish wife Mairead and three-year-old daughter Sira
who were already in Scotland for a month-long visit to relatives in Dennistoun,
Glasgow. The couple met four years ago and live in the Norwegian capital.
But Mr Bojanj, who has visited Scotland on several occasions, had arrived in
the UK without a visa unaware that British immigration regulations for Gambian
nationals had changed in October.
After being searched he was allowed to leave the airport on Tuesday night but
was instructed to return yesterday at lunchtime, two hours before the first
flight back to Norway.
After a distressing wait in the airport while immigration officials discussed
the case with the family's lawyer, Mr John Guthrie, Mr Bojanj was finally told
he could stay until January 1, the day he had originally planned to return home.
Mrs Bojanj, who is four months pregnant, said she and her husband were
delighted. ``My husband has been allowed to stay on compassionate grounds until
Monday. They seemed to think that Jo was coming here to get a job but that's
ridiculous, he has a job in a nursery.''
An immigration department official said she could not comment on individual
cases but said the Foreign Office had widely advertised the new visa
requirement for Gambian nationals.
``As of October a Gambian national required a visa to enter the UK. This can be
obtained from the British High Commission. If you require a visa you cannot get
round that point.''
She said airlines could also be fined if they failed to check that passengers
had the correct documentation. ``It's up to airlines to abide by UK immigration
law. Under the Carriers Liability Act airlines can be fined.''
Mr Imlach, speaking at home in Motherwell, said he was relieved at the
decision. ``My daughter was hysterical because they had already been unable to
spend Christmas together. But at least they can be together at Hogmanay. It is
really unbelievable. He has a home and a job in Norway and just came for a
holiday.''
Mr Bojanj, clearly distressed by the experience, said he had not been told he
needed a visa by SAS when he bought his ticket.
SAS manager Joergen Bounde, and a spokesman for British Midland which provides
the Glasgow to Copenhagen leg, both would not comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First step to tourist gateway for loch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667872</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BID to the National Millennium Fund, seeking #20m to provide a quality
tourist gateway to Loch Lomond at Balloch, has cleared its first hurdle.
Local MP John McFall, who heads the bid, will start talks with Dunbartonshire
Enterprise next week to flesh out the business plan behind the initiative.
``We are greatly buoyed by the early response from the Millenium Commission,''
he said yesterday.
``The majority of bids are rejected before they get past the initial stage. It
is very encouraging that we have received such a prompt response from the
commission inviting us to go on to the next stage which is submitting the
formal specification.''
He said the aim was to create something which would raise the tone of the whole
of the bottom end of Loch Lomond, and he was confident the Millennium
Commission looked upon it as an internationally important project.
The proposal would centre on Drumkinnon Bay.
It would include an exhibition and visitor centre with an open window on to the
loch concentrating on informing visitors about the loch environment; a visitor
management scheme linking this centre by foot and cycle bridge across the Leven
to Balloch Country Park; the restoration of the Maid of the Loch paddle
steamer; the restoration of the banks of Drumkinnon Bay; and a new planting and
conservation regime at Drumkinnon Wood.
Mr McFall estimates there could be a spin-off by as much as #42m in public and
private sector investment, and a #100m tourist boost leading to up to 4000 new
jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The race card in Govan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMMY Reid correctly suggests that covert racism is a deep-rooted problem in our
society which is extremely dangerous and difficult to tackle (Greatest dangers
that lurk just below the surface, December 23).
However, he makes a number of statements in relation to the recent Labour Party
selection contest in Govan which could fuel racial division although I am sure
that is not his intention.
He states that of the 52 votes cast which were ruled ineligible the majority
had been cast for Mohammed Sarwar. How could he make this assertion with such
certainty?
As a scrutineer at the count I do not know the identity of the 52 people whose
votes were ruled ineligible, so how does Jimmy Reid know who they are?
Jimmy Reid also states that Mike Watson is a Christian. This is not true. Mr
Watson is an atheist.
Jimmy Reid tells readers that ``all who had approached me on behalf of Mike
Watson . . . were white Christians, comfortably middle-class, university
graduates and with settled careers.''
This may well be the case but I would suggest that what this exposes is the
circles in which Jimmy Reid moves rather than the breadth of support which Mike
Watson had in the selection.
As his campaign manager I can assure Jimmy Reid that support was forthcoming
from bus drivers, shop workers, factory workers, building workers, shipyard
workers, unemployed workers, young people, not so young people, men, women, and
some Asian Scots too.
Jimmy Reid concludes by stating that part of his reaction to the selection in
Govan was one of shame. I too felt a deep sense of shame - shamed by those,
both Asian and white, who chose to play the race card in order to have the
result overturned.
This is a very dangerous tactic to use and I am very pleased that Mr Sarwar and
many of his colleagues have refrained from joining those involved. Jimmy Reid,
however unwittingly, has simply added fuel to the fire.
Archie Graham,
5 Mansion House Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
