<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pressure on Granada to up offer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business comment </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORTE has tossed the ball back into Granada's court with its proposed #1050m
sale of its restaurant activities to Whitbread. Together with a forthcoming
revaluation of the hotels it will put pressure on Granada to raise its offer.
Granada will of course be able to attack both events. The price obtained from
Whitbread is not generous - how could it be when the vendor is in a desperate
battle to save its independence? And hotel values are notoriously difficult to
fix.
Reports suggest the hotels will be valued at over #3000m which would imply that
Granada's #3300m bid falls some #700m short. The hotels market is certainly
more active than it was during the days of Queens Moat when, if the valuations
were to be believed, its hotels almost halved in value in a matter of months.
So it should be possible to fix a value on lower and mid-market hotels with
reasonable accuracy, but it is particularly difficult to value ``trophy''
hotels when so few change hands. They make low returns but may well appeal as
billionaires' baubles.
Valuations can also be a two-edged sword as a high figure draws attention to
return on assets, which Granada will no doubt be keen to exploit. The group has
already fiercely criticised the plan to split Forte in two and there must
surely be something in what it says, namely that some economies of scale will
be lost.
Nevertheless, Granada's bid value has been weakened by the fall in its share
price and Forte's defence has been strong enough to make it look on the low
side. A modest increase in the terms - if Granada can afford it - will probably
be necessary for victory.
New age at GEC
LORD Weinstock's 32-year tenure at the helm of General Electric Company is
expected to come to an end this spring, at which time the company has announced
it will be naming a successor as managing director.
His achievement in building up the group into the powerhouse it now is,
straddling defence, power plant and telecommunications as well as more
peripheral activities, cannot be underestimated.
For a number of years, though, GEC appeared to have run out of steam and was
the subject of criticism, mostly centred on its enormous cash mountain. There
was the feeling that the group ought to be doing something with it, rather than
just sitting back and earning interest.
Lord Weinstock would no doubt argue that his more expansionist plans would be
turned down by the authorities. The recent successful acquisition of submarine
builder VSEL certainly spurred the share price which yesterday rose 8p to a new
high for the year, indeed of two years, of 351p. It compares with a low for the
year of 268p but GEC, anyway, has its attractions as an income stock.
Resolution of the somewhat controversial management succession issue would be
regarded as a major plus for the company, removing uncertainty. Chairman Lord
Prior is drawing up a short-list of potential candidates, including both
internal and external candidates.
GEC has already stated that that no announcement can be expected until the
spring. Analysts would expect a new broom to dispose of those group activities,
such as semiconductors, washing machines and cables, not covered by the three
core activities.
This would add to the already significant cash pile and increase the scope for
further expansion in its chosen fields. In the meantime, group orders remain
strong with potential fresh defence orders in the pipeline. The shares still
look attractive.
Welcome act
INCREASES made to pensions-in-payment from major occupational pension schemes
averaged 3.1% in 1995, according to Incomes Data Services which specialises on
employment issues.
The actual range was from zero to 5% which means that while many schemes made
sure their pensioners did not see the value of their pension eroded, or at
least provided some protection, there were still a few companies which do not
appear too much concerned about the plight of their pensioners.
However, in addition to general increases, some pension schemes did award
special ``catching up'' rises to older pensioners to help restore the
purchasing power of their pensions.
At present, company pension schemes are not obliged to increase pensions to
compensate for the effects of inflation though under the new Pensions Act,
limited price indexation safeguards will start to accrue from April 1997.
But IDS says that virtually no schemes outside the public sector guarantee full
inflation-proofing, the great majority of the company pension schemes analysed,
and which covered 70 ``blue chip'' schemes, guaranteed some increase, often
matching inflation up to 5% each year.
When Limited Price Indexation for pensions-in-payment comes into force,
companies will have to decide how to implement this. For example, they will
have to decide whether they will provide guaranteed increases, in line with
statutory requirements, or continue to apply a higher upper limit as is
currently the case with some schemes.
Either way, the Pensions Act is something to be welcomed. At age 60, the
average male in the UK can expect to live a further 16.4 years and the average
female, a further 20.9 years.
So even with a fairly low rate of yearly RPI increase, the considerable length
of time which a pension may be payable means that a fixed rate pension retains
little of its original purchasing power. Poverty is not funny, even less so in
old age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
