<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Missing the target on guns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article, Shotgun permits exceed 100,000 (December 27), made a number of
interesting points. The British Association for Shooting and Conservation is
obviously delighted that recent figures indicate a rise in the number of
certificates on issue for both shotguns and firearms in Scotland.
This follows a number of years of decline, primarly due to the ill-conceived
and un-necessary Firearms (Amendment) Act of 1988.
This period of decline in the number of people legitimately owning shotguns or
firearms coincided with the ongoing increase in the use of guns in crime.
Therefore, for Mr McFall to argue that the legitimate ownership of shotguns and
firearms is in any way linked to armed crime is ridiculous.
The lowest levels of armed crime in this country coincided with the highest
levels of legitimate firearms ownership. Numerous independent studies have
failed to establish any link between legitimate firearms ownership and armed
crime.
If Mr McFall is genuinely interested in reducing armed crime in Scotland, he
should look to the criminals rather than the law-abiding. Amendments to the
existing firearms legislation will only prove to be an inconvenience to
legitimate firearm and shotgun owners and a further bureaucratic burden to our
hard-pressed police.
Dr Colin B Shedden,
Director Scottish Operations,
British Association for Shooting and Conservation, Trochry, Dunkeld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
