<DOCNO>GH951228-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Green lights For culture, read horticulture</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667878</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE millennium looms. With a little help from the lottery, all Britain is
preparing to celebrate the event with a series of prestigious projects for the
lasting benefit of the country. Which worthy candidates for millennial money
benefit and which do not is a lottery in itself, with the inscrutable
Millennium Commission in charge of the show. The #20m bid to provide a tourist
gateway to Loch Lomond has had an optimistic clearance of the first hurdle. The
most recent losing candidate, however, was Welsh National Opera, knocked back
in its campaign for a spectacular new home. For culture should we now read
horticulture? There is a distinctly green-fingered look about the last round of
favoured schemes, including a national wildflower centre on Merseyside, the
improvement of the famous Slimbridge wildfowl and wetlands site associated with
the name of Peter Scott, and the conservation of unique limestone cliffs in the
North-east of England. Green is good, according to the commissioners, who are
no doubt aware that wildlife and conservation projects are likely to be less
controversial issues in the media than the arts.
One of the Scottish initiatives already given preliminary backing is the
so-called Millennium Forest. So far only a relatively small sum has been
allocated to lay the groundwork for the project, but this implies a recognition
of the vision and a willingness to contribute further instalments as it begins
to take shape. The idea of restoring, at least to some extent, the old
Caledonian forest - which once covered much of Scotland but which latterly
faced extinction - has gained much popular support. One aspect of this is a
move among several communities to establish local woodlands for amenity,
pleasure, and recreation. In some cases the creation of employment in forestry
and woodcrafts forms part of the aim. It is a welcome sign. Government
agencies, conservation and wildlife bodies, local authorities, and a large
number of enthusiasts have expressed support. But there is no such thing as
instant woodland. In the life of a forest, four years is barely a start. Giving
back Scotland its native forest is a seductive ideal but it will not happen
today or tomorrow. It will take decades, even centuries, for the green mantle
to spread. That, surely, is the essence of a millennial project. It may be slow
to grow, but it will endure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Caught in the middle of a conflict of identities</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME WOOLASTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>open forum</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974667879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN I heard Scotland had been drawn against England in next summer's European
Championships, I groaned, realising that the news would be like a blood
transfusion to one of the worst cliches in the language. And sure enough, there
it was in the headlines the next morning - even in The Herald: ``The Auld
Enemy''.
There was an episode of The Golden Girls when Blanche, exasperated by
Southerners dedicated to nostalgia for the Confederacy, snapped at them: ``You
lost the war - get over it.'' Faced with talk of the ``auld enemy'' I'm tempted
to parody her: ``You lost your independence - get over it.'' My problem is that
only half of me can use that word ``you'' while the other half takes great
offence. For while, as my surname makes apparent, on my father's side I'm
English, on my mother's side I'm Scots. I was born in England but grew up in
Scotland; I've spent much of my adult life in England, but now I live in
Scotland. Again if obliged to define my ethnic group, I have to say ``English
Scot''.
Now there's a phrase you don't often come across. It's so unusual it sounds
like a self contradiction. How can anyone be both English and Scottish? Yet
parallel descriptions don't seem at all odd, Italian Scot, Irish Scot, Jewish
Scot, all express recognised identities. No-one would feel obliged to apologise
for using them, or to explain what the phrase meant.
But English Scots are, in fact, the largest non-native minority in Scotland.
The last census showed that 350,000 residents of Scotland were born in England
- 7%, or one in 14, of the population. The only reason we don't actually appear
to be the largest minority is because of the tendency of Scots of Irish descent
to go on celebrating their Irish identity several generations after their
families migrated.
So here we are, well entrenched in Scottish life, many of us having ``gone
native'' in a big way, and then opening our papers to see ``auld enemy''
splashed all over them, and preparations being made to fight the battle of
Bannockburn for the umpteenth time. Before that fixture is played on June 15
next year I fear that a tidal wave of such nonsense will sweep through all the
Scottish media. Most of it will be harmless enough but if England should be
instrumental in putting Scotland out of the championships, the ugly side of
Scottish Anglophobia will undoubtedly surface.
Of course you hardly need a degree in political science to work out why the
phrase ``English Scot'' sounds peculiar. It's a matter of political reality
that England dominates Scotland to an outrageous extent, so much so that to the
outside world it seems to incorporate Scotland; it's an impossible battle to
get foreigners to stop using ``England'' when they mean Britain. The root cause
is that the population of England is nine times greater than that of Scotland.
The Union beween two parties so unequal in size is always going to be
one-sided. I have never found any concept among the English that the Scots are
an ``enemy'', but at the same time they can't help feeling that the United
Kingdom consists, by and large, of themselves plus some hangers-on.
Given this cultural background there is inevitably some tension in the
``English Scottish'' identity. Sooner or later you have to make some kind of
choice. Since the relationship between England and Scotland hinges on the fact
that one is a powerful country and the other isn't, you can't consistently
identify with both. After all, not even the most skilled madam in a brothel can
be both dominatrix and submissive simultaneously.
And as is well known, this political reality impinges on the role of English
people in Scotland. To some extent they are inevitably seen as representatives
of the larger country, enjoying a privileged position reflecting that of
England in the Union. A few years ago there was a nasty attempt to stir up
hysteria about ``the Englishing of Scotland'', and though it got nowhere it
none the less expressed an underlying anxiety. The opposite side of this
particular coin is that in some economic sectors English people make an
enormous contribution to Scottish life. For example, much of Glasgow's cultural
infrastructure would collapse tomorrow if all the English involved took the
advice of some graffiti artists and ``went home''.
Those of us who are half-Scots, half-English are caught in the middle of this
conflict of identities. In this article I've used the pronoun ``they'' to refer
equitably to both sides. Yet when I write for English papers I use ``we'' and
``us'' of the Scots without the least hesitation. Certainly, when I lived in
England as an adult I never thought of myself as anything but Scottish, not
only because I'd grown up here (I was three when my family moved north) but
because everyone treated me as such, reacting to my accent. After 16 years I
still had to put up with humorists who thought that to greet me with ``och aye
the noo'' was a devastatingly original gem of wit.
In politics I've become an increasingly convinced Scottish nationalist,
precisely because, as I stated in a previous article in The Herald, I of all
people know just how different Scotland and England are and have no illusions
about how imbalanced the Union is in England's favour. But I have to admit that
to some extent my Englishness contributes to my Scottish nationalism: to change
pronouns yet again, there's a part of me that thinks that once you've got your
independence again, you won't be able to go on moaning about the ``auld enemy''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
