<HEADLINE>Sheep injection warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTOR Dermot O'Brien, head of parasitology at the Veterinary Research
Laboratory in Dublin, has warned sheep farmers of the risk of using only one
injection to treat sheep scab.
Dr O'Brien said that only invermectin was licensed for the control of sheep
scab by injection and it should be administered in two doses - as defined in
the product licence - seven days apart.
Injecting should be a two-man job, he said. ``I have seen hundreds of farmers,
who say they have injected their sheep, who have injected the fleece instead.''
</TEXT>
