<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Younger judges for tougher sentences</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with disbelief the letter from Mr William Scott on prisoners' rights
(December 18). He is one of an army of do-gooders who now prevail in our
society. He uses words like ``deserving utmost care, attention, help'' and
phrases like ``We must not fail Mrs West as we failed Fred West'', and ``We
have a duty to protect her''.
I cannot help wondering what world Mr Scott lives in. It certainly cannot be
the one where a fine decent head teacher is knifed trying to protect one of his
pupils, or the world where a man trying to protect his family and home gets his
head smashed in.
The law in our country is a farce. It is time the old men on the bench retired
and allowed younger judges who are aware of the evil around us to deal out
sentences to fit the crime.
Our concern should be for the victims not the criminals. Criminals have
choices, victims do not. Let's have harsher jails and a return to capital
punishment.
I believe jail should be hell, then perhaps those who prey on small children,
old people, and decent citizens would think twice about spending time there.
If those who push drugs were sentenced to a minimum of 20 years maybe our young
people would grow up in a safer world. Child molesters and murderers should be
executed or spend the rest of their life in jail.
J Carlisle,
28 Butt Avenue,
Helensburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Celtic's title ambitions are put on ice Freeze may work to Rangers' advantage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEARTS manager Jim Jefferies admitted last night that there is little hope of
his side's game against Celtic taking place at Tynecastle on Saturday.
The freeze is something which can surely sabotage Celtic's hopes of ending
Rangers' domination in the premier division but Jefferies has no answer to
offer for his club's problems.
He said: ``We will do everything possible to get the game on but, obviously,
the covers we have to protect the park are not going to be as effective as
undersoil heating.
``We will keep the covers on, but they are only going to help when the
temperature remains above minus four. Once they get into the figures we have
been suffering then there is nothing that we can do.
``I cannot see us getting the game on but we will be trying our best to have it
played.''
Celtic, meanwhile, can only wait and hope as the adverse weather conditions
could wreck their title ambitions.
If Rangers push still further ahead at the weekend then that would be bad
enough.
But if Celtic have to go into next Wednesday's Old Firm clash without Peter
Grant and John Hughes, because of suspension, and without having played a game
for 16 days then the dice would be loaded against them. It is not a scenario
manager Tommy Burns would want, nor should it.
The Scottish League will soon issue guidelines to premier division teams that
undersoil heating is essential. We cannot continue to have some teams
disadvantaged because some clubs have failed to realise that winter does hit
hard in this country.
Meanwhile, Hamilton and Partick Thistle were involved in talks yesterday to
ensure that the first division club's match at Firhill on Saturday will go
ahead.
Although Firhill has undersoil heating Partick's Boxing Day clash with
Hibernian was knocked out because of snow on the pitch.
Hamilton, who are ground-sharing at Firhill this season, are due to meet St
Mirren on Saturday and with recent good results, including Tuesday`s draw at
Dundee United, want the game to go ahead.
Hamilton secretary Scott Struthers said yesterday: ``We have spoken to Partick
officials this morning. The undersoil heating is on and will continue like that
during this cold spell.
``This will help Partick as well for they are at home to Falkirk next Monday
and want to ensure that match takes place.''
Almost all of the rest of the Scottish football card is set to be hit by
another winter white-out. Only matches at Ibrox, Tannadice, Hampden, and
Firhill, who all have undersoil heating, have a chance of going ahead.
A spokesman for Scotland Weather Watch last night confirmed the big freeze will
continue through the weekend.
He said: ``There is only an outside chance of temperatures improving by
Saturday and some areas seeing rain. It is far more likely that it will stay
below freezing, with sleet and snow showers.
``There is also a good chance of strong winds which would cause snowdrifts and
would close a lot of roads.''
This would mean travelling supporters would have difficulty making it to the
grounds, even if their game goes ahead.
Rangers' and Dundee United's fixtures were the only ones to survive the Boxing
Day weather. And once again, the majority of games will be called off this
weekend.
Here are the updated reports on the other premier division matches:
Kilmarnock v Aberdeen - Killie are set to use revolutionary measures in a bid
to save Saturday's match at Rugby Park from the big freeze.
The Ayrshire club are currently in discussion with several firms in an attempt
to lay their hands on protective covers for the pitch. And they are hoping to
have the covers in place, with hot air blowing underneath, to thaw the frozen
surface.
Club secretary Kevin Collins explained: ``We are making every effort to get the
park playable. There is a covering of snow on the pitch, but it's not too bad
and it's possible to push a pitchfork into the surface.
``Contact has been made with a few firms in an attempt to have the pitch
covered. No effort will be spared to save the match.''
Raith Rovers v Partick Thistle - It looks unlikely the pitch will recover in
time. General manager Billy McPhee said: ``At the moment, the pitch is totally
unplayable and it's not looking good.
``The groundstaff are working as hard as they can, but there is only so much
they can do. The referee decided on Saturday the ground was too dangerous in
places and it hasn't changed since then.''
Falkirk v Motherwell - Already looks a certain non-starter. Secretary George
Miller said: ``I would say at this stage there is no chance of the match going
ahead.
``The pitch is covered with snow and frost has made the surface brick hard
underneath. The forecast is for more severe frost and blizzards, so it's not
looking good.''
Rangers v Hibernian - Ibrox hosted the match against Kilmarnock and stood up to
the rigours of the 90 minutes. The pitch is okay for the visit of the Easter
Road outfit.
In the first division, Morton's match with Dunfermline is almost certainly off,
with several inches of snow lying on the Cappielow pitch.
Secretary Jane Rankin said: ``There is hard-packed ice on the park and it
doesn't augur well for Saturday. If the weather forecast is correct, there
isn't a chance of the game going ahead.''
St Johnstone will have a pitch inspection tomorrow, but the club are already
resigned to the fact that the match with Clydebank will be called off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN McFall's approach to becoming the party of law and order makes Michael
Howard's hare-brained schemes appear eminently sensible (December 27).
The assertion that shotguns should be subject to a firearm type controls to
reduce gun crime beggers belief.
If firearm certification reduces crime why did crimes involving handguns leap
by 47% last year, and how will increased controls on shotgun ownership cut
illegal handgun use?
I particularly liked his implication that an increase in the number of legally
owned guns is directly related to the prevalence of gun crime. It would have
been even better with some facts to back it up. Perhaps there are other reasons
for this increase, but let's not have logic intruding on a good political
argument.
The conclusion and proposed action prevent lawful citizens from owning a gun in
case we have a crime committed on us and our stolen guns are used in robberies.
I thought the fundamental principle of law and order was to protect the
innocent and punish the guilty. Even Michael Howard gets that one right now and
again.
I fully support any logical measures to reduce the use of firearms in crime but
let's not McFall down on this one again.
Mr McFall should remember to keep some principles in the rush for power.
Andy Spence,
3 Heugh Street,
Falkirk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joint group considers calls for EC assistance Meat trade group backs BSE controls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish meat industry working party which has been set up to provide a
co-ordinated response to the current BSE scare has reaffirmed its confidence in
the extended measures being taken to control and eradicate the disease.
In recognition of the heavy costs which have been incurred by the industry in
complying with requirements for the removal and disposal of specified bovine
offal (SBO) the working party is again considering an approach to the
Government for assistance in obtaining help from the European Community's
disease eradication veterinary fund.
The joint working party was set up by the Institute of Auctioneers and
Appraisers in Scotland and the Scottish Association of Meat Wholesalers. It was
founded as a means of breaking the impasse over a call from the wholesalers for
a special levy to be imposed on cattle sold at auction, as a contribution
towards the additional costs being met by abattoirs.
All sectors of the industry are represented on the joint body including
producers, renderers and retailers as well as the auctioneers and the meat
wholesalers.
Mr Don Curry, chairman of the Meat and Livestock Commission, has been leading
the working group discussions and has agreed to explore the possibility of
setting up a UK-wide strategy group to harmonise regional and sector policies
and opinions.
Meanwhile Aberdeen-Angus producers have become the first in Scotland to give
buyers a guarantee that all cattle marketed under the Certified Aberdeen-Angus
beef label are from farms registered with the Scotch Quality Beef and Lamb
Association Farm Assurance scheme.
``All farmers involved in the production of beef for our Certified Scheme must
first have achieved the high welfare and husbandry status of SQBLA Farm
Assured,'' said Mr Jim Ironside, managing director of Aberdeen-Angus Producers
(Scotland) Ltd.
``We require 100% commitment from our 500 producers, whether they are pedigreee
breeders or beef finishers,'' he added.
``We are totally confident in our members' ability to manage livestock under
strict welfare conditions. Certified wholesalers and retailers will be expected
to achieve the same degree of excellence in their respective domains.''
Sales of Aberdeen-Angus beef are reported to holding up well during the present
crisis in the meat industry, because of the healthy, quality image of Angus
beef produced in specialist beef herds.
``Consumers have confidence in our product because of the disciplines we impose
to ensure that Certified Aberdeen-Angus beef meets the highest welfare and
management standards,'' said Mr John Jamieson, of Stonehaven, chairman of the
Aberdeen-Angus producers group.
In the past year more than 7000 cattle worth #4.5m had been marketed through
the group, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000106</DOCNO>
