<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police appeal to person shielding Mhairi's murderer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE killer of schoolgirl Mhairi Julyan is almost certainly a local person who
is being shielded by a friend or relative, the officer leading the murder
investigation said yesterday.
Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder was speaking on the eleventh day of the
hunt for Mhairi's killer.
The 16-year-old redhead had been making her way home from the pantomime
Sleeping Beauty at the town's Palace Theatre on Saturday, December 16, when she
disappeared.
Her body was discovered the following afternoon in the Stagecoach bus depot in
McKinlay Place, Kilmarnock. She had been the victim of what police have
described as a ``particularly savage and brutal attack''.
Mr Lauder said yesterday: ``I believe that this is a local crime and that
someone in the Kilmarnock area holds the key to this shocking murder.
``I cannot believe that any person could act normally when the enormity of what
they have done settles upon them and for that reason I repeat my appeal to
local people to consider carefully the behaviour of those close to them in
recent days.
``It may be a change in mood or habit but any little change may be significant
and I would stress that all information will be treated in confidence.''
Mr Lauder conceded that the inquiry was being frustrated by a lack of
information relating to the time between Mhairi's passing of the Jet filling
station in London Road on Saturday night and when her body was found.
He added: ``It may be that she walked on towards her home in Samson Avenue via
the usual route or she took another route or was even taken in a car. We just
don't know and we hope that anyone out there who does will get in touch with us.
``There may be people sitting at home who were in the area and who saw nothing
but I would still ask them to get in touch so that they may be eliminated from
the inquiry.''
Mr Lauder wants four teenage boys aged between 15 and 17 who were seen at the
Jet filling station ``in boisterous mood'' around 9.20pm on December 16 to
contact the incident room.
The four youths were of average height and build and wearing dark clothing. At
the earlier time two were sitting on the wall and two were on the pavement.
In addition the senior detective appealed for two middle-aged men, who may have
been ``bus spotters'' and who were seen in the Stagecoach depot around 11.10am
on December 17, to come forward as they may have information.
Missing piece.............13
</TEXT>
