<DOCNO>GH951228-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The future for Monklands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Nimmo-Smith report on Monklands at last clears the air and should put an
end to this whole absurd affair.
As a Labour Party member, I am pleased with the report's findings but puzzled
by the reaction of some of Labour's so-called Scottish leaders.
Mr George Robertson and Mrs Helen Liddell were less than enthusiastic in their
praise of the council, which was owed a huge apology from them and others.
It was Mr Robertson (soon to be the Secretary of State for Scotland?) who
welcomed the ``thoroughness'' of the now discredited Black report. This then
led to the suspension from holding office of Labour councillors in Monklands
and North Lanarkshire.
The fact that these councillors had massive support from their electorate after
Mrs Liddell had squeezed into a once solid Labour seat did not seem to matter.
In consequence people like me who voted Labour have been denied the full
representation which we had expected.
The message from the Nimmo-Smith report to John Smith House in London, which
they would be extremely foolish to ignore, is that they have already gone too
far. They should have supported the majority in the Labour group instead of
undermining them.
They should drop the hidden threat in Helen Liddell's remarks on this very
important report by restoring with full speed all rights to those who have been
democratically elected.
In addition, they should be grateful that one of the few politicians to have
come out of this period with any credit is Tom Clarke, now happily back in the
Shadow Cabinet.
Mr Clarke was steadfast throughout in his defence of decency and democracy even
in the face of attacks, many anonymous.
Tony Blair would do well to give more weight to his counsel and less to those
like Mr Robertson and Mrs Liddell who have been completely discredited by this
unnecessary saga.
Patrick Docherty,
39 Mitchell Street,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
