<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Moral weakness</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667887</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT a nation of cowards we have become. In former times we would respond to
threats or dangers, like Hitler's blitz, by summoning our resolve and showing
traditional British pluck.
Today half the country are too scared to eat a nice juicy steak because they
are terrified of catching Mad Cow disease. I have nothing but contempt for such
poltroons.
The prospect of one's brain turning to sponge and an agonising death is
certainly appalling and only a simpleton would believe the assurances of the
Government and their scientists (many of them obviously with vested interests
in the meat industry).
But surely, the courageous thing to do is to face the danger squarely and
refuse to be deflected from one's course?
The people of this country must realise that they can't go on running forever.
We must resist the slide into the moral weakness of vegetarianism.
John M M Liddell,
30 Buckingham Terrace,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
