<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opencast firm in contract row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN opencast mining company has begun legal action against the Scottish Coal
Company over a contract drawn up with British Coal when the industry was
privatised.
SB Minerals of Uddingston, Lanarkshire, a subsidiary of Law Holdings, lodged a
summons in the Court of Session on Friday. The company is seeking a #4.2m in
compensation after the final amount of coal mined fell short of that indicated
by British Coal when private companies were invited to bid for the mine.
The company, which employs 300 people, believes Scottish Coal - which is owned
by Mining Scotland - took over all liability from British Coal last year.
Yesterday a spokesman for Law Holdings said when mining finished at the
Piperhill opencast mine in Ayrshire this September only 850,000 tonnes had been
mined instead of the expected 950,000.
``British Coal had put the mine up for tender on the basis that there was
950,000 tonnes of coal on the site. Scottish Coal has refused to agree to
compensation.''
Last night Scottish Coal's company secretary, Mr Martin Reeves, would only
confirm that the action had been lodged with the Court of Session.
</TEXT>
