<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An eye for a sporting chance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>AILEEN LITTLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OF all Scotland's 684 registered opthalmic opticians C Jeffrey Black's Sports
Vision Clinic in Glasgow occupies a unique niche.
Its branch in Hope Street, Glasgow is equipped with state-of-the-art technology
for administering 14 separate eye checks to sportsmen and women.
Established in Shettleston by Oscar Black in 1941, the company is now headed by
the founder's son Colin. There are 15 branches north of the Border, all except
three in the West of Scotland.
Visual fitness is the buzz word in sports optometry, one of the new sports
sciences. Soft contact lenses, the most commonly supplied aid for sports people
because of comfort and good peripheral vision, were prescribed at Hope Street
for 15% of the Scottish Commonwealth Games team; and already a number of
participants in the next Olympics have applied to the Glasgow clinic, one of
only three UK centres for Olympic vision testing.
They are assessed on such skills as contrast sensitivity, colour vision,
alignment, hand/eye/foot reaction times, and visual concentration.
Clients are advised by optometrist Peter Ivins a founding member of the UK
Sports Vision Association. The idea of setting up #35,000 worth of sports
vision equipment in Hope Street was his.
In 1989, Mr Ivins attended a symposium on contact lenses in Lillehammer, little
realising he'd be back there as sports vision consultant for the 1994 Winter
Olympics.
``One of the speakers, an associate professor of optometry at Pacific State
University, gave a half-day lecture on sports vision. It was my first contact
with the subject. We corresponded, I helped him at the Barcelona Olympics, then
I decided we should do something similar in Scotland.''
Coinciding fortuitously with the launch of C Jeffrey Black's #60,000
sponsorship towards assessing the visual fitness of the Scottish Commonwealth
Games squad, the sports vision branch was opened in early 1993.
Elite sportsmen and women are well aware of this provision. Just before
Christmas, Mr Ivins was invited by multi-national visioncare company, Bausch
and Lomb, to screen the English rugby team, and he has advised some English
clay pigeon shooters.
However, sports-loving members of the public come to Hope Street too for
spectacles specifically designed for skiers, orienteers, divers and snooker
players. Custom-made sunglasses are another feature.
Specialist eyeware accounts for some 6-7% of C Jeffrey Black's business with
contact lenses at 15%.
But it is in the realm of sports vision that C Jeffrey Black has established a
unique foothold north of the Border, one which works equally to the advantage
of sport and to the company itself.
The decision to specialise in this fast-growing area made sound commercial
sense. ``We're seen to be at the leading edge of the profession.
``It gives us access to top sports people who, in turn, help us compile
statistics about visual skills,'' said Mr Ivins, whose aim is for the public to
appreciate how even minor visual correction can enhance a sporting performance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
