<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young Celts on Otto pilot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667890</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC have added a new dimension to their burgeoning youth policy by inviting
Ajax coach Heini Otto to help train some of their starlets.
Otto was in Scotland yesterday and assisted the Parkhead managerial team of
Tommy Burns and Billy Stark in coaching youngsters between the ages of eight
and 14.
Otto coaches Louis van Gaal's youthful Ajax team which captured the European
Cup last season, and who have gone 52 Dutch league games without defeat.
Their side includes brilliant striker Patrick Kluivert, who scored the winner
against AC Milan in Vienna and both goals that ended the Republic of Ireland's
hopes of qualifying for the European Championship finals in the Anfield
play-off against Holland a fortnight ago.
Burns, who went to Amsterdam to visit Ajax earlier this year, has already
drafted several promising youngsters into his own first team as well as
producing a conveyor belt of young talent which will, hopefully, work up
through the ranks.
q HIBERNIAN'S undersoil heating yesterday enabled their Premier Reserve League
match against Partick Thistle to go ahead at Easter Road.
The match finished 1-1 with Hibs' manager Alex Miller's two sons both involved.
Graeme scored Hibs' equaliser and Greg missed a penalty. Partick's scorer was
25-year-old Scots-born trialist Steve McMahon, who has been training with
Partick for the last month after playing in China.
q STEVE Campbell, the former Dundee defender, is looking for a club in Scotland
after winning a four-month fight for a free transfer.
The former Dens Park left-back found himself frozen out when Irish club
Coleraine appointed Kenny Shiels as their manager last summer.
The new manager decided to stop flying the club's Scottish players over for
matches - there were six on the books when he took over - and promptly released
every one of them, apart from Campbell.
Steve said last night: ``I had a year of my contract to go and the board didn't
want to free me, even though I had cost them nothing when I first joined them.
They did let me go to Dundalk for three games, but my chance of a permanent
move there folded when Coleraine demanded a fee.
``I haven't been playing anywhere recently, but I have now managed to sort
things out with the board at Coleraine.''
</TEXT>
