<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cold-weather payments The needy deserve a flexible approach</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEENAGER freezes to death by the roadside in the middle of the night. Rivers
ice over. Pipes burst. Points seize. Roads close. Airports shut. Cars won't
start. Power lines sag under the weight of snow and ice, and snap. For days
communities are cut off from heat and light, the very sustenance whose sudden
and utter lack they most keenly feel at a time of sustained, extreme, numbing
cold. Blankets and candles are no answer. The elderly, the infirm, and the
homeless are at great risk. A state of emergency is declared in our most
northerly isles. From Shetland to the Borders record sub-zero temperatures are
logged, reported, talked about, endured. Is there no end to it? Yes, there is,
say the weathermen, but it won't come for a while yet. It will be little
consolation, as we shiver and shudder, to learn that the mercury is not
expected to rise - and with it a sense of relief - until next week. But on the
basis of their recent predictions we can at least trust the weathermen. They
did, after all, give us warning that we were about to be seized by the iciest
of grips.
Is it simplistic, then, to ask if Hydro-Electric, ScotRail, Railtrack, and the
road-maintaining local authorities were caught cold? The Western Isles Labour
MP Calum MacDonald is right to ask if the privatised power company for the
North and Western Isles could have been better prepared for the storms, which
had of course been predicted. There have been too many instances in the past of
manpower - and safety - being compromised by the primacy of privatisation.
Hydro-Electric's customers deserve answers, and at the very least public
confirmation that their needs at such times are paramount. For those linesmen
and other emergency workers who have laboured tirelessly for their fellow
citizens in the most inhospitable of conditions we have nothing but praise. But
as we wait on icy platforms and in slippery traffic jams we seem resigned to
life in the age of bottom-line accounting, when committing cash to dealing
with, and keeping it ready for, extreme weather is not an option.
That does not mean complacency, and in this regard the Government should be
flexible with its cold-weather payments to take account of such extraordinarily
inclement times. The needy deserve it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concentration-camp pioneer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667892</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT pains me to have to disagree with one sentence in an excellent essay,
Greatest dangers that lurk just below the surface (December 23) by Jimmy Reid.
He is historically incorrect when he says ``the British Empire pioneered the
concept of the concentration camp in Southern Africa''.
That dubious privilege belongs to the United States. In the freezing winter of
1863 the celebrated, but truly infamous, Kit Carson, rounded up the entire
Navajo tribe, 9000 strong, massacring all who resisted and destroying their
crops, orchards, livestock, and homes, and marched them 300 miles to Bosque
Redondo, or Fort Sumner, in New Mexico.
All who could not keep up in the snow and the cold were shot.
There they were kept for four years in what General Sherman called ``a howling
desert'', many hundreds more of them dying because of the bad water and food.
No Navajo has ever forgotten that tragic episode in their history: it is their
equivalent of the Clearances.
Andrew Lockhart Walker,
7 Lovers' Loan, Dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SRU are set a fixtures poser</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S regional leagues seem doomed to inconclusion as the result of a
mounting backlog of postponed matches. In a statement issued yesterday from
Murrayfield, Gregor Nicholson, the SRU championship secretary, said: ``In view
of the number of SRU Tennent's regional league fixtures which have been
postponed to date, it will not be possible to conclude the regional leagues
prior to the scheduled date for the third round of the SRU Tennent's 1556 Cup
on February 24.''
The regional leagues were introduced to provide a post-championship competition
for the 32 clubs in the four divisions of the Tennent's Premiership. In order
to give the regional leagues some competitive significance it was decided that
the top four finishers in each of the four groups would gain a bye directly
into the fourth round of the cup while those finishing in the lower four would
be required to come into the competition at an earlier round.
For most top clubs the regional leagues have provided opportunities to look at
second XV players while their star performers have been on duty with district
sides. All the same, there is a detectable feeling that the first division
sides went into the regional leagues with the intention of upholding their
current status.
Cynics, however, have suggested that it might be in the interests of, say, a
club like Watsonians to finish in the bottom four, thus enabling them to enter
the cup in the third round and, in so doing, attract a larger crowd for what
would be a meaningful game.
Now that the regional leagues can no longer determine at what round clubs enter
the cup, the SRU have come up with a solution that maybe should have been
implemented in the first place.
It is thus. The names of the 32 regional league clubs will be put into a hat;
the first 16 drawn will receive byes into the fourth round of the cup; the
remainder go in the hat will join the 16 winners (national league clubs) of the
second round for the third-round draw.
So, what does this all add up to?
What it means is that first division clubs are just as likely as lower-placed
clubs in the Premiership to find themselves in the third round of the cup.
Furthermore, since the third-round draw is unseeded there is a chance that, for
example, Melrose and Stirling could meet.
The possibility of division one clubs playing important cup games could present
personnel problems for the top sides given that international players may be
reluctant, or even contractually prevented, from taking part in cup matches at
the end of February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Search for the missing piece in Mhairi puzzle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kirsty Scott visits the incident room in Kilmarnock where detectives hunting
for the killer of Mhairi Julyan are using traditional techniques with hi-tech
help
IN THIS sterile world of screens and printouts the technology knows Mhairi
Julyan simply and bluntly as N1, but the men and women who work here know her
as the bright 16-year-old whose life was ended brutally and whose killer they
are determined to catch.
There are few visible signs of Mhairi in the incident room set up on the first
floor of the police headquarters in Kilmarnock, but her presence is everywhere;
her name written neatly on a board, a map showing her house and the bus depot
where her body was found, her name and reference number flashing up on every
computer screen, her diary scrutinised and analysed, possible sightings of her
scribbled on written statements, her image and the crime scene photographs in
the minds of all those who move through here.
``You don't forget,'' says Inspector Jim Russell with a grim smile. He is the
man responsible for co-ordinating the incident room and the information which
flows into it, and he has seen few crimes as distressing as this. ``I was in
CID for 17 years, and there's still a pride in locking up the bad guy,'' he
says. ``Everybody is working for the same end. We have a really brutal crime
here and you have to do your best. It means long hours, long travelling, but
it's got to be done. We have to get a result. Everybody knows a young girl's
life was taken, and that's the key.''
The crime scene photographs are not pinned to a wall, but kept in a book which
is shown, along with a video of the scene where Mhairi's body was recovered, to
any new officer joining the team. At the moment there are 60 detectives working
in the field and a further 12 sat at terminals, filing information into Holmes,
the police computer system. Many of them have been drafted in from divisions
across Strathclyde.
The main incident room has been split into two: street-pounding, door-knocking
detectives at one end, and the Holmes section, where Inspector Russell lives,
at the other. ``Lives'' is an apt word. Drafted in from `B' Division in
Partick, he drives for more than an hour to get into the office for 7am, and
there will still be people who have been in for more than an hour before that.
They worked right through Christmas and will be at their desks if need be as we
slip into the New Year.
There is never a moment of peace. If the incident room hotline isn't ringing,
then the printer is churning out screeds of paper or a detective is pulling on
his coat and bolting out of the door. In a large draughty hall down the
corridor which doubles as a briefing room, lists of names, maps and strategies
are pinned along the walls. In a separate small room marked ``Statement
Reader'' one man sits at a desk, eyes diligently criss-crossing the top sheet
of a pile of papers. There is plenty of talk, but precious little laughter.
At his desk in the corner, Jim Russell taps a few keys and Holmes's
bright-green screen flashes into action. ``Murder-Julyan'' it says in the
bottom right-hand corner. Russell calls it a great big filing system, but it is
part of the team and a crucial tool for drawing together the threads and
snippets of information which have flooded in since the news broke about
Mhairi's murder.
``If you look here,'' he says. ``Here's one individual; there were three
sightings on that night.''
He taps a few more keys. ``Say we wanted to look for how many times the word
`mark' comes up, whether for a mark on a face or maybe someone's name.'' A few
seconds later the screen flashes up a list of references. Someone who had a
visible scratch, people called Mark. The police have spoken to 2000 people and
calls are still coming in from the public.
Jim Russell has been amazed by the public response. ``The volume of calls has
been staggering,'' he says. ``We had more than 500 messages initially but the
calls have tailed off a little since Christmas Day. But up until Christmas Eve
the phone didn't stop ringing. It would start at 7am and go on until all hours
of the night. There's a bit of a joke here that there are maybe five people in
Kilmarnock who haven't phoned, and we want to know why.''
The sightings and information phoned in are each turned into a TIE (trace,
interview, eliminate) - task for the detectives, which may produce statements
which are fed into the computer, and so it goes. The police have been able to
eliminate a lot of irrelevant information this way, such as the group of
revellers who got into a fight the night of the killing and who prompted a slew
of calls to the incident room. The system has also brought them promising
nuggets of information like the latest sighting of a young man and a young
girl, who looked like Mhairi, arguing outside a hotel on London Road.
Russell hopes that the calls will keep coming because, he says, it won't be
Holmes that tracks down Mhairi's killer, but it will be that one crucial piece
of information. The one that will make the whole picture fall into place and
take Mhairi's name down off the walls.
``The smallest bit of information can be relevant. You just don't know. All it
may take is for someone to say `Hold on a minute, what was that about'. Just
one wee bit of information could be enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
