<HEADLINE>Reg Stockill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REG Stockill, who played in Arsenal's League Championship winning team of
1932-33, has died after a long illness in York at the age of 82. He was the
only non-internationalist in the Arsenal side which included such famous names
as Eddie Hapgood, Joe Hulme, David Jack, Alex James, and Cliff Bastin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951228-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Robson's choice goes to Rangers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974667897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Rangers attempt to extend their lead in the premier division over closest
rivals Celtic this weekend, they have been boosted by the news that Gremio's
Brazilian striker Jardel will be at Ibrox within a fortnight.
Former England manager Bobby Robson, who is now in charge of Porto in Portugal,
has admitted that Walter Smith has beaten him to land one of Brazil's biggest
current stars.
The other week at Wembley, where England played Portugal, Robson met Smith and
told him: ``You have a winner. I have had my man in Brazil tracking Jardel for
three months and then you turn up and get him.
``We wanted him at Porto. We watched him so often and I tried to get my man to
have him fixed up, then you appeared on the scene and we lost him. He will be a
sensation in Scotland.''
Smith jetted to Brazil to arrange the transfer and now he awaits the arrival of
the striker who has been honeymooning with his beauty queen wife.
Jardel has to fulfil nationality requirements and that appears to be no problem
as far as Brazilian players are concerned. They are granted automatic
Portuguese passports and that has been the situation which has allowed so many
of the top clubs in Portugal to play ``foreign'' players in the European
tournaments.
Jardel will be available to boost Rangers as they push towards an eighth league
title victory. He will allow them another option up front and, according to
Robson, he will fit in superbly to the British game.
The Porto coach said: ``Jardel is the kind of player who will not need any
great time to adapt to the British style. He is someone who will go there and
make an immediate impact.''
Meanwhile, Rangers expect Oleg Salenko to be fit to face Hibs this weekend and
Gordon Durie, while doubtful to face his old club, will be ready for the Old
Firm clash next Wednesday.
Stuart McCall and Ally McCoist both are doubtful for that match.
q LIBERIAN striker George Weah is dedicating his Golden Ball award to the peace
process in his home country. The annual award, organised by the magazine France
Football, is one of the most highly regarded individual accolades in Europe.
AC Milan's Weah receives the honour in the first year it has been open to
non-European players and the 29-year-old striker is hopeful that his success
will serve as an example to his young countrymen.
``I'd like to give them a model for a better future than picking up a gun to
fight your own brothers for power,'' he said.
``I'd like to offer the Golden Ball award to all the rival forces who have been
fighting each other for six years in a war that has destroyed the country.
``This trophy could help to unite the different factions, foster peace, and
promote unity for my people.''
</TEXT>
