<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The plundering of Russia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974667898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR editorial on the Russian elections states that the Government's reforms
are working (December 19). Working for whom, it must be asked.
Gorbachev Fund analyst Viktor Kuvaldin has said that ``over 70% of people have
lost ground and are living worse than a few years ago''.
The result of this can be seen in only one in 10 voting for Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin's Our Home Is Russia party, and a virtual doubling of the
Communist Party's vote compared to 1993.
While the mass of people struggle to make ends meet a small minority of
get-rich-quick merchants have plundered the wealth of the country through
privatisation and other forms of theft and are living in the lap of luxury.
Heavily armed gangsters carve up the cities into their own fiefdoms.
It is not a mass attack of nostalgia that is causing so many Russians to vote
communist but a recognition that the market economy does not work for the
majority.
You may advocate a jog rather than a sprint to market reforms but the result is
the same - misery for the masses. Only socialism provides an answer for them.
Thomas Morrison,
105 Alderman Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
