<DOCNO>GH951228-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951228-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appeal to Shetland farmers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RESPITE from blizzard conditions gave farmers in Shetland an opportunity to
carry out checks on their livestock yesterday. With more bad weather forecast,
however, the Scottish Office is standing by to respond to any requests for help.
The National Farmers' Union of Scotland has said that an appeal had been issued
on the radio for Shetland farmers in difficulty to contact their NFUS
president, Addie Doull. So far, response has been muted.
Mr Doull has been told by members that they were running out of feed and fear
supplies would be finished by the weekend.
``The problem is one of distribution, said Mr Doull. With the roads blocked the
difficulty is getting out to the farms.''
A Scottish office spokeswoman in Edinburgh said that there were emergency plans
for airlifts in such situations however, there had been no request for that
kind of assistance to date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
