<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Food to tempt the yachting crowd</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE latest effort to attract more tourists is to feature snails.
The French delicacy will be among a range of dishes going on show in London to
highlight Scotland's larder and reinforce links between tourism and the food
and drink industry.
It is part of a plan to offer top quality food to visitors at the London Boat
Show as part of a drive by Argyll and the Islands Enterprise to promote the
wealth of fresh produce available from Scotland's west coast.
Top Argyll chefs will be preparing a range dishes utilising local products,
including oysters, venison, scallops, and produce from the country's only snail
farm in Taynuilt.
AIE is staging up to seven cookery demonstrations a day at the 10-day show,
which opens on January 5 and is expected to attract more than 150,000 people.
Recipe cards have also been prepared and will be handed out to visitors to the
AIE stand, titled Argyll and the Islands - A Feast of Nature. As well as the
demonstrations, Loch Fyne Oysters is setting up a full oyster bar to tempt
visitors.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth will be visiting the stand on January 11 and
food writer Henrietta Green will be there to promote her new book, called The
Food Lover's Guide to Britain.
Earlier this year, she was invited by to visit Argyll and the islands and, as a
result, 30 local companies have been featured.
AIE chief executive Ken Abernethy said: ``We were first at the Boat Show in
1993 when our Sail Scotland initiative was unveiled to the public. It was a
tremendous success and we are seeing increasing numbers of people visiting the
area as a result of that and the ongoing efforts of the partners in Sail
Scotland.
``The Boat Show is an ideal opportunity to reach a huge number of potential
visitors and show them exactly why Argyll and the islands is a great place to
come.''
</TEXT>
