<DATE>951228</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots are among Britain's most worried employees</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974667906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than half of British employees expect their jobs will be less secure in
the year ahead, while three quarters expect they will be put under more
pressure at work, according to a Trades Union Congress survey published
yesterday.
For Scots the situation looks even bleaker. They registered figures of 56%
(against 52% for the whole of Britain) and 83% (Britain 74%) respectively.
The TUC says these job worries carry a stark economic and political warning.
Three in four workers say their employment situation makes it less likely they
will think of moving house next year, and almost two-thirds say they are less
likely to make large household purchases or raise their pension payments in
1996.
Commenting on the figures, TUC general secretary John Monks said the survey
showed people's insecurities at work were a serious brake on economic growth,
and were restraining the recovery in consumer spending and the return of any
real feel-good factor.
``If people lack confidence in the future of their jobs they will hesitate
about taking on major spending commitments,'' Mr Monks said. ``During the year
ahead this will increasingly damage the Government's economic strategy and
their political prospects.''
There was a political price to pay and the Government had exacerbated the
situation by removing many of the basic protections for people at work, Mr
Monks said. Giving employers a free hand had done little to improve economic
prosperity but had adversely affected much of middle Britain.
Job insecurity now affected the nation's core workforce, with the survey
revealing the highest levels of concern among professional and white-collar
workers and those in the prime of their working lives. Employees were most
worried in London, the West Midlands, and Scotland.
``Concerns about greater security and fairer treatment at work are set to
become a defining political difference in the year ahead, both within the
Conservative Party and between the Tories and Labour,'' he said.
</TEXT>
